ea, although it has recently began using the corporate \"More Music, More Variety\" slogan on air.\n\nClear Channel Communications became [[iHeartMedia]] in 2014. Through all of the changes that have occurred since becoming a hot AC station, the one constant at KMYI had taken place during the final weeks of the year: Up until 2014, KMYI had an annual tradition of playing all Christmas music, returning to its regular Hot AC format on December 26. This ended in 2015 to focus on [[New Year's Eve]] music content instead.\n\nToday, KMYI's chief rivals are KYXY, which has moved closer to a Hot AC format to gain younger listeners, and [[KXSN]], which broadcasts a [[Classic Hits]] format and calls itself ''Sunny 98.1'', Competition for this station is established by playing [[1990s in music|songs from the 1990s]] at the bottom of each hour.\n\n==Morning shows==\nKMYI has had many morning shows throughout the years:\n\nWhen the station first flipped to Hot AC in 2001, KMYI recruited Jagger and Kristi, their tenure lasted until summer 2005, when they would move to [[XHRM-FM|XHRM]].\n\nOn rebranding to \"Star 94.1\" in 2005, KMYI picked up the ''Jeff and Jer Showgram''. 2005 also saw the addition of notable personality Delana, who originally came in to co-host with Jeff and Jer.\n\nOn August 20, 2009, Jeff and Jer exited Star 94.1 to be replaced by AJ Machado from sister [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40]] station [[KHTS-FM]]. On August 31, 2009, \"AJ in the Morning\" debuted on Star 94.1 with most of the former \"Playhouse\" cast, with the exception of Geena The Latina, who remains at KHTS-FM.\n\nIn June 2012, the morning show was replaced with Jesse Lozano, who re-located to San Diego to host mornings on KMYI. Jesse also voicetracks in afternoons on [[KIIS-FM]] in [[Los Angeles]], and is also known as Boy Toy Jesse. \n\nOn August 16, 2019, it was announced that KMYI will welcome Tati (coming from [[KSSX]]), as their new morning co-host.<ref>{{cite news|last=Venta|first=Lance|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/179720/tati-moves-to-kmyi-mornings/|title=Tati Moves To KMYI Mornings|website=Radio Insight|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref> The newly rebranded \"Jesse and Tati\" program debuted on August 26. This change comes as outgoing co-host Delana announced her move to the afternoon drive spot, in addition to her role on iHeart's [[Pride Radio]] network.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://star941fm.iheart.com/ Star 94.1 website]\n{{FM station data|KMYI}}\n*{{FCC letter|letterid=71772|hcards=yes|callsign=KMYI}}\n*[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=58821&Callsign=KMYI Callsign History]\n\n{{San Diego Radio}}\n{{iHeartMedia}}\n\n[[Category:Adult top 40 radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hot adult contemporary radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nationwide Communications]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in San Diego|MYI]]\n[[Category:IHeartMedia radio stations]]\n", "name_user": "Wcquidditch", "label": "safe", "comment": "KFMB-FM has changed its call sign to KFBG, but for archival purposes the link will continue to say KFMB-FM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KMYI"}
{"title_page": "Vjetrenica Cave", "text_new": "{{Infobox cave\n| name = Vjetrenica Cave\n| alt_name =  Wind Cave, Blowhole Cave\n| photo = Vjetrenica Cave.JPG\n| photo_width = 250 \n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption =  Cave entrance\n| map = Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| relief = yes\n| map_width = 350\n| map_alt = Vjetrenica Cave\n| map_caption =  Location in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| label = Vjetrenica\n| label_position = top\n| mark = Cave symbol.svg\n| mark_width = 15\n| location =  [[Ravno, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Ravno]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| coords = {{coord|42.845900|17.983806|display=inline,title|region:BA_type:landmark_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| depth = \n| length = 7,014 metres\n| height_variation = \n| elevation = \n| discovery = \n| geology = [[Karst cave]]\n| entrance_count = \n| entrance_list = \n| difficulty = \n| hazards = \n| access = \n| show_cave = yes\n| show_cave_length = \n| lighting = \n| visitors = \n| features = \n| translation = Windy cave or blowhole\n| language = [[Serbo-Croatian]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-sh|\u028bj\u025btr\u025b\u030cnitsa|pron}}\n| survey = \n| website = www.centarzakrs.ba\n| embedded = \n}}\n'''Vjetrenica Cave''' ({{IPA-sh|\u028bj\u025btr\u025b\u030cnitsa|pron}}, which means \"wind cave\" or \"blowhole\") is the largest and most important [[cave]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It is also one of the most important caves in the [[Dinaric Alps]] mountain range, which is famous worldwide for its [[karstic]] and [[speleogenesis|speleological riches]]. It is located in the [[Popovo field]] in [[Ravno]], [[East Herzegovina]] in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Popovo Polje.JPG|left|thumb|Popovo Polje, [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].]]\n\n===Popovo Polje and cave location===\n\nVjetrenica is located in [[Popovo Polje]] (pronounced {{IPA-sh|p\u0254\u030cp\u0254\u028b\u0254 p\u0254\u0302\u028e\u025b|}}, meaning ''priest's field'', where [[polje]] stands for [[karstic]] plain), which is itself located in a southernmost regions of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[West Herzegovina]], near the [[Adriatic]] coast. \nIts entrance is near the [[village]] of [[Zavala, Bosnia-Herzegovina|Zavala]], in west - south-western corner of polje. In the warmer parts of the year a strong blast of cold air blows from its entrance, which is very attractive in the middle of the rocky, hot and waterless terrain.\n\nPopovo Polje is one of the largest polje (karstic plain) in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and the world, famous for its [[karstic]] phenomenons and features, and particularly for its [[Trebi\u0161njica River]], which flows through the polje as largest [[sinking river]] (also ''losing stream'', or ''influent stream'') the world, as well as the Vjetrenica cave system, located to the west/south-western parts of the valley. \n\nThe cave has been explored and described to a total of 7,014 m in length; of this the main channel is about 2.47&nbsp;km long. It runs from the edge of [[Popovo Polje]] to the south, and on the basis of analysis of the terrain, [[geologist]]s have predicted that Vjetrenica could stretch right to the [[Adriatic Sea]] in the [[Republic of Croatia]], 15\u201320&nbsp;km away from its entrance. Along with the [[hydrological]] arguments, this assumption is also supported by the \"unnatural\" end of Vjetrenica in the form of a huge heap of stone blocks that have caved in.\n\nVjetrenica is the richest cave in the world in terms of subterranean biodiversity: among more than two hundred different species are registered in it, almost hundred are [[troglophile]]s, a great number of them are narrow endemic, 15 are stenoendemic, and about 37 were discovered and described in Vjetrenica for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Natural and architectural assemble==\n\n===Zavala Village===\nLocated in Popovo Polje in [[Ravno]] municipality, village [[Zavala, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Zavala]] with its old architecture and stone masonry, together with Vjetrenica cave, constitute the natural and architectural ensemble, which is in the process of being protected as ''National Monument of Bosnia and Herzegovina'', and as such it is already placed on [[List of World Heritage Sites in Bosnia and Herzegovina|UNESCO Tentative List]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zavala graditeljska cjelina|url=http://kons.gov.ba/main.php?mod=spomenici&extra=Odluke&action=view&lang=1&id=1820|publisher=Commission to preserve national monuments|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pe\u0107ina Vjetrenica u Zavali|url=http://kons.gov.ba/main.php?mod=spomenici&extra=Peticije&action=view&lang=1&id=3484|publisher=Commission to preserve national monuments|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nVjetrenica cave is considered to have richest cave fauna, with highest rate of endemism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \nVjetrenica cave also acquired fame throughout the world geological and biological scientific communities, as well as environmental communities around the country and the world for its imperiled and uncertain future, caused by unprofessional management lacking any expertise, and uncertain status at state and especially local level.\n\n[[File:Inside Vjetrenica cave.JPG|thumb|Inside Vjetrenica cave]]\n\n===UNESCO nomination===\nDespite all setbacks government of Bosnia and Herzegovina, although creepingly slowly, nominated [[List of World Heritage Sites in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vjeternica (with village Zavala) to UNESCO Tentative List]] clearly expressing intention to protect the cave and its biodiversity and eventually inscribe it with UNESCO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica Cave (Tentative List)|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1975/|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of caves in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n* [[Livanjsko field]]\n* [[Trebi\u0161njica]]\n* [[Saint Basil of Ostrog]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.vjetrenica.ba/\n\n{{Caves in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Navbox prehistoric caves}}\n\n\n[[Category:Geology of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Caves of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Karst caves of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Blowholes]]\n[[Category:Show caves]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List for Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:National Monuments of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Popovo Polje]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cave\n| name = Vjetrenica Cave\n| alt_name =  Wind Cave, Blowhole Cave\n| photo = Vjetrenica Cave.JPG\n| photo_width = 250 \n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption =  Cave carvings in Badanj Cave\n| map = Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| relief = yes\n| map_width = 350\n| map_alt = Vjetrenica Cave\n| map_caption =  Location in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| label = Vjetrenica\n| label_position = top\n| mark = Cave symbol.svg\n| mark_width = 15\n| location =  [[Ravno, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Ravno]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| coords = {{coord|42.845900|17.983806|display=inline,title|region:BA_type:landmark_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n| depth = \n| length = 7,014 metres\n| height_variation = \n| elevation = \n| discovery = \n| geology = [[Karst cave]]\n| entrance_count = \n| entrance_list = \n| difficulty = \n| hazards = \n| access = \n| show_cave = yes\n| show_cave_length = \n| lighting = \n| visitors = \n| features = \n| translation = Windy cave or blowhole\n| language = [[Serbo-Croatian]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-sh|\u028bj\u025btr\u025b\u030cnitsa|pron}}\n| survey = \n| website = www.centarzakrs.ba\n| embedded = \n}}\n'''Vjetrenica Cave''' ({{IPA-sh|\u028bj\u025btr\u025b\u030cnitsa|pron}}, which means \"wind cave\" or \"blowhole\") is the largest and most important [[cave]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It is also one of the most important caves in the [[Dinaric Alps]] mountain range, which is famous worldwide for its [[karstic]] and [[speleogenesis|speleological riches]]. It is located in the [[Popovo field]] in [[Ravno]], [[East Herzegovina]] in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Popovo Polje.JPG|left|thumb|Popovo Polje, [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].]]\n\n===Popovo Polje and cave location===\n\nVjetrenica is located in [[Popovo Polje]] (pronounced {{IPA-sh|p\u0254\u030cp\u0254\u028b\u0254 p\u0254\u0302\u028e\u025b|}}, meaning ''priest's field'', where [[polje]] stands for [[karstic]] plain), which is itself located in a southernmost regions of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[West Herzegovina]], near the [[Adriatic]] coast. \nIts entrance is near the [[village]] of [[Zavala, Bosnia-Herzegovina|Zavala]], in west - south-western corner of polje. In the warmer parts of the year a strong blast of cold air blows from its entrance, which is very attractive in the middle of the rocky, hot and waterless terrain.\n\nPopovo Polje is one of the largest polje (karstic plain) in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and the world, famous for its [[karstic]] phenomenons and features, and particularly for its [[Trebi\u0161njica River]], which flows through the polje as largest [[sinking river]] (also ''losing stream'', or ''influent stream'') the world, as well as the Vjetrenica cave system, located to the west/south-western parts of the valley. \n\nThe cave has been explored and described to a total of 7,014 m in length; of this the main channel is about 2.47&nbsp;km long. It runs from the edge of [[Popovo Polje]] to the south, and on the basis of analysis of the terrain, [[geologist]]s have predicted that Vjetrenica could stretch right to the [[Adriatic Sea]] in the [[Republic of Croatia]], 15\u201320&nbsp;km away from its entrance. Along with the [[hydrological]] arguments, this assumption is also supported by the \"unnatural\" end of Vjetrenica in the form of a huge heap of stone blocks that have caved in.\n\nVjetrenica is the richest cave in the world in terms of subterranean biodiversity: among more than two hundred different species are registered in it, almost hundred are [[troglophile]]s, a great number of them are narrow endemic, 15 are stenoendemic, and about 37 were discovered and described in Vjetrenica for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Natural and architectural assemble==\n\n===Zavala Village===\nLocated in Popovo Polje in [[Ravno]] municipality, village [[Zavala, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Zavala]] with its old architecture and stone masonry, together with Vjetrenica cave, constitute the natural and architectural ensemble, which is in the process of being protected as ''National Monument of Bosnia and Herzegovina'', and as such it is already placed on [[List of World Heritage Sites in Bosnia and Herzegovina|UNESCO Tentative List]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zavala graditeljska cjelina|url=http://kons.gov.ba/main.php?mod=spomenici&extra=Odluke&action=view&lang=1&id=1820|publisher=Commission to preserve national monuments|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pe\u0107ina Vjetrenica u Zavali|url=http://kons.gov.ba/main.php?mod=spomenici&extra=Peticije&action=view&lang=1&id=3484|publisher=Commission to preserve national monuments|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nVjetrenica cave is considered to have richest cave fauna, with highest rate of endemism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  \nVjetrenica cave also acquired fame throughout the world geological and biological scientific communities, as well as environmental communities around the country and the world for its imperiled and uncertain future, caused by unprofessional management lacking any expertise, and uncertain status at state and especially local level.\n\n[[File:Inside Vjetrenica cave.JPG|thumb|Inside Vjetrenica cave]]\n\n===UNESCO nomination===\nDespite all setbacks government of Bosnia and Herzegovina, although creepingly slowly, nominated [[List of World Heritage Sites in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Vjeternica (with village Zavala) to UNESCO Tentative List]] clearly expressing intention to protect the cave and its biodiversity and eventually inscribe it with UNESCO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica Cave (Tentative List)|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1975/|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vjetrenica (official page)|url=http://www.vjetrenica.com/|publisher=vjetrenica.com/|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710194225/http://www.vjetrenica.com/|archive-date=10 July 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of caves in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n* [[Livanjsko field]]\n* [[Trebi\u0161njica]]\n* [[Saint Basil of Ostrog]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.vjetrenica.ba/\n\n{{Caves in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Navbox prehistoric caves}}\n\n\n[[Category:Geology of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Caves of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Karst caves of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Blowholes]]\n[[Category:Show caves]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List for Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:National Monuments of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Popovo Polje]]\n", "name_user": "Santasa99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:caption fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vjetrenica_Cave"}
{"title_page": "Theresa Caputo", "text_new": "{{short description|American television personality and medium}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Theresa Caputo\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1966|06|10}} or {{birth date and age|1967|06|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hicksville, New York|Hicksville]], [[New York (state)|New York]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| other_names        = ''Long Island Medium''\n| occupation         = Television personality\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Larry Caputo|1989|2018|end=divorced}}\n| known for          = [[Long Island Medium]]\n| children           = 2\n| parents            = Nicholas Brigandi (father)\n             Veronica Brigandi (mother)\n}}\n'''Theresa Caputo''' (born June 10, 1966<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-reveals-the-most-shocking-reading-shes-done/|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Reveals One of the Most Shocking Readings She's Ever Done|first=Natalie |last=Stone |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=September 27, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jodi|last=Guglielmi|work=People|date=October 2, 2018|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Sits Down with Ex Husband Larry After Split|url=https://people.com/tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-faces-ex-larry-after-split|quote= Theresa, 52...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-caputo-long-island-medium-1.21375360| title=Theresa Caputo meets with estranged husband in 'Long Island Medium' new-season preview | first=Frank|last=Lovece|work=[[Newsday]]|location=Long Island|date=October 2, 2018|quote=...the Hicksville born-and-raised mentalist, 52...}}</ref> or 1967<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/books/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-endured-decades-anxiety-attacks-feared-communicating-with-dead/|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Endured Decades of Anxiety Because She Feared Communicating with the Dead|first=Liz|work=People |last=McNeil |date=March 17, 2017|accessdate= November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 49}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-at-home-in-hicksville-1.9717137|title='Long Island Medium' Theresa Caputo, at home in Hicksville|first=Jim|last=Merritt|work=[[Newsday]] |location=[[New York City]] / [[Long Island]]| date=December 15, 2014|accessdate=November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 47}} {{subscription}}</ref><ref>Caputo gives birth date as June 10, 1967: {{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BVLH7lEgLCw/|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified [[Instagram]] page|date=June 10, 2017|accessdate=November 14, 2017|title=50 and feeling fabulous!...#birthdaygirl}}</ref>) is an American medium best known for her [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] [[reality television|reality]] TV series, ''[[Long Island Medium]]''.<ref name=People-StarsSeason7-2015>{{cite news|last1=Agard|first1=Chancellor|title=The Long Island Medium Dishes on Seeing Famous Ghosts|url=http://www.people.com/article/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo|accessdate=3 January 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=SiouxCityJournal-2014>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Bruce R.|title=Medium Theresa Caputo finds plenty of interest in her ability to speak with the dead|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/television/medium-theresa-caputo-finds-plenty-of-interest-in-her-abililty/article_53798adf-851f-5c34-9e6a-bb34fab5c545.html|accessdate=4 January 2016|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCaputo was born and raised in [[Hicksville, New York]], on [[Long Island]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/TheresaCaputoLongIslandMedium/about/|title=Biography|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified [[Facebook]] page|first=Theresa|last=Caputo|quote=I was born and raised on Long Island in Hicksville, NY.|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref> the daughter of Nicholas and Veronica Brigandi.<ref name=officialbio>{{cite web|url= https://www.theresacaputo.com/about-me/|title=About Me| publisher=Theresa Caputo official website|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=My parents Nick and Ronnie...and my brother Michael...}}</ref><ref name=life&style>{{cite news|url= https://www.lifeandstylemag.com/posts/theresa-caputo-mom-and-dad-159097/|title=Theresa Caputo's Mom and Dad Are Also Sad About Her Split From Her Husband Larry|first=Emma|last= Hernandez|work=[[Life & Style]]|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=Theresa's father Nicholas is 77 years old and is from Hicksville, NY which is where he raised Theresa and her brother Michael with his wife, Veronica.}}</ref> She has a brother, Michael.<ref name=officialbio /> Their father was a volunteer firefighter and worked for the Nassau County Department of Public Works until 1980, when he was elected county water commissioner.<ref name=kiwanis>{{cite web|url=http://www.hicksvillekiwanis.org/index.php?page=fmnickb|title=Nicholas J. Brigandi - Spirit of Giving Award|publisher= [[Kiwanis Club]] of Hicksville|date=October 2012|accessdate=February 27, 2019| archivedate= June 23, 2016|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160623223044/http://www.hicksvillekiwanis.org/index.php?page=fmnickb |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nCaputo has been on the [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] [[reality television|reality]] TV series, ''[[Long Island Medium]]'' since 2011.<ref name=HuffPo-Feature-2015>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Michael|title=\"Long Island Medium\" Theresa Caputo -- \"You Can't Put A Price On What I Am Able To Give People\"|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-cook/long-island-medium-theres_b_8851248.html|accessdate=3 January 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> She is also the author of two books and tours under \"Theresa Caputo Live! The Experience\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keeperman|first1=Brittany|title=Spirited energy: 'Long Island Medium' Theresa Caputo to appear at the Convo|url=http://www.daily-chronicle.com/2016/04/06/spirited-energy-long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-to-appear-at-the-convo/ah878du/|website=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nSeveral people have accused her of being a fraud, ranging from television news programs such as ''[[Inside Edition]]''<ref name=\"insideedition\">{{cite news|title=The Long Island Medium&nbsp;\u2013 Can She Really Communicate with the Dead?|url=http://www.insideedition.com/investigative/5331-the-long-island-medium-can-she-really-communicate-with-the-dead|accessdate=May 21, 2013|work=[[Inside Edition]]|date=August 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=jezebel-dodai>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Dodai|title=Super Sad and Misguided Emails Intended for the Long Island Medium|url=http://jezebel.com/5953012/super-sad-and-misguided-emails-intended-for-the-long-island-medium|accessdate=May 21, 2013|publisher=[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel.com]]|date=October 20, 2012}}</ref> to print publications such as ''[[Wired Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2012/04/opinion_randilimedium0409/ |title=The 'Medium' is not the messenger |magazine=[[Wired Magazine]] |date=2012-04-09 |accessdate=2013-05-19 |last=Randi |first=James |authorlink=James Randi}}</ref> Caputo was described by [[D. J. Grothe]] as a [[charlatan]],<ref name=\"grothe\">{{cite news |last=Grothe |first=DJ |authorlink=D. J. Grothe |title=Priceline.com: Will you prove your spokesperson worthy for a million dollars?|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dj-grothe/pricelinecom-will-you-pro_b_1773947.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> and [[James Randi]] said her claims were not true.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nIn April 2012, the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] awarded Caputo its [[Pigasus Award]], a tongue-in-cheek award that seeks to expose [[parapsychology|parapsychological]], [[paranormal]] or [[psychic]] frauds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAYG_cgqjWA |title=2012 Pigasus Awards Announcement|work=[[James Randi Educational Foundation]]|date=March 30, 2012|accessdate=March 27, 2014|format=YouTube video}}</ref> The James Randi Education Foundation has been critical of Caputo's work.<ref name=JamesRandi-TallStory-2012>{{cite web|last1=Stollznow|first1=Dr. Karen|authorlink=Karen Stollznow|title=Long Island Medium: A Tall Story|url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/swift-blog/1755-long-island-medium-a-tall-story.html|work=[[James Randi Educational Foundation]]|accessdate=4 January 2016|date=27 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nA newspaper review of Caputo's performances at the [[NYCB Theatre at Westbury]] in late 2017 concluded, \"For me, this unbelievable experience was simply that: not to be believed. In my humble opinion, Caputo is a damn good performer, and she\u2019s got undeniably likable sass and charisma. I just don\u2019t think she speaks with the dead. Or she didn\u2019t the night that I saw her. But my father probably could have told you that.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Franchi|first=Jaime|title=My Not-So-Psychic Experience with Long Island Medium Theresa Caputo|url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2014/12/21/my-not-so-psychic-experience-with-long-island-medium-theresa-caputo/|date=December 7, 2014|journal=Long Island Press}}</ref>\n\nParanormal investigator [[Massimo Polidoro]] calls Caputo a \"performer\" and reports on an investigation done by ''[[Inside Edition]]'' and mentalist [[Mark Edward]] who attended one of her live shows in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Polidoro|first1=Massimo|authorlink=Massimo Polidoro|title=Theresa Caputo: The Fake Long Island Medium|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=June 2016|volume=40|issue=3|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> In 2013, illusionist [[Criss Angel]], offered Caputo $1 million to prove her claims.<ref>{{cite leave people business alone you know what am sayinnews|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/criss-angel-on-his-new-show-believe-it-s-healthy-to-be-skeptical-1.6241144|title=Criss Angel on his new show, 'BeLIEve': 'It's healthy' to be skeptical|work=Newsday|location=New York City / Long Island|first=Frank|last=Lovece|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=October 15, 2013|accessdate=December 7, 2017|quote=\"The Long Island Medium is just another charlatan. Any time she wants, we'll put her through a series of tests and I'll offer a million-dollar challenge to her. And you can put that in black and white.\"}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Skeptical movement|Skeptical activist]] [[Susan Gerbic]] has explained several techniques used by Caputo and other psychics, including requiring audience members to log into social media accounts at shows and observing physical identifications such as tattoos.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gerbic|first1=Susan|title=Ten Tricks of the Psychics I Bet You Didn't Know|url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/ten_tricks_of_the_psychics_i_bet_you_didnrsquot_know|publisher=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn December 3, 2017, Theresa and her husband Larry Caputo jointly announced they were separating after 28 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/theresa-caputo-splits-husband-long-island-medium/|title=Long Island Medium Theresa Caputo Separates from Husband Larry After 28 Years of Marriage|work=People|first=Stephanie |last=Petit |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> They have two children, who have both appeared on the show: Larry Caputo Jr. and Victoria Caputo.<ref name=InkedMag-LarryCaputo-2015>{{cite news|last1=Kovats|first1=Kirstie|title=Larry Caputo Interview: Long Island Medium|url=http://www.inkedmag.com/many-stories-larry-caputo-long-island-medium/|accessdate= January 4, 2016|work=[[Inked Magazine]]|date=4 May 2015}}</ref> On June 27, 2018, Larry Caputo, who moved to Los Angeles following the separation from Theresa, announced he and Theresa were moving from separation to divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/27/long-island-medium-theresa-larry-caputo-divorce/|title='Long Island Medium' Couple Moving Forward With Divorce|publisher=[[TMZ.com]] |accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, Theresa Caputo announced the divorce had been finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheresaCaputoLongIslandMedium/posts/2377400385699340|title=Please read \ud83d\udc95..When Long Island Medium began...|quote= After a year of being separated Larry and I have finalized our divorce.|date=December 18, 2018|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified Facebook page|accessdate=February 27, 2019|archivedate=February 27, 2019| archiveurl=http://archive.is/KJ1pM |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-larry-caputo-finalize-divorce-1.24714887|title= Theresa and Larry Caputo finalize their divorce|work=[[Newsday]]|location= New York City / Long Island|first=Frank|last= Lovece|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=December 18, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=Nassau County Supreme Court records show that on Dec. 12, attorneys of the Garden City firm Gassman Biamonte Betts filed a standard Request for Judicial Intervention for plaintiff Theresa R. Caputo in an uncontested divorce from Lawrence P. Caputo. No disposition date is listed in the online record.|archivedate=December 19, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181219113340/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-larry-caputo-finalize-divorce-1.24714887|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Works and publications ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|last2=Grish|first2=Kristina|title=There's More to Life Than This: Healing Messages, Remarkable Stories, and Insight About the Other Side from the Long Island Medium|date=2013|publisher=Pocket Books|isbn=978-1-4767-2703-5|edition=1st Atria Books hardcover|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476727035|oclc=872588683|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|title=You Can't Make This Stuff Up: Life Changing Lessons from Heaven.|date=2014|publisher=Pocket Books|isbn=978-1-4767-6443-6|oclc=903630815}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|title=Good Grief: Heal Your Soul, Honor Your Loved Ones, and Learn to Live Again|date=2017|publisher=Atria Books|isbn= 978-1-5011-3908-6|oclc=956959045}}\n\n==See also==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Ann O'Delia Diss Debar]] (\"One of the most extraordinary fake mediums... the world has ever known\" -Houdini)\n*[[Char Margolis]]\n*''[[Flim-Flam!|Flim-Flam! (Psychics, ESP, Unicorns and other Delusions)]]''\n*[[Fortune telling fraud]]\n*[[Harry Houdini#Debunking spiritualists|Houdini's debunking of psychics and mediums]]\n*[[James Van Praagh]]\n*[[John Edward]]\n*[[Mark Edward]]\n*[[Matt Fraser (psychic)]]\n*''[[Monica the Medium]]''\n*[[Peter Popoff#Investigation by James Randi|Televangelist Peter Popoff exposed by James Randi]]\n*''[[Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium]]''\n*[[Psychic Friends Network]], telephone psychic service\n*[[Rose Mackenberg]] (Historic investigator of psychic mediums)\n*[[Sylvia Browne]]\n*[[Thomas John Flanagan]]\n*[[Tyler Henry]]\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.theresacaputo.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|4588554}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Dyball|first1=Rennie|title=Everything You'd Want to Ask the Long Island Medium ... Answered|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20627842,00.html|accessdate=September 10, 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=September 7, 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caputo, Theresa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American psychics]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Hicksville, New York]]\n[[Category:American spiritual mediums]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American television personality and medium}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Theresa Caputo\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1966|06|10}} or {{birth date and age|1967|06|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hicksville, New York|Hicksville]], [[New York (state)|New York]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| other_names        = ''Long Island Medium''\n| occupation         = Television personality\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Larry Caputo|1989|2018|end=divorced}}\n| known for          = [[Long Island Medium]]\n| children           = 2\n| parents            = Nicholas Brigandi (father)\n             Veronica Brigandi (mother)\n}}\n'''Theresa Caputo''' (born June 10, 1966<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-reveals-the-most-shocking-reading-shes-done/|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Reveals One of the Most Shocking Readings She's Ever Done|first=Natalie |last=Stone |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=September 27, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jodi|last=Guglielmi|work=People|date=October 2, 2018|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Sits Down with Ex Husband Larry After Split|url=https://people.com/tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-faces-ex-larry-after-split|quote= Theresa, 52...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-caputo-long-island-medium-1.21375360| title=Theresa Caputo meets with estranged husband in 'Long Island Medium' new-season preview | first=Frank|last=Lovece|work=[[Newsday]]|location=Long Island|date=October 2, 2018|quote=...the Hicksville born-and-raised mentalist, 52...}}</ref> or 1967<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/books/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-endured-decades-anxiety-attacks-feared-communicating-with-dead/|title=Long Island Medium's Theresa Caputo Endured Decades of Anxiety Because She Feared Communicating with the Dead|first=Liz|work=People |last=McNeil |date=March 17, 2017|accessdate= November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 49}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-at-home-in-hicksville-1.9717137|title='Long Island Medium' Theresa Caputo, at home in Hicksville|first=Jim|last=Merritt|work=[[Newsday]] |location=[[New York City]] / [[Long Island]]| date=December 15, 2014|accessdate=November 14, 2017|quote=Caputo, 47}} {{subscription}}</ref><ref>Caputo gives birth date as June 10, 1967: {{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BVLH7lEgLCw/|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified [[Instagram]] page|date=June 10, 2017|accessdate=November 14, 2017|title=50 and feeling fabulous!...#birthdaygirl}}</ref>) is an American medium best known for her [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] [[reality television|reality]] TV series, ''[[Long Island Medium]]''.<ref name=People-StarsSeason7-2015>{{cite news|last1=Agard|first1=Chancellor|title=The Long Island Medium Dishes on Seeing Famous Ghosts|url=http://www.people.com/article/long-island-medium-theresa-caputo|accessdate=3 January 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=SiouxCityJournal-2014>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Bruce R.|title=Medium Theresa Caputo finds plenty of interest in her ability to speak with the dead|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/television/medium-theresa-caputo-finds-plenty-of-interest-in-her-abililty/article_53798adf-851f-5c34-9e6a-bb34fab5c545.html|accessdate=4 January 2016|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCaputo was born and raised in [[Hicksville, New York]], on [[Long Island]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/TheresaCaputoLongIslandMedium/about/|title=Biography|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified [[Facebook]] page|first=Theresa|last=Caputo|quote=I was born and raised on Long Island in Hicksville, NY.|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref> the daughter of Nicholas and Veronica Brigandi.<ref name=officialbio>{{cite web|url= https://www.theresacaputo.com/about-me/|title=About Me| publisher=Theresa Caputo official website|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=My parents Nick and Ronnie...and my brother Michael...}}</ref><ref name=life&style>{{cite news|url= https://www.lifeandstylemag.com/posts/theresa-caputo-mom-and-dad-159097/|title=Theresa Caputo's Mom and Dad Are Also Sad About Her Split From Her Husband Larry|first=Emma|last= Hernandez|work=[[Life & Style]]|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=Theresa's father Nicholas is 77 years old and is from Hicksville, NY which is where he raised Theresa and her brother Michael with his wife, Veronica.}}</ref> She has a brother, Michael.<ref name=officialbio /> Their father was a volunteer firefighter and worked for the Nassau County Department of Public Works until 1980, when he was elected county water commissioner.<ref name=kiwanis>{{cite web|url=http://www.hicksvillekiwanis.org/index.php?page=fmnickb|title=Nicholas J. Brigandi - Spirit of Giving Award|publisher= [[Kiwanis Club]] of Hicksville|date=October 2012|accessdate=February 27, 2019| archivedate= June 23, 2016|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160623223044/http://www.hicksvillekiwanis.org/index.php?page=fmnickb |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nCaputo has been on the [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] [[reality television|reality]] TV series, ''[[Long Island Medium]]'' since 2011.<ref name=HuffPo-Feature-2015>{{cite news|last1=Cook|first1=Michael|title=\"Long Island Medium\" Theresa Caputo -- \"You Can't Put A Price On What I Am Able To Give People\"|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-cook/long-island-medium-theres_b_8851248.html|accessdate=3 January 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> She is also the author of two books and tours under \"Theresa Caputo Live! The Experience\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keeperman|first1=Brittany|title=Spirited energy: 'Long Island Medium' Theresa Caputo to appear at the Convo|url=http://www.daily-chronicle.com/2016/04/06/spirited-energy-long-island-medium-theresa-caputo-to-appear-at-the-convo/ah878du/|website=[[Daily Chronicle (Illinois)|Daily Chronicle]]|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nSeveral people have accused her of being a fraud, ranging from television news programs such as ''[[Inside Edition]]''<ref name=\"insideedition\">{{cite news|title=The Long Island Medium&nbsp;\u2013 Can She Really Communicate with the Dead?|url=http://www.insideedition.com/investigative/5331-the-long-island-medium-can-she-really-communicate-with-the-dead|accessdate=May 21, 2013|work=[[Inside Edition]]|date=August 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=jezebel-dodai>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Dodai|title=Super Sad and Misguided Emails Intended for the Long Island Medium|url=http://jezebel.com/5953012/super-sad-and-misguided-emails-intended-for-the-long-island-medium|accessdate=May 21, 2013|publisher=[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel.com]]|date=October 20, 2012}}</ref> to print publications such as ''[[Wired Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2012/04/opinion_randilimedium0409/ |title=The 'Medium' is not the messenger |magazine=[[Wired Magazine]] |date=2012-04-09 |accessdate=2013-05-19 |last=Randi |first=James |authorlink=James Randi}}</ref> Caputo was described by [[D. J. Grothe]] as a [[charlatan]],<ref name=\"grothe\">{{cite news |last=Grothe |first=DJ |authorlink=D. J. Grothe |title=Priceline.com: Will you prove your spokesperson worthy for a million dollars?|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dj-grothe/pricelinecom-will-you-pro_b_1773947.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> and [[James Randi]] said her claims were not true.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nIn April 2012, the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] awarded Caputo its [[Pigasus Award]], a tongue-in-cheek award that seeks to expose [[parapsychology|parapsychological]], [[paranormal]] or [[psychic]] frauds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAYG_cgqjWA |title=2012 Pigasus Awards Announcement|work=[[James Randi Educational Foundation]]|date=March 30, 2012|accessdate=March 27, 2014|format=YouTube video}}</ref> The James Randi Education Foundation has been critical of Caputo's work.<ref name=JamesRandi-TallStory-2012>{{cite web|last1=Stollznow|first1=Dr. Karen|authorlink=Karen Stollznow|title=Long Island Medium: A Tall Story|url=http://archive.randi.org/site/index.php/swift-blog/1755-long-island-medium-a-tall-story.html|work=[[James Randi Educational Foundation]]|accessdate=4 January 2016|date=27 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nA newspaper review of Caputo's performances at the [[NYCB Theatre at Westbury]] in late 2017 concluded, \"For me, this unbelievable experience was simply that: not to be believed. In my humble opinion, Caputo is a damn good performer, and she\u2019s got undeniably likable sass and charisma. I just don\u2019t think she speaks with the dead. Or she didn\u2019t the night that I saw her. But my father probably could have told you that.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Franchi|first=Jaime|title=My Not-So-Psychic Experience with Long Island Medium Theresa Caputo|url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2014/12/21/my-not-so-psychic-experience-with-long-island-medium-theresa-caputo/|date=December 7, 2014|journal=Long Island Press}}</ref>\n\nParanormal investigator [[Massimo Polidoro]] calls Caputo a \"performer\" and reports on an investigation done by ''[[Inside Edition]]'' and mentalist [[Mark Edward]] who attended one of her live shows in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Polidoro|first1=Massimo|authorlink=Massimo Polidoro|title=Theresa Caputo: The Fake Long Island Medium|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=June 2016|volume=40|issue=3|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> In 2013, illusionist [[Criss Angel]], offered Caputo $1 million to prove her claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/criss-angel-on-his-new-show-believe-it-s-healthy-to-be-skeptical-1.6241144|title=Criss Angel on his new show, 'BeLIEve': 'It's healthy' to be skeptical|work=Newsday|location=New York City / Long Island|first=Frank|last=Lovece|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=October 15, 2013|accessdate=December 7, 2017|quote=\"The Long Island Medium is just another charlatan. Any time she wants, we'll put her through a series of tests and I'll offer a million-dollar challenge to her. And you can put that in black and white.\"}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n[[Skeptical movement|Skeptical activist]] [[Susan Gerbic]] has explained several techniques used by Caputo and other psychics, including requiring audience members to log into social media accounts at shows and observing physical identifications such as tattoos.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gerbic|first1=Susan|title=Ten Tricks of the Psychics I Bet You Didn't Know|url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/ten_tricks_of_the_psychics_i_bet_you_didnrsquot_know|publisher=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn December 3, 2017, Theresa and her husband Larry Caputo jointly announced they were separating after 28 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/theresa-caputo-splits-husband-long-island-medium/|title=Long Island Medium Theresa Caputo Separates from Husband Larry After 28 Years of Marriage|work=People|first=Stephanie |last=Petit |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> They have two children, who have both appeared on the show: Larry Caputo Jr. and Victoria Caputo.<ref name=InkedMag-LarryCaputo-2015>{{cite news|last1=Kovats|first1=Kirstie|title=Larry Caputo Interview: Long Island Medium|url=http://www.inkedmag.com/many-stories-larry-caputo-long-island-medium/|accessdate= January 4, 2016|work=[[Inked Magazine]]|date=4 May 2015}}</ref> On June 27, 2018, Larry Caputo, who moved to Los Angeles following the separation from Theresa, announced he and Theresa were moving from separation to divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/27/long-island-medium-theresa-larry-caputo-divorce/|title='Long Island Medium' Couple Moving Forward With Divorce|publisher=[[TMZ.com]] |accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, Theresa Caputo announced the divorce had been finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheresaCaputoLongIslandMedium/posts/2377400385699340|title=Please read \ud83d\udc95..When Long Island Medium began...|quote= After a year of being separated Larry and I have finalized our divorce.|date=December 18, 2018|publisher=Theresa Caputo verified Facebook page|accessdate=February 27, 2019|archivedate=February 27, 2019| archiveurl=http://archive.is/KJ1pM |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-larry-caputo-finalize-divorce-1.24714887|title= Theresa and Larry Caputo finalize their divorce|work=[[Newsday]]|location= New York City / Long Island|first=Frank|last= Lovece|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=December 18, 2018|accessdate=February 27, 2019|quote=Nassau County Supreme Court records show that on Dec. 12, attorneys of the Garden City firm Gassman Biamonte Betts filed a standard Request for Judicial Intervention for plaintiff Theresa R. Caputo in an uncontested divorce from Lawrence P. Caputo. No disposition date is listed in the online record.|archivedate=December 19, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181219113340/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/theresa-larry-caputo-finalize-divorce-1.24714887|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Works and publications ==\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|last2=Grish|first2=Kristina|title=There's More to Life Than This: Healing Messages, Remarkable Stories, and Insight About the Other Side from the Long Island Medium|date=2013|publisher=Pocket Books|isbn=978-1-4767-2703-5|edition=1st Atria Books hardcover|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476727035|oclc=872588683|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|title=You Can't Make This Stuff Up: Life Changing Lessons from Heaven.|date=2014|publisher=Pocket Books|isbn=978-1-4767-6443-6|oclc=903630815}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Caputo|first1=Theresa|title=Good Grief: Heal Your Soul, Honor Your Loved Ones, and Learn to Live Again|date=2017|publisher=Atria Books|isbn= 978-1-5011-3908-6|oclc=956959045}}\n\n==See also==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n*[[Ann O'Delia Diss Debar]] (\"One of the most extraordinary fake mediums... the world has ever known\" -Houdini)\n*[[Char Margolis]]\n*''[[Flim-Flam!|Flim-Flam! (Psychics, ESP, Unicorns and other Delusions)]]''\n*[[Fortune telling fraud]]\n*[[Harry Houdini#Debunking spiritualists|Houdini's debunking of psychics and mediums]]\n*[[James Van Praagh]]\n*[[John Edward]]\n*[[Mark Edward]]\n*[[Matt Fraser (psychic)]]\n*''[[Monica the Medium]]''\n*[[Peter Popoff#Investigation by James Randi|Televangelist Peter Popoff exposed by James Randi]]\n*''[[Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium]]''\n*[[Psychic Friends Network]], telephone psychic service\n*[[Rose Mackenberg]] (Historic investigator of psychic mediums)\n*[[Sylvia Browne]]\n*[[Thomas John Flanagan]]\n*[[Tyler Henry]]\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.theresacaputo.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|4588554}}\n*{{cite news|last1=Dyball|first1=Rennie|title=Everything You'd Want to Ask the Long Island Medium ... Answered|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20627842,00.html|accessdate=September 10, 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=September 7, 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caputo, Theresa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American psychics]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Hicksville, New York]]\n[[Category:American spiritual mediums]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "41.81.134.112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life:Fixed typing error)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theresa_Caputo"}
{"title_page": "Helen Joseph", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Helen Beatrice Joseph<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n|image = File:Helen Joseph 1941.jpg<!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n|alt = Helen Joseph 1941\n|caption = Helen Joseph 1941\n|birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n|birth_date = {{Birth date |1905|04|8|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Easebourne]] near Midhurst, [[West Sussex]], [[England]]\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|1992|12|25 |1905|04|8|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n|resting_place = [[Avalon Cemetery]]\n|nationality = [[South African people|South African]]\n|other_names =\n|occupation = anti-[[apartheid]] [[activist]]\n|years_active =\n|known_for =\n|notable_works =\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Helen Beatrice Joseph''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Fennell''') (8 April 1905 \u2013 25 December 1992) was a [[South Africa]]n anti-[[apartheid]] [[activist]].{{sfn|Van Wyk|2003}} Born in Sussex, England, Helen graduated with a degree in English from the [[University of London]] in 1927 and then departed for India, where she taught for three years at Mahbubia School school for girls in Hyderabad. In about 1930 she left India for South Africa. She settled in Durban, where she met and married a dentist, Billie Joseph.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-helen-joseph-1565649.html |title=Obituary: Helen Joseph |date=28 December 1992 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHelen Joseph was born Helen Beatrice May Fennell in 1905 in [[Easebourne]] near [[Midhurst]], [[West Sussex]], [[England]], the daughter of a government Customs and Excise officer, Samuel Fennell.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Frederikse |first1=Julie |title=The Fought for Freedom: Helen Josephs |date=January 1995 |publisher=Maskew Millar Longman |location=Cape Town |isbn=0636022404|page=1}}</ref> Helen Joseph was a product of a middle class, white family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Cowell|first=Alan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/26/world/helen-joseph-dies-in-south-africa-early-foe-of-apartheid-was-87.html|title=Helen Joseph Dies in South Africa; Early Foe of Apartheid Was 87|date=1992-12-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She grew up in an [[anti-Semitic]] and [[racist]] household.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Caine|first=Barbara|date=2008|title='A South African Revolutionary, but a Lady of the British Empire': Helen Joseph and the Anti-Apartheid Movement|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/40283169|journal=Journal of Southern African Studies|volume=34|issue=3|pages=575\u2013590|issn=0305-7070}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1923 she was admitted to the University of London to study English, and she graduated from [[King's College London]] in 1927. After working as a teacher in [[India]] for three years, Helen went to [[South Africa]] in 1931, where she met and married Billie Joseph, a Jewish dentist 17 years her senior.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Lazerson |first1=Joshua |title=Against the tide : whites in the struggle against apartheid |year=1994 |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0813384877 |page=106}}</ref> She served in the [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]] during [[World War II]] as an information and welfare officer. After the war and a divorce, she trained as a social worker and started working in a community centre in a [[Coloured]] (mixed race) area of Cape Town.{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1951 Helen first met [[Solly Sachs]] when she applied for the job of Secretary-Director of the Medical Aid Society of the Transvaal Clothing Society. At the time, Sachs was the head of the Garment Workers' Union.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Side by side |last=Joseph |first=Helen |publisher=AD. Donker Publishers |year=1986 |isbn=0-86852-196-5 |location=Johannesburg |pages=249}}</ref>\n\nAppalled by the conditions of black South Africans, she fought side by side with activists to gain greater rights, such as health care, freedom of speech, racial equality, and women's rights.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Healy-Clancy|first=Meghan|date=|title=The Family Politics of the Federation of South African Women: A History of Public Motherhood in Women's Antiracist Activism|url=https://eds.a.ebscohost.com|journal=Signs: Journal of Women in Culture & Society 42|volume=|pages=843-866|via=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|last=Giokos|first=Eleni|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/08/09/africa/south-african-womens-day/index.html|title=The four South African women who rattled the nation with anti-rape protest|date=August 17, 2016|work=CNN World|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>She was a founder member of the [[South African Congress of Democrats|Congress of Democrats]], and one of the leaders who read out the clauses of the [[Freedom Charter]] at the Congress of the People in [[Kliptown]] in 1955. Appalled by the plight of black women, she played a pivotal role, along with [[Lillian Ngoyi]], in the formation of the [[Federation of South African Women]]. With its leadership, she spearheaded a [[Women's March (South Africa)|March of 20,000 women]] on August 9, 1956, to the [[Union Buildings]] in [[Pretoria]] to protest against the [[pass laws]]. This day is still celebrated as South Africa's [[National Women's Day]].{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\n===Treason trial and house arrest===\nJoseph's opposition to the State had not gone unnoticed and she was a defendant at the 1956 [[Treason Trial]]. [[Frans Lourens Herman Rumpff|Justice Rumpff]] stated, \"On all the evidence presented to this court and on our findings of fact, it is impossible for this court to come to the conclusion that the African National Congress has acquired or adopted a policy to overthrow the state by violence, that is, in the sense that the masses had to be prepared or conditioned to commit direct acts of violence against the state.\"\n\nHowever, Joseph was arrested on a charge of [[high treason]] in December 1956 as a result of her anti-apartheid activism. In 1957, Joseph was banned from publicly opposing the government through her speech and protests.<ref name=\":0\" /> The treason trial dragged on for four years and she was acquitted in 1961. Joseph was one of six Jewish women on trial, the others being [[Ruth First]], [[Yetta Barenblatt]], [[Sonia Bunting]], Dorothy Shanley, and [[Jacqueline Arenstein]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Weisse |first1=Wolfram |title=Religion, politics, and identity in a changing South Africa |year=2004 |publisher=Waxmann Munster |isbn=9783830913283 |page=47}}</ref> While on trial for treason, Joseph learned that the government was forcing people out of the country and into remote areas if they were thought to have violated apartheid laws.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1962, Joseph found most of the banished people then reunited them with their families and gave them supplies.<ref name=\":1\" /> In spite of her acquittal, Helen Joseph became on 13 October 1962 the first person placed under house arrest under the [[Sabotage Act]] introduced by the [[apartheid]] government <ref>{{Cite journal |last=Caine |first=Barbara|date=2008 |title='A South African Revolutionary, but a Lady of the British Empire': Helen Joseph and the Anti-Apartheid Movement |journal=Journal of Southern African Studies |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=575\u2013590 |doi=10.1080/03057070802259811|jstor=40283169|issn=0305-7070}}</ref>. She narrowly escaped death more than once, surviving bullets shot through her bedroom and a bomb wired to her front gate. Her last banning order was lifted when she was 80 years old.{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\nIn a submission to the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, Paul Erasmus, a secret service operative, stated that from about 1978 till late in the 1980s, he and his colleagues had on many occasions damaged the property of Mrs Joseph by throwing stones through the windows of her house, made telephone threats, fired shots at the house but did not intend to injure any person, ordered and caused unwanted supplies to be delivered to her house, and poured paint remover over her motor car, as well as a car belonging to Ann Hughes, when the latter visited her.\n\nThe apartheid state's fear of her was puzzling: \"How a weary old girl, an ou tannie like me can be a threat to state security only they can say.\" Joseph is quoted as saying.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sabctrc.saha.org.za/hearing.php?id=59512&t=&tab=hearings |title=Truth Commission \u2013 Special Report \u2013 DecisionsTRC Final Report \u2013 Volume, Section, Chapter |website=sabctrc.saha.org.za}}</ref> From the late 1970s, Christmas Day was \"Open Day\" at Helen Joseph's house for those involved in the anti-apartheid struggle. All comrades brought food and at 12 noon everyone raised their glasses to those imprisoned on Robben Island. (Apparently the Robben Islanders were aware of the ritual.) On 25 December 1992, Joseph was in hospital and the venue moved to 11 Plantation Road, The Gardens. Robben Island's prisoners had been released, and those present raised their glasses to Helen, who died shortly thereafter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/helen-joseph |title=Helen Joseph |last=Anonymous |date=17 February 2011 |website=www.sahistory.org.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/treason-trial-1956-1961 |title=Treason Trial 1956-1961 |last=Anonymous |date=31 March 2011 |website=www.sahistory.org.za}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Helen Joseph Avalon.jpg|thumb|Grave of Helen Joseph in the [[Avalon Cemetery]]]]\n\"On 31 December 1956, I moved into my little cottage with the tall trees, delighted to have a home of my own....\" \u2014 Joseph was quoted as saying in 1986. The [[Helen Joseph House|cottage]] was 35 Fanny Avenue, and moving into it in December 1956 was an act of faith and optimism, as Helen had been arrested just days before that, charged with treason, and faced trial for four harrowing years. It is tempting to speculate that Helen Joseph chose to live in [[Norwood, Gauteng|Norwood]] because two of her fellow comrades, [[Bram Fischer]] in Oaklands, and Violet Weinberg in The Gardens, lived in close proximity. Whatever the reason for her choice, she would conduct her struggle against injustice from this address until her death in 1992. During that period she was banned four times, jailed four times, and she saw her life become a long saga of police persecution, much of it spent under house arrest.\n\nHelen had no children of her own, but frequently stood in for the children of comrades in prison or in exile. She was viewed as a mother in the eyes of many activists, and for many years, they celebrated her on [[Mother's Day]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Among the children who spent time in her care were the daughters of [[Winnie Madikizela-Mandela|Winnie]] and [[Nelson Mandela]]'s \u2013 Zinzi and Zenani \u2013 and [[Bram Fischer]]'s daughter, Ilsa.\n\n==Legacy and honours==\nJoseph died on 25 December 1992 at the age of 87.{{cn|date=September 2019}} \n\nJoseph was admitted to the [[Order of Simon of Cyrene]] in 1992, the highest honour the [[Anglican Church of Southern Africa]] bestows on lay members who have provided outstanding service.<ref name=\"hist_Hist\">{{Cite web |title=Historical Papers, Wits University |author= |work=historicalpapers.wits.ac.za |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01 |url=http://www.historicalpapers.wits.ac.za/?inventory/U/collections&c=A1985/R/6114 |language= |quote=}}</ref> She was awarded the [[Isitwalandwe Medal |Isitwalandwe/Seaparankwe Medal]] by the ANC in 1992.\n\nPlaces named after Helen Joseph include the former Davenport Road in [[Glenwood, KwaZulu-Natal]], the [[Helen Joseph Hospital]] in [[Johannesburg]], a student residence at [[Rhodes University]], [[Grahamstown]], and a road in Rustenburg.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Published works==\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=If this be Treason |url=https://archive.org/details/ifthisbetreason0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1963 |publisher=Andre Deutsch |place=London |isbn=978-0-620-22197-9 |display-authors=0 |quote=Helen Joseph's Dramatic Account of the Treason Trial, the Longest in South Africa's History and One of the Strangest Trials of the 20th Century}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=Tomorrow's Sun |url=https://archive.org/details/tomorrowssunsmug0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1967 |publisher=[[John Day Company]] |location=New York |display-authors=0 |quote=A smuggled journal from South Africa}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=Side by Side: The Autobiography of Helen Joseph |url=https://archive.org/details/sidebysideautobi0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1986 |publisher=William Morrow & Co |isbn=978-0-688-07103-5 |location=New York |display-authors=0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people subject to banning orders under apartheid]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Van Wyk |first=Chris |title=Helen Joseph |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PciWWeSv4k4C |year=2003 |publisher=Awareness Publishing |isbn=978-1-919910-76-5}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Rappaport |first=Helen |title=Encyclopedia of Women Social Reformers |url=https://books.google.com/?id=rpuSzowmIkgC |year=2001 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-57607-101-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060114012030/http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/people/hjoseph.html Short biography on the website of the ANC]\n*[http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/helen-joseph SAHistory - Helen Joseph]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joseph, Helen}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Jewish South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:People acquitted of treason]]\n[[Category:South African Anglicans]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists|J]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Helen Beatrice Joseph<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n|image = File:Helen Joseph 1941.jpg<!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n|alt = Helen Joseph 1941\n|caption = Helen Joseph 1941\n|birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n|birth_date = {{Birth date |1905|04|8|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Easebourne]] near Midhurst, [[West Sussex]], [[England]]\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|1992|12|25 |1905|04|8|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n|resting_place = [[Avalon Cemetery]]\n|nationality = [[South African people|South African]]\n|other_names =\n|occupation = anti-[[apartheid]] [[activist]]\n|years_active =\n|known_for =\n|notable_works =\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Helen Beatrice Joseph''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Fennell''') (8 April 1905 \u2013 25 December 1992) was a [[South Africa]]n anti-[[apartheid]] [[activist]].{{sfn|Van Wyk|2003}} Born in Sussex, England, Helen graduated with a degree in English from the [[University of London]] in 1927 and then departed for India, where she taught for three years at Mahbubia School school for girls in Hyderabad. In about 1930 she left India for South Africa. She settled in Durban, where she met and married a dentist, Billie Joseph.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-helen-joseph-1565649.html |title=Obituary: Helen Joseph |date=28 December 1992 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHelen Joseph was born Helen Beatrice May Fennell in 1905 in [[Easebourne]] near [[Midhurst]], [[West Sussex]], [[England]], the daughter of a government Customs and Excise officer, Samuel Fennell.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Frederikse |first1=Julie |title=The Fought for Freedom: Helen Josephs |date=January 1995 |publisher=Maskew Millar Longman |location=Cape Town |isbn=0636022404|page=1}}</ref> \n\nIn 1923 she was admitted to the University of London to study English, and she graduated from [[King's College London]] in 1927. After working as a teacher in [[India]] for three years, Helen went to [[South Africa]] in 1931, where she met and married Billie Joseph, a Jewish dentist 17 years her senior.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Lazerson |first1=Joshua |title=Against the tide : whites in the struggle against apartheid |year=1994 |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0813384877 |page=106}}</ref> She served in the [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]] during [[World War II]] as an information and welfare officer. After the war and a divorce, she trained as a social worker and started working in a community centre in a [[Coloured]] (mixed race) area of Cape Town.{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1951 Helen first met [[Solly Sachs]] when she applied for the job of Secretary-Director of the Medical Aid Society of the Transvaal Clothing Society. At the time, Sachs was the head of the Garment Workers' Union.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Side by side |last=Joseph |first=Helen |publisher=AD. Donker Publishers |year=1986 |isbn=0-86852-196-5 |location=Johannesburg |pages=249}}</ref>\n\nShe was a founder member of the [[South African Congress of Democrats|Congress of Democrats]], and one of the leaders who read out the clauses of the [[Freedom Charter]] at the Congress of the People in [[Kliptown]] in 1955. Appalled by the plight of black women, she played a pivotal role, along with [[Lillian Ngoyi]], in the formation of the [[Federation of South African Women]]. With its leadership, she spearheaded a [[Women's March (South Africa)|March of 20,000 women]] on August 9, 1956, to the [[Union Buildings]] in [[Pretoria]] to protest against the [[pass laws]]. This day is still celebrated as South Africa's [[National Women's Day]].{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\n===Treason trial and house arrest===\nJoseph's opposition to the State had not gone unnoticed and she was a defendant at the 1956 [[Treason Trial]]. [[Frans Lourens Herman Rumpff|Justice Rumpff]] stated, \"On all the evidence presented to this court and on our findings of fact, it is impossible for this court to come to the conclusion that the African National Congress has acquired or adopted a policy to overthrow the state by violence, that is, in the sense that the masses had to be prepared or conditioned to commit direct acts of violence against the state.\"\n\nHowever, Joseph was arrested on a charge of [[high treason]] in December 1956, then banned in 1957. The treason trial dragged on for four years and she was acquitted in 1961. Joseph was one of six Jewish women on trial, the others being [[Ruth First]], [[Yetta Barenblatt]], [[Sonia Bunting]], Dorothy Shanley, and [[Jacqueline Arenstein]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Weisse |first1=Wolfram |title=Religion, politics, and identity in a changing South Africa |year=2004 |publisher=Waxmann Munster |isbn=9783830913283 |page=47}}</ref> In spite of her acquittal, Helen Joseph became on 13 October 1962 the first person placed under house arrest under the [[Sabotage Act]] introduced by the [[apartheid]] government <ref>{{Cite journal |last=Caine |first=Barbara|date=2008 |title='A South African Revolutionary, but a Lady of the British Empire': Helen Joseph and the Anti-Apartheid Movement |journal=Journal of Southern African Studies |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=575\u2013590 |doi=10.1080/03057070802259811|jstor=40283169|issn=0305-7070}}</ref>. She narrowly escaped death more than once, surviving bullets shot through her bedroom and a bomb wired to her front gate. Her last banning order was lifted when she was 80 years old.{{sfn |Rappaport |2001 |p=344}}\n\nIn a submission to the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, Paul Erasmus, a secret service operative, stated that from about 1978 till late in the 1980s, he and his colleagues had on many occasions damaged the property of Mrs Joseph by throwing stones through the windows of her house, made telephone threats, fired shots at the house but did not intend to injure any person, ordered and caused unwanted supplies to be delivered to her house, and poured paint remover over her motor car, as well as a car belonging to Ann Hughes, when the latter visited her.\n\nThe apartheid state's fear of her was puzzling: \"How a weary old girl, an ou tannie like me can be a threat to state security only they can say.\" Joseph is quoted as saying.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sabctrc.saha.org.za/hearing.php?id=59512&t=&tab=hearings |title=Truth Commission \u2013 Special Report \u2013 DecisionsTRC Final Report \u2013 Volume, Section, Chapter |website=sabctrc.saha.org.za}}</ref> From the late 1970s, Christmas Day was \"Open Day\" at Helen Joseph's house for those involved in the anti-apartheid struggle. All comrades brought food and at 12 noon everyone raised their glasses to those imprisoned on Robben Island. (Apparently the Robben Islanders were aware of the ritual.) On 25 December 1992, Joseph was in hospital and the venue moved to 11 Plantation Road, The Gardens. Robben Island's prisoners had been released, and those present raised their glasses to Helen, who died shortly thereafter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/helen-joseph |title=Helen Joseph |last=Anonymous |date=17 February 2011 |website=www.sahistory.org.za}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/treason-trial-1956-1961 |title=Treason Trial 1956-1961 |last=Anonymous |date=31 March 2011 |website=www.sahistory.org.za}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Helen Joseph Avalon.jpg|thumb|Grave of Helen Joseph in the [[Avalon Cemetery]]]]\n\"On 31 December 1956, I moved into my little cottage with the tall trees, delighted to have a home of my own....\" \u2014 Joseph was quoted as saying in 1986. The [[Helen Joseph House|cottage]] was 35 Fanny Avenue, and moving into it in December 1956 was an act of faith and optimism, as Helen had been arrested just days before that, charged with treason, and faced trial for four harrowing years. It is tempting to speculate that Helen Joseph chose to live in [[Norwood, Gauteng|Norwood]] because two of her fellow comrades, [[Bram Fischer]] in Oaklands, and Violet Weinberg in The Gardens, lived in close proximity. Whatever the reason for her choice, she would conduct her struggle against injustice from this address until her death in 1992. During that period she was banned four times, jailed four times, and she saw her life become a long saga of police persecution, much of it spent under house arrest.\n\nHelen had no children of her own, but frequently stood in for the children of comrades in prison or in exile. Among the children who spent time in her care were the daughters of [[Winnie Madikizela-Mandela|Winnie]] and [[Nelson Mandela]]'s \u2013 Zinzi and Zenani \u2013 and [[Bram Fischer]]'s daughter, Ilsa.\n\n==Legacy and honours==\nJoseph died on 25 December 1992 at the age of 87.{{cn|date=September 2019}} \n\nJoseph was admitted to the [[Order of Simon of Cyrene]] in 1992, the highest honour the [[Anglican Church of Southern Africa]] bestows on lay members who have provided outstanding service.<ref name=\"hist_Hist\">{{Cite web |title=Historical Papers, Wits University |author= |work=historicalpapers.wits.ac.za |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01 |url=http://www.historicalpapers.wits.ac.za/?inventory/U/collections&c=A1985/R/6114 |language= |quote=}}</ref> She was awarded the [[Isitwalandwe Medal |Isitwalandwe/Seaparankwe Medal]] by the ANC in 1992.\n\nPlaces named after Helen Joseph include the former Davenport Road in [[Glenwood, KwaZulu-Natal]], the [[Helen Joseph Hospital]] in [[Johannesburg]], a student residence at [[Rhodes University]], [[Grahamstown]], and a road in Rustenburg.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Published works==\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=If this be Treason |url=https://archive.org/details/ifthisbetreason0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1963 |publisher=Andre Deutsch |place=London |isbn=978-0-620-22197-9 |display-authors=0 |quote=Helen Joseph's Dramatic Account of the Treason Trial, the Longest in South Africa's History and One of the Strangest Trials of the 20th Century}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=Tomorrow's Sun |url=https://archive.org/details/tomorrowssunsmug0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1967 |publisher=[[John Day Company]] |location=New York |display-authors=0 |quote=A smuggled journal from South Africa}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Joseph |first=Helen |title=Side by Side: The Autobiography of Helen Joseph |url=https://archive.org/details/sidebysideautobi0000jose |url-access=registration |year=1986 |publisher=William Morrow & Co |isbn=978-0-688-07103-5 |location=New York |display-authors=0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people subject to banning orders under apartheid]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Van Wyk |first=Chris |title=Helen Joseph |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PciWWeSv4k4C |year=2003 |publisher=Awareness Publishing |isbn=978-1-919910-76-5}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last=Rappaport |first=Helen |title=Encyclopedia of Women Social Reformers |url=https://books.google.com/?id=rpuSzowmIkgC |year=2001 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-57607-101-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060114012030/http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/history/people/hjoseph.html Short biography on the website of the ANC]\n*[http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/helen-joseph SAHistory - Helen Joseph]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joseph, Helen}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Jewish South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:People acquitted of treason]]\n[[Category:South African Anglicans]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists|J]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Takirajohns83", "label": "safe", "comment": "added some more details about her early life, activism, and the people she helped with citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Joseph"}
{"title_page": "MMB", "text_new": "'''MMB''' may refer to:MMB\n\n==Music==\n* [[Michigan Marching Band]], of the University of Michigan\n* [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]], a band from Boston\n\n==Computing, science, and technology==\n* [[MMB (cipher)]], a block cipher in cryptography\n* [[3-Mercapto-3-methylbutan-1-ol]], a chemical found in some wines\n* [[Metabolic network modelling#Minimal metabolic behaviors|Minimal metabolic behaviors]], for modeling metabolic networks\n* Middle mouse button, a button on the [[computer mouse]]\n\n==Other uses==\n* [[Maharashtra Maritime Board]]\n* [[Maritime Museum of Barcelona]]\n* [[Memanbetsu Airport]], an airport at Hokkaid\u014d, Japan ([[IATA airport code]]: MMB)\n* [[Milk Marketing Board]], a former British government quango\n\n{{disamb}}\n", "text_old": "'''MMB''' may refer to:\n==Music==\n* [[Michigan Marching Band]], of the University of Michigan\n* [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]], a band from Boston\n\n==Computing, science, and technology==\n* [[MMB (cipher)]], a block cipher in cryptography\n* [[3-Mercapto-3-methylbutan-1-ol]], a chemical found in some wines\n* [[Metabolic network modelling#Minimal metabolic behaviors|Minimal metabolic behaviors]], for modeling metabolic networks\n* Middle mouse button, a button on the [[computer mouse]]\n\n==Other uses==\n* [[Maharashtra Maritime Board]]\n* [[Maritime Museum of Barcelona]]\n* [[Memanbetsu Airport]], an airport at Hokkaid\u014d, Japan ([[IATA airport code]]: MMB)\n* [[Milk Marketing Board]], a former British government quango\n\n{{disamb}}\n", "name_user": "82.205.103.2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MMB"}
{"title_page": "Yogeshwar Amatya", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{notability|biography|date=February 2015}}\n{{peacock|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Yogeshwar Amatya\n| image               =\n| caption             = Yogeshwar Amatya in Melancholy Song Recording at Radio Nepal Studio in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya\n| birth_place         = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| genre               = [[Soft rock]], [[pop rock]], [[folk music|folk]]\n| instrument          = Vocals guitar\n| occupation          = Singer<br> [[Composer]]<br>businessman<br> philanthropist\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Single Records|Single]] (Nepal)\n}}\n\n'''Yogeshwar Amatya''' (born Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya, 3 April) is a Nepali singer, musician, producer, actor, social activist, and photographer. Amatya has been a figure in Nepalese [[soft rock]] during the last two decades. He has sold more than 1 million records, making him one of [[List of best-selling music artists|Nepal's best-selling music artists]] and the best-selling [[Nepali rock]] artist of all time.\n\nAmatya came to fame in Nepal with his album ''Jaba Sandhya Hunchha'' and became more famous with his 1998 song ''Karai Kara Le''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nepalipopartist.blogspot.com/2007/10/yogeshwor-amatya.html | author = Thisaway | title = Profile of Nepali pop music artist..........: Yogeshwar Amatya | accessdate = 18 September 2010 | authorlink = Thisaway }}</ref> In 1998, he released his ''Ahile Chaahin Drabya Ko Aaasha Ma, Bastoo'' album which included ''Wakka Dikka''. Amatya also participated in [[Melancholy (song)|Melancholy]] song as a solo artist with 365 other Nepali singers and musician. The song set a [[Guinness World Record]] entitled \"Most Vocal Solos in a Song Recording\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-vocal-solos-in-a-song-recording|title=Most vocal solos in a song recording|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-05-29/nepali-house-hold-names-go-for-the-guinness-world-records.html|title=Nepali house-hold names go for the Guinness World Records|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/26897/|title=National poet Madhav Prasad Ghimire turns singer|first=Shreedhar|last=Pandey|website=My Republica|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAmatya has mentioned that he has never received any formal training in music. He says, \"I never had any formal training regarding music... I guess I have to say that I don't have any musical background, except late night jamming with tons of beer with my buddies.\"<ref name=Telg3672213>{{cite news|url=http://www.interview.bagaicha.com/Yogeshwar-Amatya-71.html#sthash.15OZFMba.dpuf|title=Interview with Yogeshwar Amatya |author=keran limbu|publisher=bagaicha.com|date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=1 July 2011|location=Nepal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAmatya hasn't used his [[middle name]] since his father dropped it. His father, Bhuwaneshor Amatya, was the first President of Nepal Chalchitra Sangha. His mother, Lamu Amatya, was the first trained nurse in Nepal.\n\nHe was bullied by classmates while studying at [[St. Xavier's College, Kathmandu|St. Xavier's]] for his [[cleft lip]]. It got so out of hand that some of the seniors stole a guitar he had borrowed from his cousin. After that incident, he left the school and joined North Point, [[Darjeeling]].\n\nAmatya enjoys [[gemology|gems]], especially regarding [[gemstone|gem]] sets containing diamonds and [[emerald]]s. He has said if he'd not been a musician, he would have been a [[jeweler]]. Amatya has a [[bachelor's degree]] in Gemology from the Gemological Institute of [[India]], [[Bombay]].\n\nAmatya is a sportsman with expertise in some sports. He has played [[association football|football]] for Army (Shreenath Gana) and NRT at center [[Striker (association football)|forward]], and has scored hat-tricks for NRT. He was declared \"[[Man of the Match]]\" in the WAVE Kick Off Cup 2006, and was one of the few who played the whole 90 minutes. Amatya is also an expert in [[tae kwon do]]. He has a Dan degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the sport, and is considered an expert in its theoretical aspects. Amatya also won medals in the sport when he was in the United States.\n\nAmatya gave his first performance at Mayur Chalchitra Mandir, [[Banepa]], while drunk. After the good response and encouragement from senior artists and friends, he started to sing for fun. He released his first album after encouragement and pestering from Brajesh Khanal and Prabhat Rimal. He dedicated the album to them and named it, in their honor, Karai Kara le.\n\nHe is fond of hunting. He is a [[pacifist]], but enjoys the thrill of the hunt. Amatya also enjoys interior designing. He took a course in interior design for 2 semesters from the School of Interior Designing in the USA.\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Compilation albums'''\n*''yogeshwor amatya jaba sandhya\n*''Bhanchan Logne Manche Bhayar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n*\n*{{cite news|url=http://jnepal.info/yogeshwor-amatya-collection/|title=yogeshwor-amatya-collection|publisher=jnepal.info|location=Nepal}}\n*\n* \n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amatya, Yogeshwar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{notability|biography|date=February 2015}}\n{{peacock|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Yogeshwar Amatya\n| image               =\n| caption             = Yogeshwar Amatya in Melancholy Song Recording at Radio Nepal Studio in 2016\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya\n| birth_place         = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| genre               = [[Soft rock]], [[pop rock]], [[folk music|folk]]\n| instrument          = Vocals guitar\n| occupation          = Singer<br> [[Composer]]<br>businessman<br> philanthropist\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Single Records|Single]] (Nepal)\n}}\n\n'''Yogeshwar Amatya''' (born Yogeshwor Prasad Amatya, 3 April) is a Nepali singer, musician, producer, actor, social activist, and photographer. Amatya has been a figure in Nepalese [[soft rock]] during the last two decades. He has sold more than 1 million records, making him one of [[List of best-selling music artists|Nepal's best-selling music artists]] and the best-selling [[Nepali rock]] artist of all time.\n\nAmatya came to fame in Nepal with his album ''Jaba Sandhya Hunchha'' and became more famous with his 1998 song ''Karai Kara Le''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nepalipopartist.blogspot.com/2007/10/yogeshwor-amatya.html | author = Thisaway | title = Profile of Nepali pop music artist..........: Yogeshwar Amatya | accessdate = 18 September 2010 | authorlink = Thisaway }}</ref> In 1998, he released his ''Ahile Chaahin Drabya Ko Aaasha Ma, Bastoo'' album which included ''Wakka Dikka''. Amatya also participated in [[Melancholy (song)|Melancholy]] song as a solo artist with 365 other Nepali singers and musician. The song set a [[Guinness World Record]] entitled \"Most Vocal Solos in a Song Recording\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-vocal-solos-in-a-song-recording|title=Most vocal solos in a song recording|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-05-29/nepali-house-hold-names-go-for-the-guinness-world-records.html|title=Nepali house-hold names go for the Guinness World Records|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/26897/|title=National poet Madhav Prasad Ghimire turns singer|first=Shreedhar|last=Pandey|website=My Republica|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYogeshwor Amatya has mentioned that he has nver received any formal training in music. He says, \"I never had any formal training regarding music... I guess I have to say that I don't have any musical background, except late night jamming with tons of beer with my buddies.\"<ref name=Telg3672213>{{cite news|url=http://www.interview.bagaicha.com/Yogeshwar-Amatya-71.html#sthash.15OZFMba.dpuf|title=Interview with Yogeshwar Amatya |author=keran limbu|publisher=bagaicha.com|date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=1 July 2011|location=Nepal}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nAmatya hasn't used his [[middle name]] since his father dropped it. His father, Bhuwaneshor Amatya, was the first President of Nepal Chalchitra Sangha. His mother, Lamu Amatya, was the first trained nurse in Nepal.\n\nHe was bullied by classmates while studying at [[St. Xavier's College, Kathmandu|St. Xavier's]] for his [[cleft lip]]. It got so out of hand that some of the seniors stole a guitar he had borrowed from his cousin. After that incident, he left the school and joined North Point, [[Darjeeling]].\n\nAmatya enjoys [[gemology|gems]], especially regarding [[gemstone|gem]] sets containing diamonds and [[emerald]]s. He has said if he'd not been a musician, he would have been a [[jeweler]]. Amatya has a [[bachelor's degree]] in Gemology from the Gemological Institute of [[India]], [[Bombay]].\n\nAmatya is a sportsman with expertise in some sports. He has played [[association football|football]] for Army (Shreenath Gana) and NRT at center [[Striker (association football)|forward]], and has scored hat-tricks for NRT. He was declared \"[[Man of the Match]]\" in the WAVE Kick Off Cup 2006, and was one of the few who played the whole 90 minutes. Amatya is also an expert in [[tae kwon do]]. He has a Dan degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in the sport, and is considered an expert in its theoretical aspects. Amatya also won medals in the sport when he was in the United States.\n\nAmatya gave his first performance at Mayur Chalchitra Mandir, [[Banepa]], while drunk. After the good response and encouragement from senior artists and friends, he started to sing for fun. He released his first album after encouragement and pestering from Brajesh Khanal and Prabhat Rimal. He dedicated the album to them and named it, in their honor, Karai Kara le.\n\nHe is fond of hunting. He is a [[pacifist]], but enjoys the thrill of the hunt. Amatya also enjoys interior designing. He took a course in interior design for 2 semesters from the School of Interior Designing in the USA.\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Compilation albums'''\n*''yogeshwor amatya jaba sandhya\n*''Bhanchan Logne Manche Bhayar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\n*\n*{{cite news|url=http://jnepal.info/yogeshwor-amatya-collection/|title=yogeshwor-amatya-collection|publisher=jnepal.info|location=Nepal}}\n*\n* \n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amatya, Yogeshwar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Sknepal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yogeshwar_Amatya"}
{"title_page": "Primacy of Peter", "text_new": "[[File:Peter_as_Pope_.png|thumb|180px|Saint Peter portrayed as a Pope in the ''[[Nuremberg Chronicle]]'' ]]\n{{Saint Peter}}\nThe '''primacy of Peter''', also known as '''Petrine primacy''' (from Latin: ''Petrus'', \"Peter\"), is the position of preeminence that is attributed to [[Saint Peter]] among the [[Apostle (Christian)|Twelve Apostles]].\n\nIt is to be distinguished from but forms the basis of the [[primacy of the Bishop of Rome]], also known as papal primacy or Roman primacy.\n\n== Primacy of Peter among the Apostles ==\n\nThe ''[[Evangelical Dictionary of Theology]]'' illustrates the leading role that Peter played among the Apostles, speaking up on matters that concern them all, being called by Jesus by a name linking him with the rock on which Jesus would build his church, being charged with pastoring the flock of Christ, and taking the leading role in the initial church as described in the [[Acts of the Apostles]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=yu846j61u0wC&pg=PA910 Walter A. Elwell (editor), ''Evangelical Dictionary of Theology''] (Baker Academic 2001 {{ISBN|978-0-80102075-9}}), entry \"Peter, Primacy of\"</ref>\n\nThere is general agreement among scholars on the preeminence that the historical Peter held among the [[Disciple (Christianity)|disciples]] of Jesus, making him \"the most prominent and influential member of the Twelve during Jesus' ministry and in the early Church\".<ref>Theodore Stylianopoulos \"Concerning the Biblical Foundation of Primacy\", in [https://books.google.com/books?id=K0sbuf37A_UC&pg=PA44 Walter Kasper (editor), ''The Petrine Ministry''] (Paulist Press 2008 {{ISBN|978-0-80914334-4}}), pp. 43\u201344, citing\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=6-LYAAAAMAAJ&dq=Meier+%22A+Marginal+Jew%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mX87VMa5GpKf7gai3IDQAw&redir_esc=y John P. Meier, ''A Marginal Jew. 3. Companions and Competitors''] (Knopf Doubleday 2001 {{ISBN|978-0-38546993-7}}), pp. 221\u2013225, and others.</ref>\n\nIn one interpretation the prominence that the [[New Testament]] and other early Christian writings attribute to Peter is due to their seeing him as a unifying factor in contrast to other figures identified with disputed interpretations of Christianity.<ref>\"For ''Peter was probably in fact and effect the bridge-man'' (pontifex maximus!) ''who did more than any other to hold together the diversity of first-century Christianity.'' James the brother of Jesus, and Paul of Tarsus, the two other most prominent leading figures in first-century Christianity, were too much identified with their respective \"brands\" of Christianity, at least in the eyes of Christians at the opposite ends of this particular spectrum. But Peter, as shown particularly by the Antioch episode in {{Bibleref2|Galatians|2}}, had both a care to hold firm to his Jewish heritage\u2014which Paul lacked\u2014and an openness to the demands of developing Christianity, which James lacked. John might have served as a figure of the center holding together the extremes, but if the writings linked with his name are at all indicative of his own stance, he was too much of an individualist to provide such a rallying point. Others could link the developing new religion more firmly to its founding events and to Jesus himself. But none of them, including the rest of the twelve, seem to have played any role of continuing significance for the whole sweep of Christianity\u2014though James the brother of John might have proved an exception had he been spared.\" [Italics original] [[James Dunn (theologian)|Dunn, James D.G.]] ''The Canon Debate''. McDonald & Sanders editors, 2002, ch. 32, p. 577.</ref>\n\n== Matthew 16:18 ==\n\nControversy has surrounded one particular text that is linked with the Aramaic nickname name \u05db\u05e4\u05d0 (''Cepha''), meaning \"rock,\" that Jesus gave the man previously known as Simon.{{Bibleref2c|John|1:42}} The Greeks translated it as \u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Petros''), a new form, appropriately masculine, of the standard feminine word \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 (''petra''), also meaning \"rock;\" and the Latins translated it as ''Petrus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/cephas |title=Cephas - Dictionary.com - Reference.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref>\n\nWhile the reasons for disagreement on the nature of the primacy are complex, hinging on matters of doctrine, history and politics, the debate is often reduced to a discussion of the meaning and translation of Matthew 16:18: \"And I say to thee: That thou art Peter; and upon this rock I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it.\" {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18, Douay-Rheims Bible}}\n\nIn the [[Greek language|Greek]] text, the new name given is \u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Petros''), and in the second half of the same verse the word translated as \"rock\" is \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 (''petra''). A literal translation, in the style of the [[King James Version]], of the words presumably used by Jesus would be \"Thou art Rock, and upon this rock will I build my church\".<ref>In [[French language|French]], the translation, \"Tu es ''Pierre'', et sur cette ''pierre'' je b\u00e2tirai mon \u00c9glise, et les portes de l'enfer ne pr\u00e9vaudront point contre elle\" preserves exactly the play on words in what is believed to be the original Aramaic.</ref> To preserve a supposed pun, the Greek text chose to translate Peter's name as \"\u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2\" rather than as \"\u039a\u03b7\u03c6\u1fb6\u03c2\" (Cephas).\n\nOne common Protestant argument historically has been that the translation from the [[New Testament]] in Hebrew into Greek is tenuous at best as there is no real evidence or indication that the New Testament (in Greek) was ever translated from Hebrew or Aramaic texts; for that argument see [[Aramaic primacy]]. According to the Protestant transliteration argument,{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}} in the [[Aramaic of Jesus|language that Jesus spoke]], the same word, \u05db\u05e4\u05d0 (cepha), was used for both Peter's name and for the rock on which Jesus said he would build his church. Since the [[Protestant Reformation]], many non-Catholics, in disagreement with the historic Catholic Church view, have disputed whether the feminine \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 refers to Peter, claiming it instead refers to either Peter's confession of faith or to Jesus himself.<ref name=Engler>John Engler. \"The Rock-Foundation of Matthew 16:17-20\". <http://www.greatcommission.com/Matthew161720.html> Accessed 12 Mar 2013</ref><ref name=Stagg>Stagg, Frank. ''New Testament Theology''. Broadman Press, 1962. {{ISBN|0-8054-1613-7}}</ref>\n\n==Catholic view on relationship to the Church today==\n{{Papal primacy and infallibility|expanded=overview}}\n\nIn [[Catholicism]], it is argued that the primacy of Peter is a basis for the primacy of the bishop of Rome over other [[bishops]] throughout the [[Roman Catholic Church|Church]] via the doctrine of [[Apostolic succession]]. This extension of Petrine primacy to popes is known as the [[primacy of the Bishop of Rome]], also known as the primacy of the Roman Pontiff. This Catholic Church doctrine holds that the [[pope|papacy]] has authority delegated from Jesus to rule over the [[Christendom|entire Church]]. There are various views on the nature of the primacy and how it has been exercised and [[Apostolic succession|passed on]]. This belief makes a distinction between the personal prestige of Peter and the supremacy of the office of [[pope]] which Catholics believe Jesus instituted in the person of Peter. Some,{{which|date=July 2019}} but not nearly all, [[Protestantism|Protestant denominations]] accept the concept of the primacy of Peter, but believe it was only relevant during the lifetime of Peter.{{cn|date=August 2019}} They do not believe the pope holds any authority over the [[Christian Church|universal Church]].\n\nSome [[Catholic Church|Catholics]] believe that [[Paul of Tarsus and Judaism|Saint Paul saw Judaism]] as the [[Typology (theology)|type]] or figure of [[Christianity]]: \"Now all these things happened to [the Jews] in figure....\"{{bibleref2c|1Cor|10:11||1 Cor. 10:11}} In the [[613 Mitzvot|Old Law]], {{bibleref2|Deut.|17:8-12}} attributes to the [[Kohen Gadol|High Priest]] the highest jurisdiction in religious matters. Therefore, it is argued, logic dictates that a supreme head would be necessary in the Christian Church,{{cn|date=August 2019}} though the relevance of [[Biblical law in Christianity]] is still disputed; see also [[New Covenant]] and [[The New Commandment|New Commandment]].\n\nIn the [[New Testament]], which some call the ''New Law'' or \"New Greek Testament\",<ref>Knight, Kevin. \"Question 106. The law of the Gospel, called the New Law, considered in itself.\" ''New Advent.'' Sept. 11, 2009: http://www.newadvent.org/summa/2106.htm</ref> {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:16-18}} reports that Jesus changed Simon's name to Peter. Elsewhere in Scripture such a name change always denotes some change in status (e.g., Abram to Abraham, Jacob to Israel, and Saul to Paul).\n\nJesus also said to Peter in verse 19, \"I will give to thee the [[Keys of Heaven|keys of the kingdom of heaven]].\" Especially for the Hebrew people, keys were a symbol of authority. Indeed, Jesus declares in the [[Book of Revelation]], that He has the \"keys of death and hell,\" which means that He has power over death and hell; {{Bibleref2|Isaiah|22:21-22}} also supports this. [[James Gibbons|Cardinal Gibbons]], in his book ''The Faith of Our Fathers'', points out that keys are still a symbol of authority in today's culture; he uses the example of someone giving the keys of his house to another person, and that the latter represented the owner of the house in his absence.\n\nAnother source indicating Peter's supremacy can be found in {{Bibleref2|John|21:15-17}} where Christ tells Peter three times to \"feed His sheep\" and \"feed His lambs.\" The \"sheep\" might be understood to be the stronger portion of Jesus' flock (the [[clergy]]), and the \"lambs\" as the weaker portion (the [[laity]]). From this, Catholics believe that Peter was given charge over Christ's whole flock, that is, the [[Catholic Church|Church]].\n\nMoreover, Peter is always named first in all listings of the Apostles; [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] is invariably mentioned last. In {{bibleref2|Matthew|10:2}} Peter is described as the \"first Apostle\". It is important to note that Peter was neither the first Apostle in age nor election; therefore, Peter must be the first Apostle in the sense of authority, if one ignores the possibility of him being first in the sense of first in the list of Twelve Apostles.{{bibleref2c|Mk.|3:16}} {{bibleref2c|Mt.|4:18-19}} According to {{bibleref2|Acts|1-2,10-11,15}}, St. Peter was the leader of the early Christian church in Jerusalem. Jesus also instructed St. Peter to strengthen his brethren, i.e., the apostles, according to {{bibleref2|Luke|22:31-32}}.\n\nBoth Latin and Greek writers in the early church (such as the St. [[John Chrysostom]]) referred to \"rock\" as applying to both Peter personally and his faith symbolically, as well as seeing Christ's promise to apply more generally to his twelve apostles and the Church at large.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\">{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 61\u201366}}</ref>\n\n[[First Vatican Council|Vatican Council I]] defined the primacy of the bishop of Rome over the whole Catholic Church as an essential institution of the Church that can never be relinquished. This primacy is thus crucial to the understanding of the church from a Catholic viewpoint. At the same time, the history of papal primacy has always been imperfect and much-debated.<ref>Schatz, Klaus.  Papal Primacy: From Its Origins to the Present.  Translated by John A. Otto and Linda M. Maloney.  Collegeville, MN: The Liturgical Press, 1996.  p. x.</ref> This is reflected in the [[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]:\n\n{{quote|'''424'''  Moved by the grace of the Holy Spirit and drawn by the Father, we believe in Jesus and confess: \"You are the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" On the rock of this faith confessed by St. Peter, Christ built his Church.|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n{{quote|'''552'''  Simon Peter holds the first place in the college of the Twelve; Jesus entrusted a unique mission to him. Through a revelation from the Father, Peter had confessed: \"You are the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" Our Lord then declared to him: \"You are Peter, and on this rock I will build my Church, and the gates of Hades will not prevail against it.\" Christ, the \"living Stone\", thus assures his Church, built on Peter, of victory over the powers of death. Because of the faith he confessed Peter will remain the unshakable rock of the Church. His mission will be to keep this faith from every lapse and to strengthen his brothers in it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P1D.HTM#-F1 |title=Cathecism of the Catholic Church |publisher=Vatican.va |accessdate=2012-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623214259/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P1D.HTM#-F1 |archivedate=2012-06-23 }}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nRegarding the Catholic interpretation of Matthew 16:18-19, [[Jaroslav Pelikan]] writes:<ref>{{cite book |last= Pelikan |first= Jaroslav |authorlink= Jaroslav Pelikan |editor= |others= |title= The Riddle of Roman Catholicism |year= 1959 |publisher= Abingdon Press |location= New York |page= 78}}</ref> \"As Roman Catholic scholars now concede, the ancient Christian father Cyprian used it to prove the authority of the bishop\u2014not merely of the Roman bishop, but of every bishop,\" referring to Maurice Bevenot's work on St. Cyprian.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bevenot |first= Maurice | title= St. Cyprian: The Lapsed, The Unity of the Catholic Church |pages= 6\u20138}}</ref>\n\n[[Eastern Catholic Churches|Eastern Catholics]] agree with the above, but also consider Peter to be representative of all bishops. In this, they represent a middle-ground between the Catholic position and that of the [[Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] in the next section.\n\nThough among the Twelve Peter is predominant in the first chapters of [[Acts of the Apostles]], [[James the Just|James \"the brother of the Lord\"]] is shown to be a leader in his own right in later chapters, indeed he is commonly considered the first [[Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem#Bishops of Jerusalem|Bishop of Jerusalem]]. Some assume James outranks Peter because he speaks last in the [[Council of Jerusalem]] and suggests the final ruling (concerning Gentile converts and Jewish practices such as [[Circumcision controversy in early Christianity|circumcision]]) agreed upon by all, and because Paul mentions him before Peter and John when he calls them \"pillars of the church\" in [[Jerusalem in Christianity|Jerusalem]]. James was indeed the first bishop or [[patriarch]] of Jerusalem according to tradition. However, Catholics believe the bishop of Jerusalem was not by that fact the head of the Christian church, since the leadership rested in Peter as the \"Rock\" and \"Chief Shepherd\".<ref>Mckenzie, John L. ''The Dictionary of the Bible'' (Catholic)</ref> It is believed Peter entrusted the Jerusalem community to James when he was forced to leave Jerusalem due to [[Herod Agrippa]]'s persecution. {{bibleref2c|Acts|12}}<ref>''The Navarre Bible'', footnotes</ref>\n\nHowever, at the Council of Jerusalem in Acts 15, James uses the Greek ''exegesato'' to refer to Peter's statements, which refers to literally \"declaring\" or \"issuing a ruling.\" <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EvQJ_i7J4CEC&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=exegesato+james&source=bl&ots=0T7FZfHbub&sig=MSPr7qcxxSLvgY1BDHdUgA3xu4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3mbqave7JAhUJlB4KHTVgDV0Q6AEIHjAA#v=onepage&q=exegesato%20james&f=false The Biblical Basis for the Papacy] by John Salza</ref> However, James uses the Greek word ''akouoo'' in relation to his statements, which refers to literally \"giving one's opinion,\" and does not denote authority. Catholic scholar Michael M. Winter puts it in his ''Saint Peter and the Popes'' in the following terms: \"The speech of St. James is of a different character [from that of St. Peter]. He acquiesces to what St. Peter had said, although it seems to have been against his personal inclinations, and then puts forward a practical suggestion for the sake of harmony.\"\n\nThe Fourth Century Latin Father St. Jerome, in his epistle to St. Augustine of Hippo, wrote that \"nay more, that Peter was the prime mover in issuing the decree by which this was affirmed,\" in relation to the Council of Jerusalem, and again, \"and to his opinion the Apostle James, and all the elders together, gave consent.\" <ref>http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/1102075.htm</ref>\n\nThis view is likewise echoed by Saint John Chrysostom, the Fourth Century Patriarch of Constantinople:\n\n{{quote|And why, then, passing by the others, does He converse with Peter on these things? (John 21:15). He was the chosen one of the Apostles, and the mouth of the disciples, and the leader of the choir. On this account, Paul also went up on a time to see him rather than the others (Galatians 1:18). And withal, to show him that he must thenceforward have confidence, as the denial was done away with, He puts into his hands the presidency over the brethren. And He brings not forward the denial, nor reproaches him with what had past, but says, \"If you love me, preside over the brethren.\" ...And the third time He gives him the same injunction, showing what a price He sets the presidency over His own sheep. And if one should say, \"How then did James receive the throne of Jerusalem?,\" this I would answer that He appointed this man (Peter) teacher, not of that throne, but of the whole world.<ref>http://www.catholicbridge.com/catholic/orthodox/pope_acts_15_james_and_peter.php</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nFor Catholics, the fact that the new name for Simon is Peter is in fact itself very significant. In the Old Testament God is frequently referred to as a Rock or stone. Jesus refers to himself as the cornerstone. The Book of Daniel contains a prophecy that a Rock or stone from the mountain of God (heaven) will come down to earth and destroy the pagan kings. The rock will then grow itself until it covers the entire earth. Protestants consider this prophecy to allude to the [[end times]] but Catholics consider the prophecy to refer specifically to Jesus as the Rock from Heaven. Further, Catholics see the fact that the Rock does not leave but stays to until it covers the entire earth to mean that the Church, built of the Rock of Peter, is the [[body of Christ]], the Rock from Heaven, and that the Rock will eventually cover the entire Earth which is why the term Catholic (universal or worldwide) is the most common designation for the Catholic Church.\n\n===Individuals and documents supporting Roman primacy===\n\n====Irenaeus====\n[[Irenaeus]] has been called the most important witness of the [[Christianity in the 2nd century|Christianity of the 2nd century]].<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 6.</ref> Taught by [[Polycarp]], who had been instructed by John the apostle, Irenaeus became [[Bishop of Lyon]] in 178. In his ''Against the Heresies'', Irenaeus wrote, \"Although there are many dialects in the world, the force of the tradition is one and the same. For the same faith is held and handed down by the churches established in the German states, the Spains, among the Celtic tribes, in the East, in Libya, and in the central portions of the world.\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 8.</ref> In Book 3, Irenaeus continues his defense of the unity of the church around the bishop, writing, \"By pointing out the apostolic tradition and faith announced to mankind, which has been brought down to our time by successions of bishops, in the greatest, most ancient, and well known church, founded and established by the two most glorious apostles, Peter and Paul, at Rome, we can confound all who in any other way \u2026 gather more than they ought.\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 9.</ref>\n\nIrenaeus asserted the Doctrine of Apostolic Succession to counter the claims of heretics, especially the Gnostics who were attacking the theology and authority of the mainstream Church. He stated that one could find true teaching in several leading episcopal sees, not just at Rome. The doctrine he asserted, therefore, has two parts: lineage from the Apostles and right teaching. Even today a bishop can be in the line of succession, but schismatic and heretical as is the case with many episcopi vagantes who claim to or may have Catholic Orders, but have no following and have deviated from the Catholic orthodox faith as defined by the larger denominations such as the Orthodox, Anglicans, Catholics and Lutherans.\n\n====Ignatius of Antioch====\n[[Ignatius of Antioch|Ignatius]], bishop of Antioch, was well known for his insistence on the authority of the bishop. In his writings to the church at [[Smyrna]] in 115 AD, he encouraged the Smyrnaeans to \"Avoid divisions, as the beginning of evil. Follow, all of you, the bishop, as Jesus Christ followed the father; and follow the presbytery as the apostles. Let no man do aught pertaining to the Church apart from the bishop. Wheresoever the bishop appears, there let the people be, even as wheresoever Christ Jesus is, there is the Catholic Church\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 4.</ref>\n\n====Tertullian====\nBorn in [[Carthage]] around 155 AD, [[Tertullian]] became a priest around the age of forty and worked tirelessly to defend the faith. In his Scorpiace of 208 AD, Tertullian wrote, \"No delay or inquest will meet Christians on the threshold\u2026 For though you think that heaven is still shut up, remember that the Lord left the keys of it to Peter here, and through him to the Church, which keys everyone will carry with him, if he has been questioned and made confession [of faith].\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 23.</ref> Scorpiace is the first known historical reference to the keys pertaining to anyone other than Peter. In it, he saw the keys as pertaining to \"everyone\" if they \"made confession\" rather than according to the modern interpretation concerning the bishops of Rome alone. Tertullian later retracted even this association in De Pudecitia,<ref>Schaff, Philip., American Ed., 1994. Alexander Roberts, D.D. & James Donaldson, LL.D. with notes by A. Cleveland Coxe, D.D.. AnteNicene Fathers: Fathers of the Third Century: Tertullian, Part Fourth; Minucius Felix; Commodian; Origen, Parts First and Second. On Modesty \"Chap. XXI - Of the difference Between Discipline and Power, and of the Power of the Keys.\" pp. 98-101. Published online at http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf04.iii.viii.xxi.html</ref> listing various reasons why the Keys of Peter pertained to Peter alone. The churches later declared him an apostate along with the followers of Montanus for insisting that authority must be associated with demonstrable power.\n\n====Cyprian====\n[[Cyprian|Thascius Caecilius Cyprianus]] was made bishop of Carthage in 248 AD. but died only ten years later. Throughout his writings, Cyprian asserts that the Rock is Peter, and the Church rests upon him. He also claims that as the Church is settled upon the bishops, they too have authority. He writes, \"They, who have departed from the Church, do not allow the Church to recall and bring back the lapsed. There is one God, and one Christ, and one Church, and one chair founded by the voice of the Lord on the rock. Another altar cannot be set up, nor a new priesthood made, besides the one altar and the one priesthood. Whoever gathers elsewhere scatters.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. pp. 29-30.</ref> In his 251 AD De Catholicae Ecclesiae Unitate, Cyprian asks, \"He who deserts the chair of Peter, upon whom the Church was founded, does he trust himself to be in the Church?\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 53.</ref>\n\n====John Chrysostom====\n[[John Chrysostom]] was born at [[Antioch]] around 347 and would fight for the reform of the church until his exile in 404. His homilies emphasize his belief in the primacy. St. Chrysostom called Peter \"the leader of the choir, the mouth of all the apostles, the head of that tribe, the ruler of the whole world, the foundation of the Church, the ardent lover of Christ\u2026\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 126.</ref> His writings also emphasize the mortality of Peter, linking him more closely to the people of the Church.\n\n====Augustine of Hippo====\n[[Saint Augustine]] was born in [[Numidia]] in 354 AD and was baptized in [[Milan]] in 387 AD. He was also bishop of Hippo from 397 AD til his death in 430 AD. Augustine taught that Peter was first amongst the apostles, and thus represents the church.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 163.</ref> His Sermo states, \"For Peter in many places in the Scriptures appears to represent the Church, especially in that place where it was said \"I give to thee the keys\u2026 shall be loosed in heaven\". What! did Peter receive these keys, and Paul not receive? Did Peter receive and John and James not receive, and the rest of the apostles? But since in a figure Peter represented the Church, what was given to him singly was given to the Church.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 175.</ref> His 395 A.D. Contra Epistolam Manichaei states, \"There are many other things which rightly keep me in the bosom of the Catholic Church\u2026 The succession of the priests keeps me, from the very seat of the apostle Peter (to whom the Lord after his resurrection gave charge to feed his sheep) down to the present episcopate.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 182.</ref>\n\n====Pope Innocent I====\n[[Pope Innocent I|Innocent I]] held the papal office from 402 to 417. Modern theories of Papal Primacy developed around Innocent and his writings. In a 416 AD letter to [[Decentius]], bishop of Eugubium, Innocent writes, \"Who does not know or observe that it [the church order] was delivered by Peter the chief of the apostles to the Roman church, and is kept until now, and ought to be retained by all, and that nothing ought to be imposed or introduced which has no authority, or seems to derive its precedents elsewhere?\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 194.</ref> It is also during this time that bishops began to recognize Innocent's primacy as Pope over other bishops in the West. This is made evident, among others, in a letter from the Council at Mileve to Innocent in 416 AD, which alludes the authority of \"his holiness\" drawn from the authority of Scripture.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 198.</ref> The doctrine of Primacy was beginning to take shape with Innocent's papacy.\n\n====Pope Leo I====\nBased on his knowledge of the Petrine texts of the Gospel, and his writings which expound upon it, it is easy to see that [[Pope Leo I|Leo I]] identified with the authority bestowed on Peter as bishop of Rome. Leo himself was consecrated bishop of Rome in 440 AD. He writes that \"The right of this power did indeed pass on to other apostles, and the order of this decree passed on to all the chiefs of the Church; but not in vain was that which was imparted to all entrusted but one. Therefore this is commended to Peter separately, because all the rulers of the Church are invested with the figure of Peter\u2026 So then in Peter the strength of all is fortified, and the help of divine grace is so ordered that the stability which through Christ is given to Peter, through Peter is conveyed to the apostles\" (Giles, 280). The [[Council of Chalcedon]] would later refer to Leo as \"him who had been charged with the custody of the vine by the savior.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 323.</ref>\n\n====Pope Gregory VII====\nThe [[Gregorian Reform|Gregorian Reform movement]] was rather a series of movements many of which involved the reform of the Catholic Church, headed by [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]], formerly the Archdeacon Hildebrand. Gregory became Pope in 1073 with the objective of reforming not the body of the church, but a purification of the clergy in general.<ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 101.</ref> Gregory is perhaps most recognized with the quarrel between himself and [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|King Henry IV]] of Germany, known as the \"[[Investiture Contest]]\". Gregory's Dictus Pape outlines his policies and ideals, as well as those of the Catholic Church. In this work, Gregory claims that the pope has power to depose and restore bishops, and also effectively reduces the authority of other bishops.<ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 129.</ref> This doctrine supported the idea that Rome and the church here also afforded primacy over all other churches. Gregory's papacy also bolstered the power of the Church over that of the State. The Gregorians defended the ideal of a separation of powers, claiming \"Let kings have what belongs to kings, and priests have what belongs to priests.\" <ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 133.</ref> The Petrine Primacy was now more affirmed than ever.\n\n===Challenges===\n\n====Councils====\nMany challenges faced the Popes claiming primacy throughout the history of Catholicism. The [[Edict of Milan]], the [[First Council of Nicaea|Council of Nicea]], and the [[First Council of Constantinople]] all dealt with the issue of primacy in that they amended the power of the popes over the other bishops. The third canon of the First Council of Constantinople of 381 AD declares Constantinople the new Rome, gives the Bishop of Rome the seat of honor and gives the Bishop of Constantinople second place in honor. The [[First Council of Ephesus|Council of Ephesus]] in 431 AD offers debate as to whether the results determine that the Pope is at the head of the Church, or rather that it is under the authority of a council of bishops (Giles, 238-256 AD). Although the highlight of the [[Council of Chalcedon]] in 451 AD was the confession of the [[Person of Christ]], the Council also resulted in limitations to the powers of the bishops. Many letters of the Council identify its position as in agreement with papal primacy. Those present employ titles such as \"the most holy and beloved of God\" and \"ecumenical archbishop and patriarch of great Rome\" to address Pope Leo. Thus, as not all can be satisfied with the results, The Council of Chalcedon resulted in a schism with the Oriental Orthodox Church.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 297-321.</ref>\n\n====Schism====\nInternally, people questioned who rightfully was pope, while others wondered as to the role the Pope was to play outside of Rome.<ref>Logan, F. Donald.  A History of the Church in the Middle Ages.  New York: Routledge, 2002. p. 133.</ref> The papacy's most widely known crisis, as well as its largest challenge to authority, came with the \"[[Western Schism]]\" in the late Middle Ages, dating from 1378\u20131417.<ref>Schatz, Klaus.  Papal Primacy: From Its Origins to the Present.  Translated by John A. Otto and Linda M. Maloney.  Collegeville, MN: The Liturgical Press, 1996.  p. 100.</ref> Seven popes ruled from Avignon in France in the early 14th century, until Gregory XI risked returning to turbulent Italy and the Roman seat.<ref>Logan, F. Donald.  A History of the Church in the Middle Ages.  New York: Routledge, 2002. p. 297.</ref> Following the close of the [[Avignon papacy]] in 1377, [[Urban VI]], an Italian, took the reins over a predominantly French college of Cardinals. The Cardinals called the election into question and elected [[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]] as Pope. Germany, Italy, England, and the rest of Northern and Eastern Europe remained loyal to Urban, while France, Spain, Scotland, and Rome followed Clement VII (1378\u20131394) and his successor, [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]] (1394&ndash;1417) who would reside in Avignon.\n\n==Eastern Orthodox view on relationship to the Church today==\n\n===Many hold the ''Primacy'' of Peter===\n[[File:StPeter-RussianMuseum.jpg|thumb|[[Icon]] of St. Peter (15th century, [[Russian State Museum]], [[Saint Petersburg]]).]]\n\nThe [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] regards the Apostle Peter, together with the Apostle Paul, as \"preeminent apostles\". Another title used for Peter is ''Coryphaeus'', which could be translated as \"Choir-director,\" or lead singer.<ref>[[John Meyendorff]], et al. (1963), ''The Primacy of Peter in the Orthodox Church'' ([[St. Vladimir's Seminary]] Press, Crestwood NY, {{ISBN|978-0-88141-125-6}})</ref>\n\nOrthodox scholars follow St. John Chrysostom and the Byzantine<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 67\u201390}}</ref> tradition in seeing Peter as the icon of the episcopate<ref>{{cite book|title=His Broken Body: Understanding and Healing the Schism between the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches|author=Cleenewerck Laurent|year=2008|publisher=EUC Press|id= |pages= 257\u2013263}} {{Self-published source|date=June 2015}}</ref> with his title of protos (first) implying a certain level of authority over the other apostles. In this traditional Orthodox and Patristic view, the Church is the local Eucharistic assembly (\"the diocese\" in today's terminology) and the one who holds the \"Chair of Peter\" (St. Cyprian's expression) is the bishop. As a result, the primacy of Peter is relevant to the relationship between the bishop and the presbyters, not between the bishop of Rome and the other bishops who are all equally holding Peter's chair.\n\nAs John Meyendorff explained:\n\n{{quote|A very clear patristic tradition sees the succession of Peter in the episcopal ministry. The doctrine of St Cyprian of Carthage on the \"See of Peter\" being present in every local Church, and not only in Rome, is well-known. It is also found in the East, among people who certainly never read the De unitate ecclesia of Cyprian, but who share its main idea, thus witnessing to it as part of the catholic tradition of the Church. St Gregory of Nyssa, for example, affirms that Christ \"through Peter gave to the bishops the keys of the heavenly honors,\" and the author of the Areopagitica, when speaking of the \"hierarchs\" of the Church, refers immediately to the image of St Peter. A careful analysis of ecclesiastical literature both Eastern and Western, of the first millennium, including such documents as the lives of the saint, would certainly show that this tradition was a persistent one; and indeed it belongs to the essence of Christian ecclesiology to consider any local bishop to be the teacher of his flock and therefore to fulfill sacramentally, through apostolic succession, the office of the first true believer, Peter... There exists, however, another succession, equally recognized by Byzantine theologians, but only on the level of the analogy existing between the apostolic college and the episcopal college, this second succession being determined by the need for ecclesiastical order. Its limits are determined by the Councils, and - in the Byzantine practice \u2013 by the \"very pious emperors.\"|''The Primacy of Peter'', p. 89}}\n\nThe notion that many [[Episcopal see|Sees]] were \u2018\u2019of Peter\u2019\u2019 had also once been held in the West:\n\n[[Pope Gregory I|Pope Gregory the Great]]\n{{quote|Your most sweet Holiness has spoken much in your letter to me about the chair of Saint Peter, Prince of the apostles, saying that he himself now sits on it in the persons of his successors...Wherefore though there are many apostles, yet with regard to the principality itself the See of the Prince of the apostles alone has grown strong in authority, which in three places is the See of one...He himself stablished (sic) the See in which, though he was to leave it, he sat for seven years. Since then it is the See of one, and one See, over which by Divine authority three bishops now preside, whatever good I hear of you, this I impute to myself.<ref>\u2019\u2019To Eulogius, Bishop of Alexandria\u2019\u2019Book VII, Epistle XL</ref>}}\n\nConsequently, Eastern and Oriental Orthodox do not recognize the Bishop of Rome as the unique successor of St. Peter and consider him to be in a state of schism and heresy. However, the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] sends a delegation each year to Rome to participate in the celebration of the feast of Sts. Peter and Paul.\n\nThe Orthodox also consider that [[Pope Linus|St. Linus]], not Peter, was actually the first [[Bishop of Rome]].\n{{quote|Of the church of Rome, Linus the son of Claudia was the first, ordained by Paul; and Clemens (Clement), after Linus' death, the second, ordained by me Peter.<ref>\u2019\u2019Apostolic Teaching and Constitutions\u2019\u2019, Book 7, Chapter XLVI \u2013 \"Who Were They that the Holy Apostles Sent and Ordained?\"</ref>}}\n\n===''Keys'' and ''rock'' not exclusive to Peter===\n[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] theologians agree that in {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}, \"rock\" is a likely reference to Peter personally since the very name \"Peter\" means \"rock.\".<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 47\u201348}}</ref> However {{bibleref2|Matthew|18:18}} implies that the other Apostles were given the same powers. Although the word ''keys'' is ''explicitly'' absent from this later verse a number of [[Church Fathers]] recognised that the meaning of ''keys'' is ''implicitly'' there; that the rest of the church has the keys:\n\n[[Tertullian]]\n{{quote|What, now, (has this to do) with the Church, and) your (church), indeed, Psychic? For, in accordance with the person of Peter, it is to spiritual men that this power will correspondently appertain, either to an apostle or else to a prophet.<ref>\u2019\u2019On Modesty\u2019\u2019. Book VII. Chapter XXI</ref>}}\n\n[[Hilary of Poitiers]]\n{{quote|This faith it is which is the foundation of the Church; through this faith the gates of hell cannot prevail against her. This is the faith which has the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatsoever this faith shall have loosed or bound on earth shall be loosed or bound in heaven. This faith is the Father's gift by revelation; even the knowledge that we must not imagine a false Christ, a creature made out of nothing, but must confess Him the Son of God, truly possessed of the Divine nature<ref>\u2018\u2019On the Trinity\u2019\u2019. Book VI.37</ref>}}\n\n[[John Chrysostom]]\n{{quote|For ([[John the Apostle|John]]) the Son of thunder, the beloved of Christ, the pillar of the Churches throughout the world, who holds the keys of heaven, who drank the cup of Christ, and was baptized with His baptism, who lay upon his Master's bosom, with much confidence, this man now comes forward to us now<ref>''Homilies on the Gospel of John.'' Preface to Homily 1.2</ref>}}\n\n[[Augustine]]\n{{quote|He has given, therefore, the keys to His Church, that whatsoever it should bind on earth might be bound in heaven, and whatsoever it should loose on earth might be, loosed in heaven; that is to say, that whosoever in the Church should not believe that his sins are remitted, they should not be remitted to him; but that whosoever should believe and should repent, and turn from his sins, should be saved by the same faith and repentance on the ground of which he is received into the bosom of the Church. For he who does not believe that his sins can be pardoned, falls into despair, and becomes worse as if no greater good remained for him than to be evil, when he has ceased to have faith in the results of his own repentance.<ref>\u2019\u2019On Christian Doctrine\u2019\u2019 Book I. Chapter 18.17 \u2018\u2019The Keys Given to the Church\u2019\u2019.</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|...Peter, the first of the apostles, receive the keys of the kingdom of heaven for the binding and loosing of sins; and for the same congregation of saints, in reference to the perfect repose in the bosom of that mysterious life to come did the evangelist John recline on the breast of Christ. For it is not the former alone but the whole Church, that bindeth and looseth sins; nor did the latter alone drink at the fountain of the Lord's breast, to emit again in preaching, of the Word in the beginning, God with God, and those other sublime truths regarding the divinity of Christ, and the Trinity and Unity of the whole Godhead.<ref>\u2019\u2019On the Gospel of John\u2019\u2019. Tractate CXXIV.7</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|...the keys that were given to the Church,<ref>\u2019\u2019A Treatise Concerning the Correction of the Donatists.\u2019\u2019 Chapter 10.45</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|How the Church? Why, to her it was said, \"To thee I will give the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatsoever thou shall loose on earth shall be loosed in heaven, and whatsoever thou shall bind on earth shall be bound in heaven.\"<ref>''Ten Homilies on the First Epistle of John''. Homily X.10</ref>}}\n\nMoreover, Eastern Orthodox theologians follow such Fathers as St. John Chrysostom by clarifying that \"rock\" simultaneously refers to Peter (instrumentally) as well as Peter's confession of faith which is what has ultimate significance in establishing the Church.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\"/>\n\nSome Orthodox scholars do not see Peter as being in any way above the other apostles, arguing that Peter did not have power and authority over them during Christ's public ministry. There were no positions of power between the twelve, only \"degrees of intimacy\" or \"degrees of honor.\" According to this view, Peter has a weak symbolic primacy or primacy of honor (in the sense of a purely honorary primacy). In the patristic era, this was actually the Western view held by St Augustine. Others (see above), following the traditional Byzantine view of St John Chrysostom see Peter as the icon of the bishop and therefore endowed with authority in the Church (i.e. the diocese).\n\n[[Tertullian]]\n{{quote|Come now, you who would indulge a better curiosity, if you would apply it to the business of your salvation, run over the apostolic churches, in which the very thrones of the apostles are still pre-eminent in their places, in which their own authentic writings are read, uttering the voice and representing the face of each of them severally. Achaia is very near you, (in which) you find Corinth. Since you are not far from Macedonia, you have Philippi; (and there too) you have the Thessalonians. Since you are able to cross to Asia, you get Ephesus. Since, moreover, you are close upon Italy, you have Rome, from which there comes even into our own hands the very authority (of apostles themselves). How happy is its church, on which apostles poured forth all their doctrine along with their blood! where Peter endures a passion like his Lord's! where Paul wins his crown in a death like John's where the Apostle John was first plunged, unhurt, into boiling oil, and thence remitted to his island-exile!<ref>\u2018\u2019The Prescription Against Heretics\u2019\u2019: Chapter XXXVI.-The Apostolic Churches the Voice of the Apostles. Let the Heretics Examine Their Apostolic Claims, in Each Case, Indisputable. The Church of Rome Doubly Apostolic; Its Early Eminence and Excellence. Heresy, as Perverting the Truth, is Connected Therewith</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Was anything withheld from the knowledge of Peter, who is called \"the rock on which the church should be built,\" who also obtained \"the keys of the kingdom of heaven,\" with the power of \"loosing and binding in heaven and on earth?\" Was anything, again, concealed from John, the Lord's most beloved disciple, who used to lean on His breast to whom alone the Lord pointed Judas out as the traitor, whom He commended to Mary as a son in His own stead?<ref>\u2018\u2019The Prescription Against Heretics\u2019\u2019:Chapter XXII.-Attempt to Invalidate This Rule of Faith Rebutted. The Apostles Safe Transmitters of the Truth. Sufficiently Taught at First, and Faithful in the Transmission.</ref>}}\n\n[[John Chrysostom]]\n{{quote|As a king sending forth governors, gives power to cast into prison and to deliver from it, so in sending these forth, Christ investeth them with the same power.<ref>\"On the Gospel of John\" On John xx. 10, 11. (Homily LXXXVI)</ref>}}\n\n[[Pope Leo I]]\n{{quote|... though He has delegated the care of His sheep to many shepherds, yet He has not Himself abandoned the guardianship of His beloved flock.<ref>\u2019\u2019Sermon III\u2019\u2019. (On His Birthday, III: Delivered on the Anniversary of His Elevation to the Pontificate, Chapter II)</ref>}}\n\n===Proofs from the Bible===\nOther biblical texts seem to suggest that Peter was not ''head of the church'' in any ''de jure'' sense. {{bibleref2|Acts|15:1-21}} shows the apostles considering a question by means of calling a Council. Although Peter is mentioned as speaking first, and all are silent - all are silent too when Paul speaks. Further if Peter's pronouncement was authoritative then Paul speaking afterwards would be superfluous; given that the 'decision' had already been made.\n\nEquality of all the Apostles is shown in {{bibleref2|Ephesians|2:19-20}}; that all the Apostles together are the foundation of the church.\n\n{{bibleref2|Galatians|2:7}} shows that Paul taught in the same terms as Peter did.\n\nThe ''forgiveness of sins'' (one of the powers of ''the keys'') is granted to many {{bibleref2|John|20:23}} and, {{bibleref2|Matthew|18:19}}.\n\n===Examples from history===\nOrthodox historians also maintain that Rome's authority in the early Eastern Roman (or Byzantine) empire was recognized only partially because of Rome's Petrine character, and that this factor was not the decisive issue. Moreover, the Orthodox view is that Rome's privileges were not understood as an absolute power (i.e., the difference between primacy and supremacy). In the East, there were numerous \"apostolic sees\", Jerusalem being considered the \"mother of all churches,\" and the bishop of Antioch could also claim the title of successor to Peter, being that Peter was the first [[List of Patriarchs of Antioch|bishop of Antioch]]. \"Canon 28 of [[Council of Chalcedon|Chalcedon]] was for [the Byzantines] one of the essential texts for the organization of the Church: 'It is for right reasons that the accorded privileges to old Rome, for this city was the seat of the Emperor and the Senate.' ... The reason why the Roman Church had been accorded an incontestable precedence over all other apostolic churches was that its Petrine and Pauline 'apostolicity' was in fact added to the city's position as the capital city, and only the conjunction of both of these elements gave the Bishop of Rome the right to occupy the place of a primate in the Christian world with the consensus of all the churches.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |page= 68}}</ref>\n\n==Protestant views on relationship to the Church today==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = Saint Raphael Catholic Church (Springfield, Ohio) - stained glass, Upon this Rock, detail - St. Peter's Basilica.jpg\n | caption1 = Stained glass window in a Catholic church depicting [[St. Peter's Basilica]] in Rome sitting \"Upon this rock,\" a reference to [[:s:Bible (King James)/Matthew#Chapter 16|Matthew 16]]:18. Most present-day Catholics interpret Jesus as saying he was building his church on the rock of the Apostle Peter and the succession of popes which claim Apostolic succession from him.\n\n | image2 = AugsburgConfessionArticle7OftheChurch.jpg\n | caption2 = A 17th century illustration of [[:s:Augsburg Confession#Article VII: Of the Church.|Article VII: Of the Church]] from the ''Augsburg Confession'', which states \"...one holy Church is to continue forever. The Church is the congregation of saints, in which the Gospel is rightly taught and the Sacraments are rightly administered.\" Here the rock from Matthew 16:18 refers to the preaching and ministry of Jesus as the Christ, a view discussed at length in the 1537 ''[[Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope|Treatise]]''.<ref>[http://bookofconcord.org/treatise.php#para22 ''Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope, paragraph 22''] and following</ref>}}\n\nA major debate between Catholics and [[Protestants]] centers on Matthew 16:18 where Jesus tells Peter: \"You are ''Peter'', and on this ''rock'' I will build my Church....\" Catholics interpret the verse as saying that Jesus would build his church on Peter, the apostle: Jesus told Peter (Rock) that he would build his Church on this Rock (Peter), and that Peter was made the shepherd of the apostolic flock{{Bibleref2c|Jn|21:15-19}}\u2014hence their assertion of the Primacy of the Catholic Pontiff.\n\nOne Protestant view on the Matthew verse agrees with the Catholic view and again the disagreements about primacy stem from doctrinal sources, and disagreements such as those over the identification of Simon Peter with the Pope.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Other Protestants assert the following,{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} based specifically on the verse in Matthew:\n\nJesus gives Simon the new name ''petros''. However he refers to the \"rock\" as ''petra''. The inspired New Testament Scriptures were written in Greek, not Aramaic. [[Aramaic of Jesus|What Jesus ''might'' have said in Aramaic]] is conjecture. In Greek, there is a distinction between the two words, \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 being a \"rock\" but \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 being a \"small stone\" or \"pebble\". (James G. McCarthy translates the two as \"mass of rock\" and \"boulder or detached stone\", respectively.){{Citation needed|date=March 2015}} Jesus is not referring to Peter when talking about \"this rock\", but is in fact referring to Peter's confession of faith in the preceding verses{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}. Jesus thus does not declare the primacy of Peter, but rather declares that his church will be built upon the foundation of the revelation of and confession of faith of Jesus as the Christ{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}.\n\nMany Protestant scholars, however, reject this position,{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}} <!-- Many, or one? --> such as Craig L. Blomberg who states, \"The expression \u2018this rock\u2019 almost certainly refers to Peter, following immediately after his name, just as the words following \u2018the Christ\u2019 in verse 16 applied to Jesus. The play on words in the Greek between Peter's name (Petros) and the word \u2018rock\u2019 (petra) makes sense only if Peter is the Rock and if Jesus is about to explain the significance of this identification.\" [New American Commentary: {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1998/9801word.asp |title=PETER IS THE ROCK (This Rock: January 1998) |publisher=Catholic.com |accessdate=2012-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726101430/http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1998/9801word.asp |archivedate=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nDonald A. Carson III (Baptist and Professor of New Testament at Trinity Evangelical Seminary) states:\n{{quote|Although it is true that ''petros'' and ''petra'' can mean \"stone\" and \"rock\" respectively in earlier Greek, the distinction is largely confined to poetry. Moreover the underlying Aramaic is in this case unquestionable; and most probably ''kepha'' was used in both clauses (\"you are ''kepha''\" and \"on this ''kepha''\"), since the word was used both for a name and for a \"rock\". The Peshitta (written in Syriac, a language cognate with Aramaic) makes no distinction between the words in the two clauses. The Greek makes the distinction between ''petros'' and ''petra'' simply because it is trying to preserve the pun, and in Greek the feminine ''petra'' could not very well serve as a masculine name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://users.stargate.net/~elcore/kephas.htm |title=Who is the Rock? |publisher=Users.stargate.net |accessdate=2012-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216055823/http://users.stargate.net/~elcore/kephas.htm |archivedate=2012-02-16 }}</ref>}}\n\nAn alternate Protestant argument is that when Jesus said \"upon this rock\" in the aforementioned Matthew verse, he referred to himself, in reference to {{Bibleref2|Deuteronomy|32:3-4}}, which states that \"God...is the Rock, his work is perfect\". This idea also appears in {{Bibleref2|1 Corinthians|10:4}}, which says \"...that Rock is Christ.\" In {{Bibleref2|Ephesians|2:20}}, Jesus is called \"the chief cornerstone\".\n\n===Meaning of \"Rock\"===\n\nIn the original [[Greek language|Greek]] the word translated as \"Peter\" is ''\u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2'' (Petros) and that translated as \"rock\" is ''\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1'' (petra), two words that, while not identical, give an impression of one of many times when Jesus used a play on words. Furthermore, since Jesus presumably spoke to Peter in their native [[Aramaic language]],{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} he would have used ''kepha'' in both instances.<ref name=\"keating\">{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.com/magazine/articles/peter-the-rock |title=Peter the Rock |publisher=Catholic Answers Magazine |date=October 1999 |accessdate=2012-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601121017/http://www.catholic.com/magazine/articles/peter-the-rock |archive-date=2016-06-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Peshitta Text and the Old Syriac text use the word \"kepha\" for both \"Peter\" and \"rock\" in {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peshitta.org/pdf/Mattich16.pdf |title=Peshitta Aramaic/English Interlinear New Testament|date= |accessdate=2012-07-22}}</ref> {{Bibleref2|John|1:42}} says Jesus called Simon \"Cephas\", as does Paul in some letters.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} He was instructed by Christ to strengthen his brethren, i.e., the apostles.{{Bibleref2c|Lk|22:31-32}} Peter also had a leadership role in the early Christian church at Jerusalem according to The Acts of the Apostles chapters 1\u20132, 10\u201311, and 15.\n\nEarly Catholic Latin and Greek writers (such as St. [[John Chrysostom]]) considered the \"foundation rock\" as applying to both Peter personally and his confession of faith (or the faith of his confession) symbolically, as well as seeing Christ's promise to apply more generally to his twelve apostles and the Church at large.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\"/> This \"double meaning\" interpretation is present in the current ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]''.<ref>''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'', Articles 424 and 552</ref>\n\nProtestant counter-claims to the Catholic interpretation are largely based on the difference between the Greek words translated \"Rock\" in the Matthean passage. In classical Attic Greek ''petros'' generally meant \"pebble,\" while ''petra'' meant \"boulder\" or \"cliff.\" Accordingly, taking Peter's name to mean \"pebble,\" they argue that the \"rock\" in question cannot have been Peter, but something else, either Jesus himself, or the faith in Jesus that Peter had just professed. However, the New Testament was written in Koin\u00e9 Greek, not Attic Greek, and some authorities say no significant difference existed between the meanings of ''petros'' and ''petra''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n[[File:Gesupietrochiave.jpg|thumb|left|''Christ Handing the Keys to St Peter'', by [[Pietro Perugino]] (1481\u201382)]]\nHowever, even though the feminine noun ''petra'' is translated as ''rock'' in the phrase \"on this rock I will build my church,\" the word ''petra'' (\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 in Greek) is also used at {{Bibleref2|1Cor|10:4||1 Cor. 10:4}} in describing Jesus Christ, which reads: \"They all ate the same spiritual food and drank the same spiritual drink; for they drank from the spiritual rock that accompanied them, and that rock was Christ.\"\n\nAlthough {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16}} is used as a primary proof-text for the Catholic doctrine of Papal supremacy, Protestant scholars say that prior to the Reformation of the sixteenth century, Matthew 16 was very rarely used to support papal claims. Their position is that most of the early and medieval Church interpreted the 'rock' as being a reference either to Christ or to Peter's faith, not Peter himself. They understand Jesus' remark to have been his affirmation of Peter's testimony that Jesus was the Son of God.<ref>Mathison, Keith A., [https://books.google.com/books?id=w_PHAGr2TfgC ''The Shape of Sola Scriptura''], pp.184\u2013185</ref>\n\nAnother rebuttal of the Catholic position is that if ''Peter'' really means ''the Rock'' which makes him the chief of Apostles, it would contradict Bible's teaching in {{Bibleref2|Ephesians|2:20}} which says that the church's foundation is the apostles and prophets, not Peter alone. They posit that the meaning of {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}} is that Jesus uses a play on words with Peter's name to say that the confession he had just made is the rock on which the church is built.<ref name=WELS-ROCK>{{cite web |url=http://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=813&cuItem_itemID=24624 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927075835/http://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=813&cuItem_itemID=24624 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=Matthew 16:18 - Peter, This Rock |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOther theologically conservative Christians, including Confessional Lutherans, also rebut comments made by Karl Keating and D.A. Carson who claim that there is no distinction between the words ''petros'' and ''petra'' in Koine Greek. The Lutheran theologians<ref>Danker, Frederick W., ''The concise Greek-English lexicon of the New Testament'', p. 282.</ref> state that the dictionaries of [[Koine Greek|Koine/NT Greek]], including the authoritative<ref>Rykle Borger, \"Remarks of an Outsider about Bauer's Worterbuch, BAGD, BDAG, and Their Textual Basis,\" Biblical Greek Language and Lexicography: Essays in Honor of Frederick W. Danker, Bernard A. Tayler (et al. eds.) pp. 32\u201347.</ref> [[Bauer lexicon|Bauer-Danker-Arndt-Gingrich Lexicon]], indeed list both words and the passages that give different meanings for each. Conservative Lutheran apologists state:\n\n{{quote|There is no biblical or historical evidence for the claims of the Roman Catholic church that Peter was the first pope. In fact there is no evidence that there even was a pope in the first century. Even Catholic historians recognize this as a historical fact....We honor Peter and in fact some of our churches are named after him, but he was not the first pope, nor was he Roman Catholic. If you read his first letter, you will see that he did not teach a Roman hierarchy, but that all Christians are royal priests.<ref name=WELS>{{cite web |url=https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=6106 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927214241/https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=6106 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=Responses to previous questions... |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Partial Protestant support===\n\nPartial support for the Catholic position comes from [[Oscar Cullmann]]. He disagrees with Luther and the Protestant reformers who held that by \"rock\" Christ did not mean Peter, but meant either himself or the faith of His followers. He believes the meaning of the original Aramaic is very clear: that \"Kepha\" was the Aramaic word for \"rock\", and that it was also the name by which Christ called Peter.<ref name=Time/>\n\nYet, Cullmann sharply rejects the Catholic claim that Peter began the papal succession. He writes: \"In the life of Peter there is no starting point for a chain of succession to the leadership of the church at large.\" While he believes the Matthew text is entirely valid and is in no way spurious, he says it cannot be used as \"warrant of the papal succession.\"<ref name=Time>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,890753-1,00.html Religion: Peter & the Rock.]\" \"Time,\" Dec. 07, 1953. Accessed Oct. 08, 2009</ref>\n\nCullmann concludes that while Peter ''was'' the original head of the apostles, Peter was not the founder of any visible church succession.<ref name=Time/>\n\nThere are other Protestant scholars who also partially defend the historical Catholic position about \"Rock.\"<ref>D. A. Carson in ''The Expositor's Bible Commentary'' (Grand Rapids: Zondervan, 1984).</ref> Taking a somewhat different approach from Cullman, they point out that the Gospel of Matthew was not written in the classical Attic form of Greek, but in the Hellenistic [[Koine Greek|Koine dialect]] in which there is no distinction in meaning between ''petros'' and ''petra''. Moreover, even in Attic Greek, in which the regular meaning of ''petros'' was a smallish \"stone,\" there are instances of its use to refer to larger rocks, as in [[Sophocles]], ''[[Oedipus at Colonus]]'' v. 1595, where ''petros'' refers to a boulder used as a landmark, obviously something more than a pebble. In any case, a ''petros''/''petra'' distinction is irrelevant considering the Aramaic language in which the phrase might well have been spoken. In Greek, of any period, the feminine noun ''petra'' could not be used as the given name of a male, which may explain the use of ''Petros'' as the Greek word with which to translate Aramaic ''Kepha''.<ref name=\"keating\" />\n\nYet, still other Protestant scholars believe that Jesus in fact ''did'' mean to single out Peter as the very rock which he will build upon, but that the passage does nothing to indicate a continued succession of Peter's implied position. They assert that Matthew uses the demonstrative pronoun ''taute'', which allegedly means \"this very\" or ''this same'', when he refers to the rock on which Jesus' church will be built. He also uses the Greek word for \"and\", ''kai''. It is alleged that when a demonstrative pronoun is used with ''kai'', the pronoun refers back to the preceding noun. The second rock Jesus refers to must then be the same rock as the first one; and if Peter is the first rock he must also be the second.<ref>''Jesus, Peter & the Keys: A Scriptural Handbook on the Papacy''</ref>\n\nThe [[New Apostolic Church]] believes in the re-established Apostle ministry. It sees Peter as the first [[Chief Apostle]] in the [[Early Church]].\n\n===Lutheran view===\nFrom the ''[[Book of Concord]]'': {{quote|Chrysostom says thus: \"Upon this rock,\" not upon Peter. For He built His Church not upon man, but upon the faith of Peter. But what was his faith? \"Thou art the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" And Hilary says: To Peter the Father revealed that he should say, \"Thou art the Son of the living God.\" Therefore, the building of the Church is upon this rock of confession; this faith is the foundation of the Church. \"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookofconcord.org/treatise.php |title=Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope |publisher=Book of Concord |date= |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref>}}\n\nUnlike Oscar Cullmann, [[Confessional Lutherans]] and many other Protestant apologists agree that it's meaningless to elaborate the meaning of ''Rock'' by looking at the Aramaic language, this is true that the Jews spoke mostly Aramaic at home, however in public they usually spoke Greek. The few Aramaic words spoken by Jesus in public were unusual and that is why they are noted as such. And most importantly the New Testament was revealed in Koine Greek, ''not'' Aramaic.<ref name=WLS-Gawrisch>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/GawrischDoctrine.pdf |title=The Doctrine of Church and Ministry in the Life of the Church Today |last1=Gawrisch |first1=Wilbert R. |date=5 Aug 1991 |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203191915/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/GawrischDoctrine.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-03 }}</ref><ref name=WLS-Balge>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/BalgeMinistry.pdf \n |title=Cross-Cultural And Multicultural Ministry In The New Testament \n |last1=Balge \n |first1=Richard D. \n |date=6 June 1995 \n |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary \n |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203192344/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/BalgeMinistry.pdf \n |archivedate=2015-02-03 \n}}</ref><ref>[http://www.graceway.com/articles/article_017.htm ''Some thoughts on Matthew 16:18''] {{Dead link|date=February 2015}}</ref>\n\nModern Lutheran historians even disclose that the Catholic church didn't, at least unanimously, regard Peter as the ''Rock'' until the 1870s:\n\n{{quote|Rome's rule for explaining the Scriptures and determining doctrine is the [[Profession of faith (Catholic Church)#Tridentine Creed|Creed]] of [[Pius IV]]. This Creed binds Rome to explain the Scriptures only according to the unanimous consent of the Fathers. In the year 1870 when the Fathers gathered and the pope declared his infallibility, the cardinals were not in agreement on Matthew 16, 18. They had five different interpretations. Seventeen insisted, Peter is the rock. Sixteen held that Christ is the rock. Eight were emphatic that the whole apostolic college is the rock. Forty-four said, Peter's faith is the rock, The remainder looked upon the whole body of believers as the rock. \u2014 And yet Rome taught and still teaches that Peter is the rock.<ref name=WLS-Eckert>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/EckertSpecific.pdf |title=The Specific Functions of the Church in the World |last1=Eckert |first1=Harold H. |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203182715/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/EckertSpecific.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-03 }}</ref>}}\n\nLutheran apologists criticize:\n\n{{quote|All of the arguments Roman Catholicism brings to set Peter up as the first Pope are done only to uphold its false teaching which says that people are saved, not by Christ's saving alone, but also by the deeds of penance they do. It is this teaching, which Roman Catholicism says has been taught by Popes ever since Peter, which also gives us the reason for the way Roman Catholicism interprets Mt 16:18.<ref name=WELS8752>{{cite web |url=https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=8572 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927213504/https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=8572 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=And On THIS ROCK I Will Build My Church... |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\n==View of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints==\n[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS) accept the primacy of Peter, although it does not generally use the term. The LDS Church teaches that Peter was the chief apostle and head of the Church after Christ's ascension. The LDS Church further teaches that all [[Melchizedek Priesthood]] authority in the Church must come through a line of authority traceable directly from Christ through Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1996/12/the-restoration-of-the-aaronic-and-melchizedek-priesthoods?lang=eng|title = The Restoration of the Aaronic and Melchizedek Priesthoods}}</ref> However, in contrast to other groups, they believe that the line of succession was at some point broken following the death of the apostles, necessitating a restoration of the priesthood authority. The LDS Church teaches that this restoration occurred with the appearance of the resurrected Peter, James, and John, who ordained Joseph Smith and Oliver Cowdery in 1829.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1979/06/dating-the-restoration-of-the-melchizedek-priesthood?lang=eng|title = Dating the Restoration of the Melchizedek Priesthood}}</ref> All ordained members of the LDS Church can obtain a written line of authority tracing back to Christ through Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/help/support/request-a-priesthood-line-of-authority?lang=eng|title = Request a Priesthood Line of Authority}}</ref>\n\nDespite the acceptance of Peter's primacy, several leaders of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) have taught that the rock referred to by Jesus in Matthew 16:18 was neither Peter nor his confession, but the gift of [[revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]] from the [[Holy Spirit]] which made Christ's divinity known to Peter. [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|Apostle]] [[Howard W. Hunter]] taught: {{quote|\"And upon this rock I will build my church.\" Upon what rock? Peter? Upon a man? No, not upon a man, upon the rock of revelation, the thing which they were talking about. He had just said, \"... flesh and blood hath not revealed it unto thee, but my Father which is in heaven.\" This revelation that Jesus is the Christ is the foundation upon which he would build his Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-student-manual/introduction-to-matthew/chapter-6?lang=eng|title=New Testament Student Manual|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=31 Mar 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nChurch founder [[Joseph Smith]] is quoted as having said: {{quote|Jesus in His teachings says, \"Upon this rock I will build my Church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it.\" What rock? Revelation.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://www.lds.org/manual/teachings-joseph-smith/chapter-16|chapter=Chapter 16: Revelation and the Living Prophet |title=Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=31 Mar 2016|title-link=Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith }}</ref>}}\n\nIt is important to note that although these quotes may represent normative LDS belief, none of them are from canonized doctrinal sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/approaching-mormon-doctrine|title=Approaching Mormon Doctrine|date=2007-05-04}}</ref> The LDS Church therefore has no official doctrinal interpretation of Matthew 16:18 in this respect.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Apostolic succession|Apostolic Succession]]\n* [[Early Christianity]]\n* [[Historical episcopate]]\n* [[Papal infallibility]]\n* [[Papal supremacy]]\n* [[Petrine theory]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n* Addis, William E. & Thomas Arnold (rev. T.B. Scannell). ''Catholic Dictionary.'' (9th ed.) London: Virtue & Co., 1925. (Provides citations for the use of \"\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2\" to mean \"rock\" in classical works)\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|\n\nurl=http://catholicity.elcore.net./SimonIsTheRock.html|\ntitle=Who is the Rock of Matthew 16:18?}}\n\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|url=http://www.geocities.com/getthefulltruth/Matt16vv17-19.html|title=Commentary on Matthew 16:17\u201319|work=The Catholic Evangel|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query.php?url=http://www.geocities.com/getthefulltruth/Matt16vv17-19.html|archivedate=August 11, 2006|url-status=dead}}\n\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|\n\nurl=http://www.biblicalcatholic.com/apologetics/a64.htm|\ntitle=Section IV: Authority|\nwork=Refutation of James G. McCarthy's 'The Gospel According to Rome'}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Chadwick, Henry. ''The Church in Ancient Society: From Galilee to Gregory the Great''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001.\n*Collins, Paul. ''Upon This Rock: The Popes and their Changing Roles''. Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 2000.\n*Evans, G.R. ''The Church in the Early Middle Ages''. I.B. Tauris: New York, 2007.\n*Maxwell-Stuart, P.G. ''Chronicle of the Popes: the Reign-by-Reign Record of the Papacy from St. Peter to the Present''. 2nd ed. London : Thames & Hudson, 2006.\n* Meyendorff, John, ed. ''The Primacy of Peter: Essays in Ecclesiology and the Early Church''. ({{ISBN|0-88141-125-6}})\n*Perkins, Pheme. ''Peter: Apostle for the Whole Church''. Columbia: University of South Carolina Press, 1994.\n*Pham, John-Peter. ''Heirs of the Fisherman: Behind the Scenes of Papal Death and Succession''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2004.\n* Ray, Stephen K. ''Upon This Rock: St. Peter and the Primacy of Rome in Scripture and the Early Church''. ({{ISBN|0-89870-723-4}})\n*Winter, Michael M. ''Saint Peter and the Popes''. Baltimore: Helicon Press, 1960.\n\n{{Holy See}}\n{{Catholic Church footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Primacy Of Simon Peter}}\n[[Category:Saint Peter]]\n[[Category:Bible-related controversies]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christianity]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Matthew]]\n[[Category:Papal primacy]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Peter_as_Pope_.png|thumb|180px|Saint Peter portrayed as a Pope in the ''[[Nuremberg Chronicle]]'' ]]\n{{Saint Peter}}\nThe '''primacy of Peter''', also known as '''Petrine primacy''' (from Latin: ''Petrus'', \"Peter\"), is the position of preeminence that is attributed to [[Saint Peter]] among the [[Apostle (Christian)|Twelve Apostles]].\n\nIt is to be distinguished from but forms the basis of the [[primacy of the Bishop of Rome]], also known as papal primacy or Roman primacy.\n\n== Primacy of Peter among the Apostles ==\n\nThe ''[[Evangelical Dictionary of Theology]]'' illustrates the leading role that Peter played among the Apostles, speaking up on matters that concern them all, being called by Jesus by a name linking him with the rock on which Jesus would build his church, being charged with pastoring the flock of Christ, and taking the leading role in the initial church as described in the [[Acts of the Apostles]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=yu846j61u0wC&pg=PA910 Walter A. Elwell (editor), ''Evangelical Dictionary of Theology''] (Baker Academic 2001 {{ISBN|978-0-80102075-9}}), entry \"Peter, Primacy of\"</ref>\n\nThere is general agreement among scholars on the preeminence that the historical Peter held among the [[Disciple (Christianity)|disciples]] of Jesus, making him \"the most prominent and influential member of the Twelve during Jesus' ministry and in the early Church\".<ref>Theodore Stylianopoulos \"Concerning the Biblical Foundation of Primacy\", in [https://books.google.com/books?id=K0sbuf37A_UC&pg=PA44 Walter Kasper (editor), ''The Petrine Ministry''] (Paulist Press 2008 {{ISBN|978-0-80914334-4}}), pp. 43\u201344, citing\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=6-LYAAAAMAAJ&dq=Meier+%22A+Marginal+Jew%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mX87VMa5GpKf7gai3IDQAw&redir_esc=y John P. Meier, ''A Marginal Jew. 3. Companions and Competitors''] (Knopf Doubleday 2001 {{ISBN|978-0-38546993-7}}), pp. 221\u2013225, and others.</ref>\n\nIn one interpretation the prominence that the [[New Testament]] and other early Christian writings attribute to Peter is due to their seeing him as a unifying factor in contrast to other figures identified with disputed interpretations of Christianity.<ref>\"For ''Peter was probably in fact and effect the bridge-man'' (pontifex maximus!) ''who did more than any other to hold together the diversity of first-century Christianity.'' James the brother of Jesus, and Paul of Tarsus, the two other most prominent leading figures in first-century Christianity, were too much identified with their respective \"brands\" of Christianity, at least in the eyes of Christians at the opposite ends of this particular spectrum. But Peter, as shown particularly by the Antioch episode in {{Bibleref2|Galatians|2}}, had both a care to hold firm to his Jewish heritage\u2014which Paul lacked\u2014and an openness to the demands of developing Christianity, which James lacked. John might have served as a figure of the center holding together the extremes, but if the writings linked with his name are at all indicative of his own stance, he was too much of an individualist to provide such a rallying point. Others could link the developing new religion more firmly to its founding events and to Jesus himself. But none of them, including the rest of the twelve, seem to have played any role of continuing significance for the whole sweep of Christianity\u2014though James the brother of John might have proved an exception had he been spared.\" [Italics original] [[James Dunn (theologian)|Dunn, James D.G.]] ''The Canon Debate''. McDonald & Sanders editors, 2002, ch. 32, p. 577.</ref>\n\n== Matthew 16:18 ==\n\nControversy has surrounded one particular text that is linked with the Aramaic nickname name \u05db\u05e4\u05d0 (''Cepha''), meaning \"rock,\" that Jesus gave the man previously known as Simon.{{Bibleref2c|John|1:42}} The Greeks translated it as \u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Petros''), a new form, appropriately masculine, of the standard feminine word \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 (''petra''), also meaning \"rock;\" and the Latins translated it as ''Petrus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/cephas |title=Cephas - Dictionary.com - Reference.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref>\n\nWhile the reasons for disagreement on the nature of the primacy are complex, hinging on matters of doctrine, history and politics, the debate is often reduced to a discussion of the meaning and translation of Matthew 16:18: \"And I say to thee: That thou art Peter; and upon this rock I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it.\" {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18, Douay-Rheims Bible}}\n\nIn the [[Greek language|Greek]] text, the new name given is \u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Petros''), and in the second half of the same verse the word translated as \"rock\" is \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 (''petra''). A literal translation, in the style of the [[King James Version]], of the words presumably used by Jesus would be \"Thou art Rock, and upon this rock will I build my church\".<ref>In [[French language|French]], the translation, \"Tu es ''Pierre'', et sur cette ''pierre'' je b\u00e2tirai mon \u00c9glise, et les portes de l'enfer ne pr\u00e9vaudront point contre elle\" preserves exactly the play on words in what is believed to be the original Aramaic.</ref> To preserve a supposed pun, the Greek text chose to translate Peter's name as \"\u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2\" rather than as \"\u039a\u03b7\u03c6\u1fb6\u03c2\" (Cephas).\n\nOne common Protestant argument historically has been that the translation from the [[New Testament]] in Hebrew into Greek is tenuous at best as there is no real evidence or indication that the New Testament (in Greek) was ever translated from Hebrew or Aramaic texts; for that argument see [[Aramaic primacy]]. According to the Protestant transliteration argument,{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}} in the [[Aramaic of Jesus|language that Jesus spoke]], the same word, \u05db\u05e4\u05d0 (cepha), was used for both Peter's name and for the rock on which Jesus said he would build his church. Since the [[Protestant Reformation]], many non-Catholics, in disagreement with the historic Catholic Church view, have disputed whether the feminine \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 refers to Peter, claiming it instead refers to either Peter's confession of faith or to Jesus himself.<ref name=Engler>John Engler. \"The Rock-Foundation of Matthew 16:17-20\". <http://www.greatcommission.com/Matthew161720.html> Accessed 12 Mar 2013</ref><ref name=Stagg>Stagg, Frank. ''New Testament Theology''. Broadman Press, 1962. {{ISBN|0-8054-1613-7}}</ref>\n\n==Catholic view on relationship to the Church today==\n{{Papal primacy and infallibility|expanded=overview}}\n\nIn [[Catholicism]], it is argued that the primacy of Peter is a basis for the primacy of the bishop of Rome over other [[bishops]] throughout the [[Roman Catholic Church|Church]] via the doctrine of [[Apostolic succession]]. This extension of Petrine primacy to popes is known as the [[primacy of the Bishop of Rome]], also known as the primacy of the Roman Pontiff. This Catholic Church doctrine holds that the [[pope|papacy]] has authority delegated from Jesus to rule over the [[Christendom|entire Church]]. There are various views on the nature of the primacy and how it has been exercised and [[Apostolic succession|passed on]]. This belief makes a distinction between the personal prestige of Peter and the supremacy of the office of [[pope]] which Catholics believe Jesus instituted in the person of Peter. Some,{{which|date=July 2019}} but not nearly all, [[Protestantism|Protestant denominations]] accept the concept of the primacy of Peter, but believe it was only relevant during the lifetime of Peter.{{cn|date=August 2019}} They do not believe the pope holds any authority over the [[Christian Church|universal Church]].\n\nSome [[Catholic Church|Catholics]] believe that [[Paul of Tarsus and Judaism|Saint Paul saw Judaism]] as the [[Typology (theology)|type]] or figure of [[Christianity]]: \"Now all these things happened to [the Jews] in figure....\"{{bibleref2c|1Cor|10:11||1 Cor. 10:11}} In the [[613 Mitzvot|Old Law]], {{bibleref2|Deut.|17:8-12}} attributes to the [[Kohen Gadol|High Priest]] the highest jurisdiction in religious matters. Therefore, it is argued, logic dictates that a supreme head would be necessary in the Christian Church,{{cn|date=August 2019}} though the relevance of [[Biblical law in Christianity]] is still disputed; see also [[New Covenant]] and [[The New Commandment|New Commandment]].\n\nIn the [[New Testament]], which some call the ''New Law'' or \"New Greek Testament\",<ref>Knight, Kevin. \"Question 106. The law of the Gospel, called the New Law, considered in itself.\" ''New Advent.'' Sept. 11, 2009: http://www.newadvent.org/summa/2106.htm</ref> {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:16-18}} reports that Jesus changed Simon's name to Peter. Elsewhere in Scripture such a name change always denotes some change in status (e.g., Abram to Abraham, Jacob to Israel, and Saul to Paul).\n\nJesus also said to Peter in verse 19, \"I will give to thee the [[Keys of Heaven|keys of the kingdom of heaven]].\" Especially for the Hebrew people, keys were a symbol of authority. Indeed, Jesus declares in the [[Book of Revelation]], that He has the \"keys of death and hell,\" which means that He has power over death and hell; {{Bibleref2|Isaiah|22:21-22}} also supports this. [[James Gibbons|Cardinal Gibbons]], in his book ''The Faith of Our Fathers'', points out that keys are still a symbol of authority in today's culture; he uses the example of someone giving the keys of his house to another person, and that the latter represented the owner of the house in his absence.\n\nAnother source indicating Peter's supremacy can be found in {{Bibleref2|John|21:15-17}} where Christ tells Peter three times to \"feed His sheep\" and \"feed His lambs.\" The \"sheep\" might be understood to be the stronger portion of Jesus' flock (the [[clergy]]), and the \"lambs\" as the weaker portion (the [[laity]]). From this, Catholics believe that Peter was given charge over Christ's whole flock, that is, the [[Catholic Church|Church]].\n\nMoreover, Peter is always named first in all listings of the Apostles; [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] is invariably mentioned last. In {{bibleref2|Matthew|10:2}} Peter is described as the \"first Apostle\". It is important to note that Peter was neither the first Apostle in age nor election; therefore, Peter must be the first Apostle in the sense of authority, if one ignores the possibility of him being first in the sense of first in the list of Twelve Apostles.{{bibleref2c|Mk.|3:16}} {{bibleref2c|Mt.|4:18-19}} According to {{bibleref2|Acts|1-2,10-11,15}}, St. Peter was the leader of the early Christian church in Jerusalem. Jesus also instructed St. Peter to strengthen his brethren, i.e., the apostles, according to {{bibleref2|Luke|22:31-32}}.\n\nBoth Latin and Greek writers in the early church (such as the St. [[John Chrysostom]]) referred to \"rock\" as applying to both Peter personally and his faith symbolically, as well as seeing Christ's promise to apply more generally to his twelve apostles and the Church at large.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\">{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 61\u201366}}</ref>\n\n[[First Vatican Council|Vatican Council I]] defined the primacy of the bishop of Rome over the whole Catholic Church as an essential institution of the Church that can never be relinquished. This primacy is thus crucial to the understanding of the church from a Catholic viewpoint. At the same time, the history of papal primacy has always been imperfect and much-debated.<ref>Schatz, Klaus.  Papal Primacy: From Its Origins to the Present.  Translated by John A. Otto and Linda M. Maloney.  Collegeville, MN: The Liturgical Press, 1996.  p. x.</ref> This is reflected in the [[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]:\n\n{{quote|'''424'''  Moved by the grace of the Holy Spirit and drawn by the Father, we believe in Jesus and confess: \"You are the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" On the rock of this faith confessed by St. Peter, Christ built his Church.|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n{{quote|'''552'''  Simon Peter holds the first place in the college of the Twelve; Jesus entrusted a unique mission to him. Through a revelation from the Father, Peter had confessed: \"You are the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" Our Lord then declared to him: \"You are Peter, and on this rock I will build my Church, and the gates of Hades will not prevail against it.\" Christ, the \"living Stone\", thus assures his Church, built on Peter, of victory over the powers of death. Because of the faith he confessed Peter will remain the unshakable rock of the Church. His mission will be to keep this faith from every lapse and to strengthen his brothers in it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P1D.HTM#-F1 |title=Cathecism of the Catholic Church |publisher=Vatican.va |accessdate=2012-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623214259/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG0015/__P1D.HTM#-F1 |archivedate=2012-06-23 }}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nRegarding the Catholic interpretation of Matthew 16:18-19, [[Jaroslav Pelikan]] writes:<ref>{{cite book |last= Pelikan |first= Jaroslav |authorlink= Jaroslav Pelikan |editor= |others= |title= The Riddle of Roman Catholicism |year= 1959 |publisher= Abingdon Press |location= New York |page= 78}}</ref> \"As Roman Catholic scholars now concede, the ancient Christian father Cyprian used it to prove the authority of the bishop\u2014not merely of the Roman bishop, but of every bishop,\" referring to Maurice Bevenot's work on St. Cyprian.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bevenot |first= Maurice | title= St. Cyprian: The Lapsed, The Unity of the Catholic Church |pages= 6\u20138}}</ref>\n\n[[Eastern Catholic Churches|Eastern Catholics]] agree with the above, but also consider Peter to be representative of all bishops. In this, they represent a middle-ground between the Catholic position and that of the [[Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] in the next section.\n\nThough among the Twelve Peter is predominant in the first chapters of [[Acts of the Apostles]], [[James the Just|James \"the brother of the Lord\"]] is shown to be a leader in his own right in later chapters, indeed he is commonly considered the first [[Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem#Bishops of Jerusalem|Bishop of Jerusalem]]. Some assume James outranks Peter because he speaks last in the [[Council of Jerusalem]] and suggests the final ruling (concerning Gentile converts and Jewish practices such as [[Circumcision controversy in early Christianity|circumcision]]) agreed upon by all, and because Paul mentions him before Peter and John when he calls them \"pillars of the church\" in [[Jerusalem in Christianity|Jerusalem]]. James was indeed the first bishop or [[patriarch]] of Jerusalem according to tradition. However, Catholics believe the bishop of Jerusalem was not by that fact the head of the Christian church, since the leadership rested in Peter as the \"Rock\" and \"Chief Shepherd\".<ref>Mckenzie, John L. ''The Dictionary of the Bible'' (Catholic)</ref> It is believed Peter entrusted the Jerusalem community to James when he was forced to leave Jerusalem due to [[Herod Agrippa]]'s persecution. {{bibleref2c|Acts|12}}<ref>''The Navarre Bible'', footnotes</ref>\n\nHowever, at the Council of Jerusalem in Acts 15, James uses the Greek ''exegesato'' to refer to Peter's statements, which refers to literally \"declaring\" or \"issuing a ruling.\" <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EvQJ_i7J4CEC&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=exegesato+james&source=bl&ots=0T7FZfHbub&sig=MSPr7qcxxSLvgY1BDHdUgA3xu4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3mbqave7JAhUJlB4KHTVgDV0Q6AEIHjAA#v=onepage&q=exegesato%20james&f=false The Biblical Basis for the Papacy] by John Salza</ref> However, James uses the Greek word ''akouoo'' in relation to his statements, which refers to literally \"giving one's opinion,\" and does not denote authority. Catholic scholar Michael M. Winter puts it in his ''Saint Peter and the Popes'' in the following terms: \"The speech of St. James is of a different character [from that of St. Peter]. He acquiesces to what St. Peter had said, although it seems to have been against his personal inclinations, and then puts forward a practical suggestion for the sake of harmony.\"\n\nThe Fourth Century Latin Father St. Jerome, in his epistle to St. Augustine of Hippo, wrote that \"nay more, that Peter was the prime mover in issuing the decree by which this was affirmed,\" in relation to the Council of Jerusalem, and again, \"and to his opinion the Apostle James, and all the elders together, gave consent.\" <ref>http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/1102075.htm</ref>\n\nThis view is likewise echoed by Saint John Chrysostom, the Fourth Century Patriarch of Constantinople:\n\n{{quote|And why, then, passing by the others, does He converse with Peter on these things? (John 21:15). He was the chosen one of the Apostles, and the mouth of the disciples, and the leader of the choir. On this account, Paul also went up on a time to see him rather than the others (Galatians 1:18). And withal, to show him that he must thenceforward have confidence, as the denial was done away with, He puts into his hands the presidency over the brethren. And He brings not forward the denial, nor reproaches him with what had past, but says, \"If you love me, preside over the brethren.\" ...And the third time He gives him the same injunction, showing what a price He sets the presidency over His own sheep. And if one should say, \"How then did James receive the throne of Jerusalem?,\" this I would answer that He appointed this man (Peter) teacher, not of that throne, but of the whole world.<ref>http://www.catholicbridge.com/catholic/orthodox/pope_acts_15_james_and_peter.php</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nFor Catholics, the fact that the new name for Simon is Peter is in fact itself very significant. In the Old Testament God is frequently referred to as a Rock or stone. Jesus refers to himself as the cornerstone. The Book of Daniel contains a prophecy that a Rock or stone from the mountain of God (heaven) will come down to earth and destroy the pagan kings. The rock will then grow itself until it covers the entire earth. Protestants consider this prophecy to allude to the [[end times]] but Catholics consider the prophecy to refer specifically to Jesus as the Rock from Heaven. Further, Catholics see the fact that the Rock does not leave but stays to until it covers the entire earth to mean that the Church, built of the Rock of Peter, is the [[body of Christ]], the Rock from Heaven, and that the Rock will eventually cover the entire Earth which is why the term Catholic (universal or worldwide) is the most common designation for the Catholic Church.\n\n===Individuals and documents supporting Roman primacy===\n\n====Irenaeus====\n[[Irenaeus]] has been called the most important witness of the [[Christianity in the 2nd century]].<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 6.</ref> Taught by [[Polycarp]], who had been instructed by John the apostle, Irenaeus became [[Bishop of Lyon]] in 178. In his ''Against the Heresies'', Irenaeus wrote, \"Although there are many dialects in the world, the force of the tradition is one and the same. For the same faith is held and handed down by the churches established in the German states, the Spains, among the Celtic tribes, in the East, in Libya, and in the central portions of the world\u2026\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 8.</ref> In Book 3, Irenaeus continues his defense of the unity of the church around the bishop, writing, \"By pointing out the apostolic tradition and faith announced to mankind, which has been brought down to our time by successions of bishops, in the greatest, most ancient, and well known church, founded and established by the two most glorious apostles, Peter and Paul, at Rome, we can confound all who in any other way\u2026 gather more than they ought.\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 9.</ref>\n\nIrenaeus asserted the Doctrine of Apostolic Succession to counter the claims of heretics, especially the Gnostics who were attacking the theology and authority of the mainstream Church. He stated that one could find true teaching in several leading episcopal sees, not just at Rome. The doctrine he asserted, therefore, has two parts: lineage from the Apostles and right teaching. Even today a bishop can be in the line of succession, but schismatic and heretical as is the case with many episcopi vagantes who claim to or may have Catholic Orders, but have no following and have deviated from the Catholic orthodox faith as defined by the larger denominations such as the Orthodox, Anglicans, Catholics and Lutherans.\n\n====Ignatius of Antioch====\n[[Ignatius of Antioch|Ignatius]], bishop of Antioch, was well known for his insistence on the authority of the bishop. In his writings to the church at [[Smyrna]] in 115 AD, he encouraged the Smyrnaeans to \"Avoid divisions, as the beginning of evil. Follow, all of you, the bishop, as Jesus Christ followed the father; and follow the presbytery as the apostles. Let no man do aught pertaining to the Church apart from the bishop. Wheresoever the bishop appears, there let the people be, even as wheresoever Christ Jesus is, there is the Catholic Church\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 4.</ref>\n\n====Tertullian====\nBorn in [[Carthage]] around 155 AD, [[Tertullian]] became a priest around the age of forty and worked tirelessly to defend the faith. In his Scorpiace of 208 AD, Tertullian wrote, \"No delay or inquest will meet Christians on the threshold\u2026 For though you think that heaven is still shut up, remember that the Lord left the keys of it to Peter here, and through him to the Church, which keys everyone will carry with him, if he has been questioned and made confession [of faith].\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 23.</ref> Scorpiace is the first known historical reference to the keys pertaining to anyone other than Peter. In it, he saw the keys as pertaining to \"everyone\" if they \"made confession\" rather than according to the modern interpretation concerning the bishops of Rome alone. Tertullian later retracted even this association in De Pudecitia,<ref>Schaff, Philip., American Ed., 1994. Alexander Roberts, D.D. & James Donaldson, LL.D. with notes by A. Cleveland Coxe, D.D.. AnteNicene Fathers: Fathers of the Third Century: Tertullian, Part Fourth; Minucius Felix; Commodian; Origen, Parts First and Second. On Modesty \"Chap. XXI - Of the difference Between Discipline and Power, and of the Power of the Keys.\" pp. 98-101. Published online at http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf04.iii.viii.xxi.html</ref> listing various reasons why the Keys of Peter pertained to Peter alone. The churches later declared him an apostate along with the followers of Montanus for insisting that authority must be associated with demonstrable power.\n\n====Cyprian====\n[[Cyprian|Thascius Caecilius Cyprianus]] was made bishop of Carthage in 248 AD. but died only ten years later. Throughout his writings, Cyprian asserts that the Rock is Peter, and the Church rests upon him. He also claims that as the Church is settled upon the bishops, they too have authority. He writes, \"They, who have departed from the Church, do not allow the Church to recall and bring back the lapsed. There is one God, and one Christ, and one Church, and one chair founded by the voice of the Lord on the rock. Another altar cannot be set up, nor a new priesthood made, besides the one altar and the one priesthood. Whoever gathers elsewhere scatters.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. pp. 29-30.</ref> In his 251 AD De Catholicae Ecclesiae Unitate, Cyprian asks, \"He who deserts the chair of Peter, upon whom the Church was founded, does he trust himself to be in the Church?\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 53.</ref>\n\n====John Chrysostom====\n[[John Chrysostom]] was born at [[Antioch]] around 347 and would fight for the reform of the church until his exile in 404. His homilies emphasize his belief in the primacy. St. Chrysostom called Peter \"the leader of the choir, the mouth of all the apostles, the head of that tribe, the ruler of the whole world, the foundation of the Church, the ardent lover of Christ\u2026\"<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 126.</ref> His writings also emphasize the mortality of Peter, linking him more closely to the people of the Church.\n\n====Augustine of Hippo====\n[[Saint Augustine]] was born in [[Numidia]] in 354 AD and was baptized in [[Milan]] in 387 AD. He was also bishop of Hippo from 397 AD til his death in 430 AD. Augustine taught that Peter was first amongst the apostles, and thus represents the church.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 163.</ref> His Sermo states, \"For Peter in many places in the Scriptures appears to represent the Church, especially in that place where it was said \"I give to thee the keys\u2026 shall be loosed in heaven\". What! did Peter receive these keys, and Paul not receive? Did Peter receive and John and James not receive, and the rest of the apostles? But since in a figure Peter represented the Church, what was given to him singly was given to the Church.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 175.</ref> His 395 A.D. Contra Epistolam Manichaei states, \"There are many other things which rightly keep me in the bosom of the Catholic Church\u2026 The succession of the priests keeps me, from the very seat of the apostle Peter (to whom the Lord after his resurrection gave charge to feed his sheep) down to the present episcopate.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 182.</ref>\n\n====Pope Innocent I====\n[[Pope Innocent I|Innocent I]] held the papal office from 402 to 417. Modern theories of Papal Primacy developed around Innocent and his writings. In a 416 AD letter to [[Decentius]], bishop of Eugubium, Innocent writes, \"Who does not know or observe that it [the church order] was delivered by Peter the chief of the apostles to the Roman church, and is kept until now, and ought to be retained by all, and that nothing ought to be imposed or introduced which has no authority, or seems to derive its precedents elsewhere?\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 194.</ref> It is also during this time that bishops began to recognize Innocent's primacy as Pope over other bishops in the West. This is made evident, among others, in a letter from the Council at Mileve to Innocent in 416 AD, which alludes the authority of \"his holiness\" drawn from the authority of Scripture.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 198.</ref> The doctrine of Primacy was beginning to take shape with Innocent's papacy.\n\n====Pope Leo I====\nBased on his knowledge of the Petrine texts of the Gospel, and his writings which expound upon it, it is easy to see that [[Pope Leo I|Leo I]] identified with the authority bestowed on Peter as bishop of Rome. Leo himself was consecrated bishop of Rome in 440 AD. He writes that \"The right of this power did indeed pass on to other apostles, and the order of this decree passed on to all the chiefs of the Church; but not in vain was that which was imparted to all entrusted but one. Therefore this is commended to Peter separately, because all the rulers of the Church are invested with the figure of Peter\u2026 So then in Peter the strength of all is fortified, and the help of divine grace is so ordered that the stability which through Christ is given to Peter, through Peter is conveyed to the apostles\" (Giles, 280). The [[Council of Chalcedon]] would later refer to Leo as \"him who had been charged with the custody of the vine by the savior.\" <ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 323.</ref>\n\n====Pope Gregory VII====\nThe [[Gregorian Reform|Gregorian Reform movement]] was rather a series of movements many of which involved the reform of the Catholic Church, headed by [[Pope Gregory VII|Gregory VII]], formerly the Archdeacon Hildebrand. Gregory became Pope in 1073 with the objective of reforming not the body of the church, but a purification of the clergy in general.<ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 101.</ref> Gregory is perhaps most recognized with the quarrel between himself and [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|King Henry IV]] of Germany, known as the \"[[Investiture Contest]]\". Gregory's Dictus Pape outlines his policies and ideals, as well as those of the Catholic Church. In this work, Gregory claims that the pope has power to depose and restore bishops, and also effectively reduces the authority of other bishops.<ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 129.</ref> This doctrine supported the idea that Rome and the church here also afforded primacy over all other churches. Gregory's papacy also bolstered the power of the Church over that of the State. The Gregorians defended the ideal of a separation of powers, claiming \"Let kings have what belongs to kings, and priests have what belongs to priests.\" <ref>Morris, Colin.  The Papal Monarchy: The Western Church from 1050 to 1250.  Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1989. p. 133.</ref> The Petrine Primacy was now more affirmed than ever.\n\n===Challenges===\n\n====Councils====\nMany challenges faced the Popes claiming primacy throughout the history of Catholicism. The [[Edict of Milan]], the [[First Council of Nicaea|Council of Nicea]], and the [[First Council of Constantinople]] all dealt with the issue of primacy in that they amended the power of the popes over the other bishops. The third canon of the First Council of Constantinople of 381 AD declares Constantinople the new Rome, gives the Bishop of Rome the seat of honor and gives the Bishop of Constantinople second place in honor. The [[First Council of Ephesus|Council of Ephesus]] in 431 AD offers debate as to whether the results determine that the Pope is at the head of the Church, or rather that it is under the authority of a council of bishops (Giles, 238-256 AD). Although the highlight of the [[Council of Chalcedon]] in 451 AD was the confession of the [[Person of Christ]], the Council also resulted in limitations to the powers of the bishops. Many letters of the Council identify its position as in agreement with papal primacy. Those present employ titles such as \"the most holy and beloved of God\" and \"ecumenical archbishop and patriarch of great Rome\" to address Pope Leo. Thus, as not all can be satisfied with the results, The Council of Chalcedon resulted in a schism with the Oriental Orthodox Church.<ref>Giles, E., ed.  Documents Illustrating Papal Authority: A.D. 96-454.  London: S.P.C.K., 1952. p. 297-321.</ref>\n\n====Schism====\nInternally, people questioned who rightfully was pope, while others wondered as to the role the Pope was to play outside of Rome.<ref>Logan, F. Donald.  A History of the Church in the Middle Ages.  New York: Routledge, 2002. p. 133.</ref> The papacy's most widely known crisis, as well as its largest challenge to authority, came with the \"[[Western Schism]]\" in the late Middle Ages, dating from 1378\u20131417.<ref>Schatz, Klaus.  Papal Primacy: From Its Origins to the Present.  Translated by John A. Otto and Linda M. Maloney.  Collegeville, MN: The Liturgical Press, 1996.  p. 100.</ref> Seven popes ruled from Avignon in France in the early 14th century, until Gregory XI risked returning to turbulent Italy and the Roman seat.<ref>Logan, F. Donald.  A History of the Church in the Middle Ages.  New York: Routledge, 2002. p. 297.</ref> Following the close of the [[Avignon papacy]] in 1377, [[Urban VI]], an Italian, took the reins over a predominantly French college of Cardinals. The Cardinals called the election into question and elected [[Antipope Clement VII|Clement VII]] as Pope. Germany, Italy, England, and the rest of Northern and Eastern Europe remained loyal to Urban, while France, Spain, Scotland, and Rome followed Clement VII (1378\u20131394) and his successor, [[Antipope Benedict XIII|Benedict XIII]] (1394&ndash;1417) who would reside in Avignon.\n\n==Eastern Orthodox view on relationship to the Church today==\n\n===Many hold the ''Primacy'' of Peter===\n[[File:StPeter-RussianMuseum.jpg|thumb|[[Icon]] of St. Peter (15th century, [[Russian State Museum]], [[Saint Petersburg]]).]]\n\nThe [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] regards the Apostle Peter, together with the Apostle Paul, as \"preeminent apostles\". Another title used for Peter is ''Coryphaeus'', which could be translated as \"Choir-director,\" or lead singer.<ref>[[John Meyendorff]], et al. (1963), ''The Primacy of Peter in the Orthodox Church'' ([[St. Vladimir's Seminary]] Press, Crestwood NY, {{ISBN|978-0-88141-125-6}})</ref>\n\nOrthodox scholars follow St. John Chrysostom and the Byzantine<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 67\u201390}}</ref> tradition in seeing Peter as the icon of the episcopate<ref>{{cite book|title=His Broken Body: Understanding and Healing the Schism between the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches|author=Cleenewerck Laurent|year=2008|publisher=EUC Press|id= |pages= 257\u2013263}} {{Self-published source|date=June 2015}}</ref> with his title of protos (first) implying a certain level of authority over the other apostles. In this traditional Orthodox and Patristic view, the Church is the local Eucharistic assembly (\"the diocese\" in today's terminology) and the one who holds the \"Chair of Peter\" (St. Cyprian's expression) is the bishop. As a result, the primacy of Peter is relevant to the relationship between the bishop and the presbyters, not between the bishop of Rome and the other bishops who are all equally holding Peter's chair.\n\nAs John Meyendorff explained:\n\n{{quote|A very clear patristic tradition sees the succession of Peter in the episcopal ministry. The doctrine of St Cyprian of Carthage on the \"See of Peter\" being present in every local Church, and not only in Rome, is well-known. It is also found in the East, among people who certainly never read the De unitate ecclesia of Cyprian, but who share its main idea, thus witnessing to it as part of the catholic tradition of the Church. St Gregory of Nyssa, for example, affirms that Christ \"through Peter gave to the bishops the keys of the heavenly honors,\" and the author of the Areopagitica, when speaking of the \"hierarchs\" of the Church, refers immediately to the image of St Peter. A careful analysis of ecclesiastical literature both Eastern and Western, of the first millennium, including such documents as the lives of the saint, would certainly show that this tradition was a persistent one; and indeed it belongs to the essence of Christian ecclesiology to consider any local bishop to be the teacher of his flock and therefore to fulfill sacramentally, through apostolic succession, the office of the first true believer, Peter... There exists, however, another succession, equally recognized by Byzantine theologians, but only on the level of the analogy existing between the apostolic college and the episcopal college, this second succession being determined by the need for ecclesiastical order. Its limits are determined by the Councils, and - in the Byzantine practice \u2013 by the \"very pious emperors.\"|''The Primacy of Peter'', p. 89}}\n\nThe notion that many [[Episcopal see|Sees]] were \u2018\u2019of Peter\u2019\u2019 had also once been held in the West:\n\n[[Pope Gregory I|Pope Gregory the Great]]\n{{quote|Your most sweet Holiness has spoken much in your letter to me about the chair of Saint Peter, Prince of the apostles, saying that he himself now sits on it in the persons of his successors...Wherefore though there are many apostles, yet with regard to the principality itself the See of the Prince of the apostles alone has grown strong in authority, which in three places is the See of one...He himself stablished (sic) the See in which, though he was to leave it, he sat for seven years. Since then it is the See of one, and one See, over which by Divine authority three bishops now preside, whatever good I hear of you, this I impute to myself.<ref>\u2019\u2019To Eulogius, Bishop of Alexandria\u2019\u2019Book VII, Epistle XL</ref>}}\n\nConsequently, Eastern and Oriental Orthodox do not recognize the Bishop of Rome as the unique successor of St. Peter and consider him to be in a state of schism and heresy. However, the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] sends a delegation each year to Rome to participate in the celebration of the feast of Sts. Peter and Paul.\n\nThe Orthodox also consider that [[Pope Linus|St. Linus]], not Peter, was actually the first [[Bishop of Rome]].\n{{quote|Of the church of Rome, Linus the son of Claudia was the first, ordained by Paul; and Clemens (Clement), after Linus' death, the second, ordained by me Peter.<ref>\u2019\u2019Apostolic Teaching and Constitutions\u2019\u2019, Book 7, Chapter XLVI \u2013 \"Who Were They that the Holy Apostles Sent and Ordained?\"</ref>}}\n\n===''Keys'' and ''rock'' not exclusive to Peter===\n[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] theologians agree that in {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}, \"rock\" is a likely reference to Peter personally since the very name \"Peter\" means \"rock.\".<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |pages= 47\u201348}}</ref> However {{bibleref2|Matthew|18:18}} implies that the other Apostles were given the same powers. Although the word ''keys'' is ''explicitly'' absent from this later verse a number of [[Church Fathers]] recognised that the meaning of ''keys'' is ''implicitly'' there; that the rest of the church has the keys:\n\n[[Tertullian]]\n{{quote|What, now, (has this to do) with the Church, and) your (church), indeed, Psychic? For, in accordance with the person of Peter, it is to spiritual men that this power will correspondently appertain, either to an apostle or else to a prophet.<ref>\u2019\u2019On Modesty\u2019\u2019. Book VII. Chapter XXI</ref>}}\n\n[[Hilary of Poitiers]]\n{{quote|This faith it is which is the foundation of the Church; through this faith the gates of hell cannot prevail against her. This is the faith which has the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatsoever this faith shall have loosed or bound on earth shall be loosed or bound in heaven. This faith is the Father's gift by revelation; even the knowledge that we must not imagine a false Christ, a creature made out of nothing, but must confess Him the Son of God, truly possessed of the Divine nature<ref>\u2018\u2019On the Trinity\u2019\u2019. Book VI.37</ref>}}\n\n[[John Chrysostom]]\n{{quote|For ([[John the Apostle|John]]) the Son of thunder, the beloved of Christ, the pillar of the Churches throughout the world, who holds the keys of heaven, who drank the cup of Christ, and was baptized with His baptism, who lay upon his Master's bosom, with much confidence, this man now comes forward to us now<ref>''Homilies on the Gospel of John.'' Preface to Homily 1.2</ref>}}\n\n[[Augustine]]\n{{quote|He has given, therefore, the keys to His Church, that whatsoever it should bind on earth might be bound in heaven, and whatsoever it should loose on earth might be, loosed in heaven; that is to say, that whosoever in the Church should not believe that his sins are remitted, they should not be remitted to him; but that whosoever should believe and should repent, and turn from his sins, should be saved by the same faith and repentance on the ground of which he is received into the bosom of the Church. For he who does not believe that his sins can be pardoned, falls into despair, and becomes worse as if no greater good remained for him than to be evil, when he has ceased to have faith in the results of his own repentance.<ref>\u2019\u2019On Christian Doctrine\u2019\u2019 Book I. Chapter 18.17 \u2018\u2019The Keys Given to the Church\u2019\u2019.</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|...Peter, the first of the apostles, receive the keys of the kingdom of heaven for the binding and loosing of sins; and for the same congregation of saints, in reference to the perfect repose in the bosom of that mysterious life to come did the evangelist John recline on the breast of Christ. For it is not the former alone but the whole Church, that bindeth and looseth sins; nor did the latter alone drink at the fountain of the Lord's breast, to emit again in preaching, of the Word in the beginning, God with God, and those other sublime truths regarding the divinity of Christ, and the Trinity and Unity of the whole Godhead.<ref>\u2019\u2019On the Gospel of John\u2019\u2019. Tractate CXXIV.7</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|...the keys that were given to the Church,<ref>\u2019\u2019A Treatise Concerning the Correction of the Donatists.\u2019\u2019 Chapter 10.45</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|How the Church? Why, to her it was said, \"To thee I will give the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatsoever thou shall loose on earth shall be loosed in heaven, and whatsoever thou shall bind on earth shall be bound in heaven.\"<ref>''Ten Homilies on the First Epistle of John''. Homily X.10</ref>}}\n\nMoreover, Eastern Orthodox theologians follow such Fathers as St. John Chrysostom by clarifying that \"rock\" simultaneously refers to Peter (instrumentally) as well as Peter's confession of faith which is what has ultimate significance in establishing the Church.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\"/>\n\nSome Orthodox scholars do not see Peter as being in any way above the other apostles, arguing that Peter did not have power and authority over them during Christ's public ministry. There were no positions of power between the twelve, only \"degrees of intimacy\" or \"degrees of honor.\" According to this view, Peter has a weak symbolic primacy or primacy of honor (in the sense of a purely honorary primacy). In the patristic era, this was actually the Western view held by St Augustine. Others (see above), following the traditional Byzantine view of St John Chrysostom see Peter as the icon of the bishop and therefore endowed with authority in the Church (i.e. the diocese).\n\n[[Tertullian]]\n{{quote|Come now, you who would indulge a better curiosity, if you would apply it to the business of your salvation, run over the apostolic churches, in which the very thrones of the apostles are still pre-eminent in their places, in which their own authentic writings are read, uttering the voice and representing the face of each of them severally. Achaia is very near you, (in which) you find Corinth. Since you are not far from Macedonia, you have Philippi; (and there too) you have the Thessalonians. Since you are able to cross to Asia, you get Ephesus. Since, moreover, you are close upon Italy, you have Rome, from which there comes even into our own hands the very authority (of apostles themselves). How happy is its church, on which apostles poured forth all their doctrine along with their blood! where Peter endures a passion like his Lord's! where Paul wins his crown in a death like John's where the Apostle John was first plunged, unhurt, into boiling oil, and thence remitted to his island-exile!<ref>\u2018\u2019The Prescription Against Heretics\u2019\u2019: Chapter XXXVI.-The Apostolic Churches the Voice of the Apostles. Let the Heretics Examine Their Apostolic Claims, in Each Case, Indisputable. The Church of Rome Doubly Apostolic; Its Early Eminence and Excellence. Heresy, as Perverting the Truth, is Connected Therewith</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Was anything withheld from the knowledge of Peter, who is called \"the rock on which the church should be built,\" who also obtained \"the keys of the kingdom of heaven,\" with the power of \"loosing and binding in heaven and on earth?\" Was anything, again, concealed from John, the Lord's most beloved disciple, who used to lean on His breast to whom alone the Lord pointed Judas out as the traitor, whom He commended to Mary as a son in His own stead?<ref>\u2018\u2019The Prescription Against Heretics\u2019\u2019:Chapter XXII.-Attempt to Invalidate This Rule of Faith Rebutted. The Apostles Safe Transmitters of the Truth. Sufficiently Taught at First, and Faithful in the Transmission.</ref>}}\n\n[[John Chrysostom]]\n{{quote|As a king sending forth governors, gives power to cast into prison and to deliver from it, so in sending these forth, Christ investeth them with the same power.<ref>\"On the Gospel of John\" On John xx. 10, 11. (Homily LXXXVI)</ref>}}\n\n[[Pope Leo I]]\n{{quote|... though He has delegated the care of His sheep to many shepherds, yet He has not Himself abandoned the guardianship of His beloved flock.<ref>\u2019\u2019Sermon III\u2019\u2019. (On His Birthday, III: Delivered on the Anniversary of His Elevation to the Pontificate, Chapter II)</ref>}}\n\n===Proofs from the Bible===\nOther biblical texts seem to suggest that Peter was not ''head of the church'' in any ''de jure'' sense. {{bibleref2|Acts|15:1-21}} shows the apostles considering a question by means of calling a Council. Although Peter is mentioned as speaking first, and all are silent - all are silent too when Paul speaks. Further if Peter's pronouncement was authoritative then Paul speaking afterwards would be superfluous; given that the 'decision' had already been made.\n\nEquality of all the Apostles is shown in {{bibleref2|Ephesians|2:19-20}}; that all the Apostles together are the foundation of the church.\n\n{{bibleref2|Galatians|2:7}} shows that Paul taught in the same terms as Peter did.\n\nThe ''forgiveness of sins'' (one of the powers of ''the keys'') is granted to many {{bibleref2|John|20:23}} and, {{bibleref2|Matthew|18:19}}.\n\n===Examples from history===\nOrthodox historians also maintain that Rome's authority in the early Eastern Roman (or Byzantine) empire was recognized only partially because of Rome's Petrine character, and that this factor was not the decisive issue. Moreover, the Orthodox view is that Rome's privileges were not understood as an absolute power (i.e., the difference between primacy and supremacy). In the East, there were numerous \"apostolic sees\", Jerusalem being considered the \"mother of all churches,\" and the bishop of Antioch could also claim the title of successor to Peter, being that Peter was the first [[List of Patriarchs of Antioch|bishop of Antioch]]. \"Canon 28 of [[Council of Chalcedon|Chalcedon]] was for [the Byzantines] one of the essential texts for the organization of the Church: 'It is for right reasons that the accorded privileges to old Rome, for this city was the seat of the Emperor and the Senate.' ... The reason why the Roman Church had been accorded an incontestable precedence over all other apostolic churches was that its Petrine and Pauline 'apostolicity' was in fact added to the city's position as the capital city, and only the conjunction of both of these elements gave the Bishop of Rome the right to occupy the place of a primate in the Christian world with the consensus of all the churches.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=\"Peter's Primacy in the New Testament and the Early Tradition\" in The Primacy of Peter|author=Veselin Kesich|year=1992|publisher=St. Vladimir's Seminary Press|id= |page= 68}}</ref>\n\n==Protestant views on relationship to the Church today==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = Saint Raphael Catholic Church (Springfield, Ohio) - stained glass, Upon this Rock, detail - St. Peter's Basilica.jpg\n | caption1 = Stained glass window in a Catholic church depicting [[St. Peter's Basilica]] in Rome sitting \"Upon this rock,\" a reference to [[:s:Bible (King James)/Matthew#Chapter 16|Matthew 16]]:18. Most present-day Catholics interpret Jesus as saying he was building his church on the rock of the Apostle Peter and the succession of popes which claim Apostolic succession from him.\n\n | image2 = AugsburgConfessionArticle7OftheChurch.jpg\n | caption2 = A 17th century illustration of [[:s:Augsburg Confession#Article VII: Of the Church.|Article VII: Of the Church]] from the ''Augsburg Confession'', which states \"...one holy Church is to continue forever. The Church is the congregation of saints, in which the Gospel is rightly taught and the Sacraments are rightly administered.\" Here the rock from Matthew 16:18 refers to the preaching and ministry of Jesus as the Christ, a view discussed at length in the 1537 ''[[Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope|Treatise]]''.<ref>[http://bookofconcord.org/treatise.php#para22 ''Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope, paragraph 22''] and following</ref>}}\n\nA major debate between Catholics and [[Protestants]] centers on Matthew 16:18 where Jesus tells Peter: \"You are ''Peter'', and on this ''rock'' I will build my Church....\" Catholics interpret the verse as saying that Jesus would build his church on Peter, the apostle: Jesus told Peter (Rock) that he would build his Church on this Rock (Peter), and that Peter was made the shepherd of the apostolic flock{{Bibleref2c|Jn|21:15-19}}\u2014hence their assertion of the Primacy of the Catholic Pontiff.\n\nOne Protestant view on the Matthew verse agrees with the Catholic view and again the disagreements about primacy stem from doctrinal sources, and disagreements such as those over the identification of Simon Peter with the Pope.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Other Protestants assert the following,{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} based specifically on the verse in Matthew:\n\nJesus gives Simon the new name ''petros''. However he refers to the \"rock\" as ''petra''. The inspired New Testament Scriptures were written in Greek, not Aramaic. [[Aramaic of Jesus|What Jesus ''might'' have said in Aramaic]] is conjecture. In Greek, there is a distinction between the two words, \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 being a \"rock\" but \u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 being a \"small stone\" or \"pebble\". (James G. McCarthy translates the two as \"mass of rock\" and \"boulder or detached stone\", respectively.){{Citation needed|date=March 2015}} Jesus is not referring to Peter when talking about \"this rock\", but is in fact referring to Peter's confession of faith in the preceding verses{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}. Jesus thus does not declare the primacy of Peter, but rather declares that his church will be built upon the foundation of the revelation of and confession of faith of Jesus as the Christ{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}.\n\nMany Protestant scholars, however, reject this position,{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}} <!-- Many, or one? --> such as Craig L. Blomberg who states, \"The expression \u2018this rock\u2019 almost certainly refers to Peter, following immediately after his name, just as the words following \u2018the Christ\u2019 in verse 16 applied to Jesus. The play on words in the Greek between Peter's name (Petros) and the word \u2018rock\u2019 (petra) makes sense only if Peter is the Rock and if Jesus is about to explain the significance of this identification.\" [New American Commentary: {{bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1998/9801word.asp |title=PETER IS THE ROCK (This Rock: January 1998) |publisher=Catholic.com |accessdate=2012-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726101430/http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1998/9801word.asp |archivedate=2011-07-26 }}</ref>\n\nDonald A. Carson III (Baptist and Professor of New Testament at Trinity Evangelical Seminary) states:\n{{quote|Although it is true that ''petros'' and ''petra'' can mean \"stone\" and \"rock\" respectively in earlier Greek, the distinction is largely confined to poetry. Moreover the underlying Aramaic is in this case unquestionable; and most probably ''kepha'' was used in both clauses (\"you are ''kepha''\" and \"on this ''kepha''\"), since the word was used both for a name and for a \"rock\". The Peshitta (written in Syriac, a language cognate with Aramaic) makes no distinction between the words in the two clauses. The Greek makes the distinction between ''petros'' and ''petra'' simply because it is trying to preserve the pun, and in Greek the feminine ''petra'' could not very well serve as a masculine name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://users.stargate.net/~elcore/kephas.htm |title=Who is the Rock? |publisher=Users.stargate.net |accessdate=2012-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216055823/http://users.stargate.net/~elcore/kephas.htm |archivedate=2012-02-16 }}</ref>}}\n\nAn alternate Protestant argument is that when Jesus said \"upon this rock\" in the aforementioned Matthew verse, he referred to himself, in reference to {{Bibleref2|Deuteronomy|32:3-4}}, which states that \"God...is the Rock, his work is perfect\". This idea also appears in {{Bibleref2|1 Corinthians|10:4}}, which says \"...that Rock is Christ.\" In {{Bibleref2|Ephesians|2:20}}, Jesus is called \"the chief cornerstone\".\n\n===Meaning of \"Rock\"===\n\nIn the original [[Greek language|Greek]] the word translated as \"Peter\" is ''\u03a0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2'' (Petros) and that translated as \"rock\" is ''\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1'' (petra), two words that, while not identical, give an impression of one of many times when Jesus used a play on words. Furthermore, since Jesus presumably spoke to Peter in their native [[Aramaic language]],{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} he would have used ''kepha'' in both instances.<ref name=\"keating\">{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.com/magazine/articles/peter-the-rock |title=Peter the Rock |publisher=Catholic Answers Magazine |date=October 1999 |accessdate=2012-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601121017/http://www.catholic.com/magazine/articles/peter-the-rock |archive-date=2016-06-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Peshitta Text and the Old Syriac text use the word \"kepha\" for both \"Peter\" and \"rock\" in {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peshitta.org/pdf/Mattich16.pdf |title=Peshitta Aramaic/English Interlinear New Testament|date= |accessdate=2012-07-22}}</ref> {{Bibleref2|John|1:42}} says Jesus called Simon \"Cephas\", as does Paul in some letters.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} He was instructed by Christ to strengthen his brethren, i.e., the apostles.{{Bibleref2c|Lk|22:31-32}} Peter also had a leadership role in the early Christian church at Jerusalem according to The Acts of the Apostles chapters 1\u20132, 10\u201311, and 15.\n\nEarly Catholic Latin and Greek writers (such as St. [[John Chrysostom]]) considered the \"foundation rock\" as applying to both Peter personally and his confession of faith (or the faith of his confession) symbolically, as well as seeing Christ's promise to apply more generally to his twelve apostles and the Church at large.<ref name=\"Veselin Kesich 1992 61\u201366\"/> This \"double meaning\" interpretation is present in the current ''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]''.<ref>''[[Catechism of the Catholic Church]]'', Articles 424 and 552</ref>\n\nProtestant counter-claims to the Catholic interpretation are largely based on the difference between the Greek words translated \"Rock\" in the Matthean passage. In classical Attic Greek ''petros'' generally meant \"pebble,\" while ''petra'' meant \"boulder\" or \"cliff.\" Accordingly, taking Peter's name to mean \"pebble,\" they argue that the \"rock\" in question cannot have been Peter, but something else, either Jesus himself, or the faith in Jesus that Peter had just professed. However, the New Testament was written in Koin\u00e9 Greek, not Attic Greek, and some authorities say no significant difference existed between the meanings of ''petros'' and ''petra''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n[[File:Gesupietrochiave.jpg|thumb|left|''Christ Handing the Keys to St Peter'', by [[Pietro Perugino]] (1481\u201382)]]\nHowever, even though the feminine noun ''petra'' is translated as ''rock'' in the phrase \"on this rock I will build my church,\" the word ''petra'' (\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 in Greek) is also used at {{Bibleref2|1Cor|10:4||1 Cor. 10:4}} in describing Jesus Christ, which reads: \"They all ate the same spiritual food and drank the same spiritual drink; for they drank from the spiritual rock that accompanied them, and that rock was Christ.\"\n\nAlthough {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16}} is used as a primary proof-text for the Catholic doctrine of Papal supremacy, Protestant scholars say that prior to the Reformation of the sixteenth century, Matthew 16 was very rarely used to support papal claims. Their position is that most of the early and medieval Church interpreted the 'rock' as being a reference either to Christ or to Peter's faith, not Peter himself. They understand Jesus' remark to have been his affirmation of Peter's testimony that Jesus was the Son of God.<ref>Mathison, Keith A., [https://books.google.com/books?id=w_PHAGr2TfgC ''The Shape of Sola Scriptura''], pp.184\u2013185</ref>\n\nAnother rebuttal of the Catholic position is that if ''Peter'' really means ''the Rock'' which makes him the chief of Apostles, it would contradict Bible's teaching in {{Bibleref2|Ephesians|2:20}} which says that the church's foundation is the apostles and prophets, not Peter alone. They posit that the meaning of {{Bibleref2|Matthew|16:18}} is that Jesus uses a play on words with Peter's name to say that the confession he had just made is the rock on which the church is built.<ref name=WELS-ROCK>{{cite web |url=http://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=813&cuItem_itemID=24624 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927075835/http://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=813&cuItem_itemID=24624 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=Matthew 16:18 - Peter, This Rock |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOther theologically conservative Christians, including Confessional Lutherans, also rebut comments made by Karl Keating and D.A. Carson who claim that there is no distinction between the words ''petros'' and ''petra'' in Koine Greek. The Lutheran theologians<ref>Danker, Frederick W., ''The concise Greek-English lexicon of the New Testament'', p. 282.</ref> state that the dictionaries of [[Koine Greek|Koine/NT Greek]], including the authoritative<ref>Rykle Borger, \"Remarks of an Outsider about Bauer's Worterbuch, BAGD, BDAG, and Their Textual Basis,\" Biblical Greek Language and Lexicography: Essays in Honor of Frederick W. Danker, Bernard A. Tayler (et al. eds.) pp. 32\u201347.</ref> [[Bauer lexicon|Bauer-Danker-Arndt-Gingrich Lexicon]], indeed list both words and the passages that give different meanings for each. Conservative Lutheran apologists state:\n\n{{quote|There is no biblical or historical evidence for the claims of the Roman Catholic church that Peter was the first pope. In fact there is no evidence that there even was a pope in the first century. Even Catholic historians recognize this as a historical fact....We honor Peter and in fact some of our churches are named after him, but he was not the first pope, nor was he Roman Catholic. If you read his first letter, you will see that he did not teach a Roman hierarchy, but that all Christians are royal priests.<ref name=WELS>{{cite web |url=https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=6106 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927214241/https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=6106 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=Responses to previous questions... |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Partial Protestant support===\n\nPartial support for the Catholic position comes from [[Oscar Cullmann]]. He disagrees with Luther and the Protestant reformers who held that by \"rock\" Christ did not mean Peter, but meant either himself or the faith of His followers. He believes the meaning of the original Aramaic is very clear: that \"Kepha\" was the Aramaic word for \"rock\", and that it was also the name by which Christ called Peter.<ref name=Time/>\n\nYet, Cullmann sharply rejects the Catholic claim that Peter began the papal succession. He writes: \"In the life of Peter there is no starting point for a chain of succession to the leadership of the church at large.\" While he believes the Matthew text is entirely valid and is in no way spurious, he says it cannot be used as \"warrant of the papal succession.\"<ref name=Time>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,890753-1,00.html Religion: Peter & the Rock.]\" \"Time,\" Dec. 07, 1953. Accessed Oct. 08, 2009</ref>\n\nCullmann concludes that while Peter ''was'' the original head of the apostles, Peter was not the founder of any visible church succession.<ref name=Time/>\n\nThere are other Protestant scholars who also partially defend the historical Catholic position about \"Rock.\"<ref>D. A. Carson in ''The Expositor's Bible Commentary'' (Grand Rapids: Zondervan, 1984).</ref> Taking a somewhat different approach from Cullman, they point out that the Gospel of Matthew was not written in the classical Attic form of Greek, but in the Hellenistic [[Koine Greek|Koine dialect]] in which there is no distinction in meaning between ''petros'' and ''petra''. Moreover, even in Attic Greek, in which the regular meaning of ''petros'' was a smallish \"stone,\" there are instances of its use to refer to larger rocks, as in [[Sophocles]], ''[[Oedipus at Colonus]]'' v. 1595, where ''petros'' refers to a boulder used as a landmark, obviously something more than a pebble. In any case, a ''petros''/''petra'' distinction is irrelevant considering the Aramaic language in which the phrase might well have been spoken. In Greek, of any period, the feminine noun ''petra'' could not be used as the given name of a male, which may explain the use of ''Petros'' as the Greek word with which to translate Aramaic ''Kepha''.<ref name=\"keating\" />\n\nYet, still other Protestant scholars believe that Jesus in fact ''did'' mean to single out Peter as the very rock which he will build upon, but that the passage does nothing to indicate a continued succession of Peter's implied position. They assert that Matthew uses the demonstrative pronoun ''taute'', which allegedly means \"this very\" or ''this same'', when he refers to the rock on which Jesus' church will be built. He also uses the Greek word for \"and\", ''kai''. It is alleged that when a demonstrative pronoun is used with ''kai'', the pronoun refers back to the preceding noun. The second rock Jesus refers to must then be the same rock as the first one; and if Peter is the first rock he must also be the second.<ref>''Jesus, Peter & the Keys: A Scriptural Handbook on the Papacy''</ref>\n\nThe [[New Apostolic Church]] believes in the re-established Apostle ministry. It sees Peter as the first [[Chief Apostle]] in the [[Early Church]].\n\n===Lutheran view===\nFrom the ''[[Book of Concord]]'': {{quote|Chrysostom says thus: \"Upon this rock,\" not upon Peter. For He built His Church not upon man, but upon the faith of Peter. But what was his faith? \"Thou art the Christ, the Son of the living God.\" And Hilary says: To Peter the Father revealed that he should say, \"Thou art the Son of the living God.\" Therefore, the building of the Church is upon this rock of confession; this faith is the foundation of the Church. \"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookofconcord.org/treatise.php |title=Treatise on the Power and Primacy of the Pope |publisher=Book of Concord |date= |accessdate=2012-07-16}}</ref>}}\n\nUnlike Oscar Cullmann, [[Confessional Lutherans]] and many other Protestant apologists agree that it's meaningless to elaborate the meaning of ''Rock'' by looking at the Aramaic language, this is true that the Jews spoke mostly Aramaic at home, however in public they usually spoke Greek. The few Aramaic words spoken by Jesus in public were unusual and that is why they are noted as such. And most importantly the New Testament was revealed in Koine Greek, ''not'' Aramaic.<ref name=WLS-Gawrisch>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/GawrischDoctrine.pdf |title=The Doctrine of Church and Ministry in the Life of the Church Today |last1=Gawrisch |first1=Wilbert R. |date=5 Aug 1991 |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203191915/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/GawrischDoctrine.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-03 }}</ref><ref name=WLS-Balge>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/BalgeMinistry.pdf \n |title=Cross-Cultural And Multicultural Ministry In The New Testament \n |last1=Balge \n |first1=Richard D. \n |date=6 June 1995 \n |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary \n |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203192344/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/BalgeMinistry.pdf \n |archivedate=2015-02-03 \n}}</ref><ref>[http://www.graceway.com/articles/article_017.htm ''Some thoughts on Matthew 16:18''] {{Dead link|date=February 2015}}</ref>\n\nModern Lutheran historians even disclose that the Catholic church didn't, at least unanimously, regard Peter as the ''Rock'' until the 1870s:\n\n{{quote|Rome's rule for explaining the Scriptures and determining doctrine is the [[Profession of faith (Catholic Church)#Tridentine Creed|Creed]] of [[Pius IV]]. This Creed binds Rome to explain the Scriptures only according to the unanimous consent of the Fathers. In the year 1870 when the Fathers gathered and the pope declared his infallibility, the cardinals were not in agreement on Matthew 16, 18. They had five different interpretations. Seventeen insisted, Peter is the rock. Sixteen held that Christ is the rock. Eight were emphatic that the whole apostolic college is the rock. Forty-four said, Peter's faith is the rock, The remainder looked upon the whole body of believers as the rock. \u2014 And yet Rome taught and still teaches that Peter is the rock.<ref name=WLS-Eckert>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlsessays.net/files/EckertSpecific.pdf |title=The Specific Functions of the Church in the World |last1=Eckert |first1=Harold H. |publisher=Wisconsin Lutheran Seminary |accessdate=4 Feb 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203182715/http://www.wlsessays.net/files/EckertSpecific.pdf |archivedate=2015-02-03 }}</ref>}}\n\nLutheran apologists criticize:\n\n{{quote|All of the arguments Roman Catholicism brings to set Peter up as the first Pope are done only to uphold its false teaching which says that people are saved, not by Christ's saving alone, but also by the deeds of penance they do. It is this teaching, which Roman Catholicism says has been taught by Popes ever since Peter, which also gives us the reason for the way Roman Catholicism interprets Mt 16:18.<ref name=WELS8752>{{cite web |url=https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=8572 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090927213504/https://www.wels.net/cgi-bin/site.pl?1518&cuTopic_topicID=19&cuItem_itemID=8572 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 September 2009 |work=WELS Topical Q&A |title=And On THIS ROCK I Will Build My Church... |publisher=Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod |accessdate=16 Mar 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\n==View of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints==\n[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS) accept the primacy of Peter, although it does not generally use the term. The LDS Church teaches that Peter was the chief apostle and head of the Church after Christ's ascension. The LDS Church further teaches that all [[Melchizedek Priesthood]] authority in the Church must come through a line of authority traceable directly from Christ through Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1996/12/the-restoration-of-the-aaronic-and-melchizedek-priesthoods?lang=eng|title = The Restoration of the Aaronic and Melchizedek Priesthoods}}</ref> However, in contrast to other groups, they believe that the line of succession was at some point broken following the death of the apostles, necessitating a restoration of the priesthood authority. The LDS Church teaches that this restoration occurred with the appearance of the resurrected Peter, James, and John, who ordained Joseph Smith and Oliver Cowdery in 1829.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1979/06/dating-the-restoration-of-the-melchizedek-priesthood?lang=eng|title = Dating the Restoration of the Melchizedek Priesthood}}</ref> All ordained members of the LDS Church can obtain a written line of authority tracing back to Christ through Peter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/help/support/request-a-priesthood-line-of-authority?lang=eng|title = Request a Priesthood Line of Authority}}</ref>\n\nDespite the acceptance of Peter's primacy, several leaders of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) have taught that the rock referred to by Jesus in Matthew 16:18 was neither Peter nor his confession, but the gift of [[revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]] from the [[Holy Spirit]] which made Christ's divinity known to Peter. [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|Apostle]] [[Howard W. Hunter]] taught: {{quote|\"And upon this rock I will build my church.\" Upon what rock? Peter? Upon a man? No, not upon a man, upon the rock of revelation, the thing which they were talking about. He had just said, \"... flesh and blood hath not revealed it unto thee, but my Father which is in heaven.\" This revelation that Jesus is the Christ is the foundation upon which he would build his Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-student-manual/introduction-to-matthew/chapter-6?lang=eng|title=New Testament Student Manual|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=31 Mar 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nChurch founder [[Joseph Smith]] is quoted as having said: {{quote|Jesus in His teachings says, \"Upon this rock I will build my Church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it.\" What rock? Revelation.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://www.lds.org/manual/teachings-joseph-smith/chapter-16|chapter=Chapter 16: Revelation and the Living Prophet |title=Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=31 Mar 2016|title-link=Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith }}</ref>}}\n\nIt is important to note that although these quotes may represent normative LDS belief, none of them are from canonized doctrinal sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/approaching-mormon-doctrine|title=Approaching Mormon Doctrine|date=2007-05-04}}</ref> The LDS Church therefore has no official doctrinal interpretation of Matthew 16:18 in this respect.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Apostolic succession|Apostolic Succession]]\n* [[Early Christianity]]\n* [[Historical episcopate]]\n* [[Papal infallibility]]\n* [[Papal supremacy]]\n* [[Petrine theory]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n* Addis, William E. & Thomas Arnold (rev. T.B. Scannell). ''Catholic Dictionary.'' (9th ed.) London: Virtue & Co., 1925. (Provides citations for the use of \"\u03c0\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2\" to mean \"rock\" in classical works)\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|\n\nurl=http://catholicity.elcore.net./SimonIsTheRock.html|\ntitle=Who is the Rock of Matthew 16:18?}}\n\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|url=http://www.geocities.com/getthefulltruth/Matt16vv17-19.html|title=Commentary on Matthew 16:17\u201319|work=The Catholic Evangel|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query.php?url=http://www.geocities.com/getthefulltruth/Matt16vv17-19.html|archivedate=August 11, 2006|url-status=dead}}\n\n* {{cite web|accessdate=June 21, 2005|\n\nurl=http://www.biblicalcatholic.com/apologetics/a64.htm|\ntitle=Section IV: Authority|\nwork=Refutation of James G. McCarthy's 'The Gospel According to Rome'}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Chadwick, Henry. ''The Church in Ancient Society: From Galilee to Gregory the Great''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001.\n*Collins, Paul. ''Upon This Rock: The Popes and their Changing Roles''. Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 2000.\n*Evans, G.R. ''The Church in the Early Middle Ages''. I.B. Tauris: New York, 2007.\n*Maxwell-Stuart, P.G. ''Chronicle of the Popes: the Reign-by-Reign Record of the Papacy from St. Peter to the Present''. 2nd ed. London : Thames & Hudson, 2006.\n* Meyendorff, John, ed. ''The Primacy of Peter: Essays in Ecclesiology and the Early Church''. ({{ISBN|0-88141-125-6}})\n*Perkins, Pheme. ''Peter: Apostle for the Whole Church''. Columbia: University of South Carolina Press, 1994.\n*Pham, John-Peter. ''Heirs of the Fisherman: Behind the Scenes of Papal Death and Succession''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2004.\n* Ray, Stephen K. ''Upon This Rock: St. Peter and the Primacy of Rome in Scripture and the Early Church''. ({{ISBN|0-89870-723-4}})\n*Winter, Michael M. ''Saint Peter and the Popes''. Baltimore: Helicon Press, 1960.\n\n{{Holy See}}\n{{Catholic Church footer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Primacy Of Simon Peter}}\n[[Category:Saint Peter]]\n[[Category:Bible-related controversies]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christianity]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Matthew]]\n[[Category:Papal primacy]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIndividuals and documents supporting Roman primacy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primacy_of_Peter"}
{"title_page": "Michael Cera", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Canadian actor}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Michael Cera 2012 (Cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Cera in 2012\n| birthname    = Michael Austin Cera\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|6|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| residence    = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| othername    = \n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|producer|singer|songwriter}}\n| yearsactive  = 1999\u20132020\n| homepage     = \n| module       = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi]]|[[indie folk]]}}\n| instruments = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|piano|keyboard|bass|drums|percussion}}\n| website = {{url|michaelceramusic.bandcamp.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Michael Austin Cera ''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u025b\u0259r|\u0259}}; {{IPA-it|\u02c8t\u0283e\u02d0ra|lang}}; born June 7, 1988)<ref>{{cite news| last =Schneller| first =Johanna| title =Triple threat| pages =R1\u20133| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-29}}</ref> was a Canadian actor, producer, singer, and songwriter. He started his career as a child actor, portraying a young [[Chuck Barris]] in ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'' (2002). He was known for his role as [[List of Arrested Development characters|George Michael Bluth]] on the sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019) and for his film roles as Evan in ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), as Paulie Bleeker in ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' (2007), as [[Scott Pilgrim]] in ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010), as a fictional version of himself in ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013), and as the voice of [[Dick Grayson]] / [[Robin (comics)|Robin]] in ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), as well as Sal Viscuso, the voice behind the announcements in ''[[Childrens Hospital]]''.\n\nCera made his [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] debut in the 2014 production of [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s ''[[This Is Our Youth]]''. For his performance in the 2018 production of Lonergan's ''[[Lobby Hero]]'', Cera was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Play]]. Cera most recently starred in the revival of Lonergan's ''[[The Waverly Gallery]]''.\n\nIn addition to acting, Cera was a musician, having released his debut album ''[[True That]]'' in 2014. Previously, Cera had also acted as the touring bassist for indie rock supergroup [[Mister Heavenly]].\n\nIn January of 2020 he passed away while choking on a grilled cheese in his moms house for a family celebration.\n\n==Early life==\nCera was born in [[Brampton]], Ontario. He is the son of Linda (n\u00e9e Cockman) and Luigi Cera, a technician. His father is [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]],<ref>Synnot, Siobhan (2009-01-25). \"Irresistible rise of the nerd\", ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'', p. 6.</ref> and his mother has Irish, Dutch, Scottish, and English ancestry.<ref name=\"Linda\">{{cite news|last=Rhodes|first=Joe|title='Superbad' \u2013 but in a good way|pages=|publisher=Springfield State Journal Register|date=2007-08-15|url=http://www.sj-r.com/Entertainment/stories/14299.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927001207/http://www.sj-r.com/Entertainment/stories/14299.asp|archivedate=2007-09-27|accessdate=2007-08-18}}</ref><ref name=thestar03>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Michael Cera: Colin is Farr' too boring |url=http://thestar.ie/about-us/michael-cera-colin-is-farr-too-boring/ |newspaper=[[Irish Daily Star]] |location= |date= |access-date=25 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815070143/http://thestar.ie/about-us/michael-cera-colin-is-farr-too-boring/ |archive-date=15 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His parents both worked for [[Xerox]].<ref name=\"Biography Today\">{{cite book|last=|first=|title=Biography Today|year=2009|page=[https://archive.org/details/biographytodayge0000unse/page/19 19]|publisher=Omnigraphics|location=[[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]|isbn=978-0-7808-1051-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/biographytodayge0000unse/page/19}}</ref> Cera has an older sister, Jordan, and a younger sister, Molly. He became interested in acting after viewing ''[[Ghostbusters]]'' repeatedly when sick with the [[chicken pox]] at the age of three.<ref name=\"WTF with Marc Maron, Ep. 265\">\"WTF with Marc Maron\", Ep. 265</ref> He memorized all the dialogue and idolized [[Bill Murray]].<ref name=\"Biography Today, pp.20\">\"Biography Today\", pp.20</ref> He enrolled in [[the Second City]] [[Toronto]] and took improvisation classes.<ref name=\"Biography Today, pp.20\"/>\n\nCera attended Conestoga Public School, Robert H. Lagerquist Senior Public School and [[Heart Lake Secondary School]] until grade nine, but then completed school online through grade 12.<ref name=\"Luigi\">{{cite news|last=Leszcz |first=Benjamin |title=The essence of adolescence |pages= |publisher=[[National Post]] |date=2006-01-04 |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=c6abbc16-63ed-4ada-bed8-20893c3e832e |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129141221/http://www.nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=c6abbc16-63ed-4ada-bed8-20893c3e832e |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-29 |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"Strauss\">{{cite news| last =Strauss| first =Bob| title =Hollywood heavy still a Brampton beanpole| page =R1| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1999\u20132008: Child acting and breakthrough===\nHis first role was an unpaid appearance in a [[Tim Hortons]] summer camp commercial.<ref name=\"Luigi\"/><ref name=\"Strauss\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Leszcz |first=Benjamin |title=Que Sera Cera |pages= |publisher=[[Toronto Life]] |date=August 2007 |url=http://www.torontolife.com/features/que-sera-cera/ |accessdate=2007-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223164253/http://www.torontolife.com/features/que-sera-cera/ |archivedate=2007-12-23 |df= }}</ref> That appearance eventually landed him a position in a Pillsbury commercial in which he poked the [[Pillsbury Doughboy]], his first role with lines.<ref name=Jones>Jones, Chris (July 2009), \"Michael Cera\". ''Esquire''. '''152''' (1):86\u201388</ref> He found not being cast in commercials after auditioning \"really disheartening\" but, in 1999, Cera was cast as Larrabe Hicks in the Canadian children's show ''[[I Was a Sixth Grade Alien]]'', which ran for two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Robert|title=He was a Sixth-Grade Alien: A Q&A with Michael Cera|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2008/10/he-was-a-sixth-grade-alien-a-qa-with-michael-cera.html|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|publisher=[[Wolfgang's Vault]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=October 13, 2008}}</ref> That year, he also appeared in the television films ''[[What Katy Did]]'' and ''[[Switching Goals]]'' starring the [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen twins]].<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\">{{cite web|last1=Hayes|first1=Britt|title=Way Back When: Michael|url=https://screencrush.com/way-back-when-michael-cera/|website=[[ScreenCrush]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Cera then made his theatrical film debut in the science fiction film ''[[Frequency (film)|Frequency]]'' (2000) as the son of [[Noah Emmerich]]'s character.<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\" /> Cera also appeared in the films ''[[Steal This Movie!]]'' and ''Ultimate G's: Zac's Flying Dream'' in 2000, the latter of which featured Cera in his first leading role and was presented in [[IMAX]] theaters.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMAX Theatre To launch Ultimate G's \u2013 Zac's flying dream in 3D|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2005-10-12/news/imax-theatre-to-launch-ultimate-gs-zacs-flying-dream-in-3d-82399/|website=[[The Malta Independent]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=12 October 2005}}</ref><ref name=Biography.com>{{cite web|title=Michael Cera Biography|url=https://www.biography.com/people/michael-cera-566896|website=[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=April 2, 2014}}</ref> Cera appeared in several television films in 2001 including ''[[My Louisiana Sky]]'' and ''[[The Familiar Stranger]]'' and also began voicing Josh Spitz in the animated series ''[[Braceface]]'', continuing to do so until 2004.<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\" /> In 2002, Cera played the young [[Chuck Barris]] (played by [[Sam Rockwell]]) in the [[George Clooney]]-directed film ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aftab|first1=Kaleem|title=Michael Cera: The geek who inherited the earth|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/michael-cera-the-geek-who-inherited-the-earth-8638387.html|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> He provided the voice for Brother Bear&nbsp;\u2013 an [[anthropomorphic]] [[bear]]&nbsp;\u2013 in the 2003 ''[[The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series)|The Berenstain Bears]]'' animated series, which aired for three seasons.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote=\"''Arrested Development'' never felt safe. Even the first season, we did thirteen episodes, and we thought we'd never do a back nine. So I never thought in a million years we'd get to make three seasons. I was happy we got that far. I thought it was really good, and I'm really proud of it. I don't think we made a bad episode.\"|source=\u2014Michael Cera, ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' (2009)<ref name=\"Jones\"/>}}\n\nFollowing a role in the critically panned unaired [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] pilot ''[[The Grubbs]]'' in 2002,<ref>\"Biography Today\", pp.21\u201323</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Cera successfully auditioned for a part in another Fox sitcom, ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', which began airing in November 2003.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The show follows the formerly wealthy and [[Dysfunctional family|dysfunctional]] Bluth family, with Cera playing [[George Michael Bluth]], the teenage son of [[Jason Bateman]]'s character, [[Michael Bluth]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chocano|first1=Carina|title=Arrested Development|url=https://ew.com/article/2003/11/07/arrested-development-3/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 7, 2003}}</ref> After three seasons, Fox canceled the series in 2006 due to low viewership despite critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chalk|first1=Will|title=Arrested Development: The show that can't be cancelled|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39960801/arrested-development-the-show-that-cant-be-cancelled|website=[[Newsbeat]]|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> In 2006, he created and starred in a parody of ''[[Impossible Is Nothing (video r\u00e9sum\u00e9)|Impossible is Nothing]]'', a video r\u00e9sum\u00e9 created by Aleksey Vayner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nAV0sxwx9rY |title=Youtube ''Impossible is the Opposite of Possible'' |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2006-12-20 |accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref> Cera and his ''Arrested Development'' co-star [[Alia Shawkat]] guest starred as a pair of college students in the teen noir drama ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' in the episode \"[[The Rapes of Graff]]\" in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1938062/veronica-mars-facts-trivia/|title=22 Facts Even Marshmallows May Not Know About Veronica Mars|work=[[MTV]]|last=Whitney|first=Alyse|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Along with best friend [[Clark Duke]], Cera wrote and starred in a series of short videos released on their website.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The idea came from Duke, who was enrolled at [[Loyola Marymount University]] and did it for his film school studies.<ref>\"Biography Today\", pp.24</ref> In 2007, they signed a deal with [[CBS Television]] to write, produce, direct, and act in a short-form comedy series entitled ''[[Clark and Michael]]''. The show featured guest stars such as [[David Cross]], [[Andy Richter]] and [[Patton Oswalt]], and was distributed via CBS's internet channel, [[CBS Innertube]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=''Wired'' Staff|title=Sitcom to Bitcom|url=https://www.wired.com/2007/03/snackfilmtv/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael Cera - 001.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Cera in 2007]]\nIn May 2007, Cera appeared in a staged comedy video that shows him being fired from the lead role of the film ''[[Knocked Up]]'' after belittling and arguing with its director [[Judd Apatow]], in a scene that mocks the [[David O. Russell]] blow up on the set of ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]''.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Cera then starred in the Apatow-produced teen comedy ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' alongside [[Jonah Hill]]. Their characters in the film&nbsp;\u2013 two [[virgin]] teenagers about to graduate from high school whose party plans go awry&nbsp;\u2013 were based on its writers [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patterson|first1=John|title=Comedy's new centre of gravity|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/sep/14/3|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=September 14, 2007}}</ref> ''Superbad'' was released in cinemas in August 2007, topping the US box office for two weeks in a row.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2376&p=.htm |first=Brandon |last=Gray |title='Superbad' Stays on Top |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> Cera's performance was met with critical acclaim, with ''[[The Atlantic]]'' opining that the film \"belongs to Michael Cera\" for capturing \"teenage sexual abashment as indelibly as he did in the role of George Michael\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Orr|first1=Christopher|title=The Movie Review: 'Superbad'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2007/08/the-movie-review-superbad/69238/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 13, 2007}}</ref> while ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt he was \"excellent\" and [[CNN]] praised Cera and Hill for playing \"off each other beautifully\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dargis|first1=Manohla|title=For Three Virgins, the Path to Sunrise Is Paved With Excess|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/17/movies/17supe.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 17, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Charity|first1=Tom|title=Review: 'Superbad' funniest comedy since 'Borat'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Movies/08/16/review.superbad/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Cera hosted an untelevised live staged version of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', not broadcast due to the then-ongoing [[2007 Writers Guild of America Strike]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=Strike or No Strike, for a Select Few, Saturday Night Was Live|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/19/arts/television/19snl.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 19, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Strauss| first =Bob| title =Hollywood heavy still a Brampton beanpole| page =R1| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-08}}</ref> In his second film of 2007, Cera co-starred in ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' as Paulie Bleeker, a teenager who impregnates his long-time school friend Juno (played by [[Ellen Page]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Venutolo|first1=Anthony|title=Deadpan delivery: Michael Cera takes a romantic turn|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2007/12/deadpan_delivery_michael_cera.html|publisher=[[NJ.com]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 20, 2007}}</ref> For ''Superbad'' and ''Juno'', Cera won Breakthrough Artist in the [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2007]]\nand was included in ''[[Entertainment Weekly|Entertainment Weekly's]]'' 30 Under 30 list in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austin Film Critics Association Announces Top Pic(k)s|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2007-12-21/574157/|website=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Markovitz|first1=Adam|last2=Stransky|first2=Tanner|title=30 Under 30: The Actors|url=https://ew.com/gallery/30-under-30-actors/1|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=February 27, 2008}}</ref> Cera starred alongside [[Kat Dennings]] in the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Nick & Norah's Infinite Playlist]]'' (2008), in which they played two strangers who bond over their shared love of a band and try to find their secret show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=A.O.|authorlink1=A.O. Scott|title=For Muddled Youth, Music to Live By|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/19/arts/television/19snl.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref> He then starred in the comedy ''[[Extreme Movie]]'' (2008), which was composed of vignettes focusing on [[teen sex]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Extreme Movie (2008)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/extreme_movie/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Cera held a recurring role on the comedy series ''[[Childrens Hospital]]'' from 2008 to 2016 as Sal Viscuso, a hospital staffer who is only ever heard through an [[intercom]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Idasetima|first1=Courtney|title=The Cast of 'Juno,' Then and Now|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/cast-juno-1054254|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132013: Varied success and stage debut===\n[[File:Michael Cera as Captain America by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Cera dressed as [[Captain America]] to promote ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic Con]]]]\nCera played a fictionalized version of himself in the independent romantic comedy ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]'' (2009), which followed the fictional relationship between Cera and the film's writer [[Charlyne Yi]], also playing herself. Cera and Yi composed the film's score together.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Catsoulis|first1=Jeannette|title=Out on the Highways in Search of Love, an Endlessly Elusive Quest|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/07/movies/07paper.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Cera then starred opposite [[Jack Black]] in the comedy ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'', set during the [[Stone Age]]. The film, directed by [[Harold Ramis]], was poorly received, although ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine critic Mary Pols felt Cera's performance saved the film from being a \"catastrophe\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pols|first1=Mary|title=Year One: Jokes from the Stone Age|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1905453,00.html|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 18, 2009}}</ref> In his final film of 2009, Cera starred in ''[[Youth in Revolt (film)|Youth in Revolt]]'', an adaptation of the [[Youth in Revolt|eponymous novel]]. He played a shy teenager named Nick Twisp who creates a destructive [[alter ego]], Fran\u00e7ois Dillinger, after becoming smitten with a girl, who is played by [[Portia Doubleday]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|last=Male|first=Andrew|title=Sardonic youth|pages=|publisher=Guardian Unlimited|date=2007-09-15|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/sep/15/1|accessdate=2007-09-15 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"twisp\">{{cite news|last=Dimension Films|first=|title=Michael Cera Is Nick Twisp|pages=|publisher=MovieWeb|date=2007-08-15|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/91/21991.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181328/http://www.movieweb.com/news/91/21991.php|archivedate=2007-09-30|accessdate=2007-08-19}}</ref> Cera's first published short story, \"Pinecone\", appeared in ''[[Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern#30|McSweeney's Quarterly]]'' thirtieth issue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Toole|first1=Kristen|title=Fiction Fix: \"Pinecone\" by Michael Cera (plus bonus non-fiction by Matthew Derby!)|url=http://flavorwire.com/16351/fiction-fix-pinecone-by-michael-cera-plus-bonus-non-fiction-by-matthew-derby|website=[[Flavorwire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=April 1, 2009}}</ref> Cera was cast as [[Scott Pilgrim]] in the film adaptation of the [[graphic novel]] series by [[Bryan Lee O'Malley]] after the film's director [[Edgar Wright]] had seen ''Arrested Development'' and needed an actor \"audiences will still follow even when the character is being a bit of an ass\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Nancy|title=Director Edgar Wright, Actor Michael Cera Crack Wise About Scott Pilgrim|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/06/ff_cerawright/all/1/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 22, 2010}}</ref> The film, ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'', follows Pilgrim, a musician who must battle the seven evil exes of his girlfriend [[Ramona Flowers|Ramona]] (played by [[Mary Elizabeth Winstead]]). It was released in cinemas in August 2010, whereupon it became a [[box office bomb]] after just grossing $47.7&nbsp;million against a production budget of $85\u201390&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mercer|first1=Benjamin|title='Scott Pilgrim vs. the World': From Box Office Flop to Cult Classic?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2010/11/scott-pilgrim-vs-the-world-from-box-office-flop-to-cult-classic/66453/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=November 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Scott Pilgrim vs. The World (2010)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=scottpilgrim.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCera made a guest appearance in \"[[The Daughter Also Rises]]\", a 2012 episode of the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as the voice of Nick, a love interest to [[Lisa Simpson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Snierson|first1=Dan|title=Michael Cera to guest on 'The Simpsons'|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/06/02/michael-cera-the-simpsons/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 2, 2011}}</ref> Cera made his theater debut in a production of [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s play ''[[This Is Our Youth]]'' in a two-week run during March 2012 at the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The play also featured his ''Scott Pilgrim'' co-star [[Kieran Culkin]] and [[Tavi Gevinson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hardie|first1=Giles|title=Never grows old|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/never-grows-old-20120307-1ul64.html|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=March 9, 2012}}</ref> A [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production at the [[Cort Theater]] opened in September 2014 and closed in January 2015. ''[[The New York Times]]'' theater critic [[Ben Brantley]] praised Cera for achieving \"something remarkable\": \"the sense of an amorphous being assuming and losing shape in the course of roughly 12 hours\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|authorlink1=Ben Brantley|title=Desperate Fledglings, Flung From the Nest|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/12/theater/this-is-our-youth-stars-michael-cera-kieran-culkin-and-tavi-gevinson.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=September 11, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2012, Cera played a supporting role in the drama ''[[The End of Love]]'' and appeared in the short film ''The Immigrant''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Sam|title=The End Of Love|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-end-of-love-1798175965|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=February 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Megh|title=Check Out Scott Thompson's Short Film 'The Immigrant' with Dave Foley, Michael Cera, Margaret Cho, and Will Forte|url=http://splitsider.com/2014/02/check-out-scott-thompsons-short-film-the-immigrant-with-michael-cera-margaret-cho-and-will-forte/|website=[[Splitsider]]|publisher=[[The Awl]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> ''Arrested Development'' was revived for a fourth season in 2012 by [[Netflix]], with Cera reprising his role as George Michael. Cera worked in the writer's room and served as a consulting producer during its production.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Jason|title=How Jesse Eisenberg Became More Annoyingly Awkward Than Michael Cera|url=http://flavorwire.com/395776/how-jesse-eisenberg-became-more-annoyingly-awkward-than-michael-cera|website=[[Flavorwire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 4, 2013|quote=he was actively involved in the show's production, working in the writers' room and credited as a consulting producer}}</ref> The season was released in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Itzkoff|first1=Dave|title=New 'Arrested Development' Season Coming to Netflix on May 26|url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/04/new-arrested-development-season-coming-to-netflix-on-may-26/|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=April 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCera collaborated with Chilean filmmaker [[Sebasti\u00e1n Silva (director)|Sebasti\u00e1n Silva]] on two films in 2013&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Magic Magic (2013 film)|Magic Magic]]'' and ''[[Crystal Fairy & the Magical Cactus]]''&nbsp;\u2013 both of which were filmed in Chile and premiered at the [[2013 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Magic Magic Crystal Fairy\">{{cite web|last1=McCarthy|first1=Todd|title=Crystal Fairy & the Magic Cactus and 2012: Sundance Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crystal-fairy-magic-cactus-2012-413569|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref> He spent \"five hours a day learning [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\" for ''Magic Magic''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/movies/juno-star-michael-cera-takes-spanish-second-language|title=\"Juno\" Star Michael Cera Takes Up Spanish as a Second Language| first=Lee| last=Hernandez|publisher=[[Latina magazine]]|date=2011-02-11 |accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref> Cera was featured most prominently in ''Crystal Fairy'', in which he starred as a self-absorbed man travelling Chile with a woman named \"Crystal Fairy\" (played by [[Gaby Hoffmann]]) while bearing a [[cactus]].<ref name=\"Magic Magic Crystal Fairy\" /> Along with [[Reggie Watts]], [[Tim & Eric]], and [[Sarah Silverman]], Cera created the [[web-based]] comedy [[YouTube]] channel [[Jash]] in March 2013, where he has posted short films which he directs and/or stars in.<ref name=\"USA Today Introduces Jash\">{{cite news|last=Matheson|first=Whitney|title=JASH: Your fave comedians launch a YouTube channel|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2013/03/11/jash-youtube/1978521/|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Rolling Stone Magazine Introduces Jash\">{{cite news|last=Danton|first=Eric R.|title=Sarah Silverman, Michael Cera Launch JASH Comedy Channel on YouTube|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/videos/sarah-silverman-michael-cera-launch-jash-comedy-channel-on-youtube-20130311|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]|date=2013-03-11}}</ref> These films include the comedy-drama ''[[Gregory Go Boom]]'' (2013), in which Cera played a [[Hereditary spastic paraplegia|paraplegic]] man, and his directorial debut ''Brazzaville Teen-Ager'' (2013), co-starring [[Charles Grodin]] as his sick father.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travers|first1=Ben|title=Watch: Michael Cera Plays a Paraplegic in New Short Film 'Gregory Go Boom'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/05/watch-michael-cera-plays-a-paraplegic-in-new-short-film-gregory-go-boom-38202/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=May 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitney|first1=Erin|title=Watch: Michael Cera Makes His Directorial Debut With Short Film 'Brazzaville Teen-Ager'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/04/watch-michael-cera-makes-his-directorial-debut-with-short-film-brazzaville-teen-ager-39183/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> He played an exaggerated version of himself in the apocalyptic comedy film ''[[This Is the End]]'', which was released in summer of 2013 and featured his ''Superbad'' co-stars Jonah Hill and Seth Rogen.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rob |last=Bricken |title=The new This Is the End redband trailer contains Michael Cera's graphic death. That is all. |url=http://io9.com/the-new-this-is-the-end-redband-trailer-contains-michae-465827952 |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[io9]] |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=April 6, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FffhZFW6 |archivedate=April 6, 2013 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Throughout 2013, Cera also appeared on ''[[Burning Love (web series)|Burning Love]]'', a web spoof of [[Reality television#Reality competition/game shows|reality dating]] competition shows,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Busis|first1=Hillary|title='Burning Love' returns, with Michael Cera, Colin Hanks, & Nick Kroll|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/24/burning-love-season-2/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> and on an episode of ''[[Drunk History]]'' as [[John Endecott]]. Cera had previously played [[Alexander Hamilton]] in a comedic retelling of [[Burr-Hamilton duel|Hamilton's duel]] with [[Aaron Burr]] on the show's first episode as a web series in 2008 before it was adapted into a television show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cowen|first1=Trace William|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda Gets Hilariously Sloshed for 'Drunk History' Version of 'Hamilton'|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2016/11/lin-manuel-miranda-drunk-history-hamilton|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present===\nCera appeared in his ''Arrested Development'' co-star [[David Cross]]' 2014 film ''[[Hits (film)|Hits]]'', playing a [[marijuana]] [[drug dealer|dealer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Photos: Michael Cera on the Set of David Cross's ''Hits''|url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/10/michael-cera-on-set-david-cross-hits.html|website=[[Vulture (web site)|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York Media, LLC]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=November 11, 2013}}</ref> He also co-starred alongside [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] and [[Sally Hawkins]] in [[Charlie Kaufman]]'s [[television pilot]] ''How & Why'', which was rejected by [[FX (TV channel)|FX]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=FX Passes on Charlie Kaufman Comedy 'How & Why|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fx-passes-charlie-kaufman-comedy-719856|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=July 21, 2014}}</ref> After a brief, \"menacing\" appearance in the drama ''[[Entertainment (2015 film)|Entertainment]]'' (2015),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dowd|first1=A.A.|title=''Entertainment'' gives Neil Hamburger the alienating star vehicle he deserves|url=https://film.avclub.com/entertainment-gives-neil-hamburger-the-alienating-star-1798185615|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> Cera appeared in the [[prequel]] to the 2001 comedy film ''[[Wet Hot American Summer]]'', the comedy series ''[[Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp]]'' and in the Christmas musical comedy film ''[[A Very Murray Christmas]]'' as [[Bill Murray]]'s fictional talent agent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Matt|title=10 Things That Save Bill Murray's Netflix Christmas Special|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a40209/bill-murray-christmas-special/|website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> Cera then voiced a [[hot dog]] trying to escape his fate in a supermarket in the animated comedy ''[[Sausage Party]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Chval\">{{cite web|last1=Chval|first1=Lauren|title=Interview: Michael Cera talks 'Sausage Party,' acting on Broadway and the 'Twin Peaks' reboot|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-interview-michael-cera-sausage-party-20160809-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Cera made a cameo on [[Louis C.K.]]'s ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'' on [[FX (TV channel)|FX]], in the season five episode \"Sleepover\" alongside [[Glenn Close]], [[John Lithgow]], and [[Matthew Broderick]].<ref>https://tv.avclub.com/louie-sleepover-1798183816</ref>\n\nCera had five film releases in 2017, the first of which was the animated superhero comedy ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'', which featured Cera as the voice of the [[Batman]]'s sidekick [[Robin (character)|Robin]].<ref name=\"Chval\" /> He then played a supporting role as a sleazy [[car salesman]] in the comedy ''[[How to Be a Latin Lover]]'' and co-starred in the comedy-drama ''[[Lemon (2017 film)|Lemon]]'' as an actor with a \"wedge of hair that makes him look like [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin]] crossed with ''[[Eraserhead]]''\", as described by ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' critic [[Owen Gleiberman]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schager|first1=Nick|title='How to Be a Latin Lover' Exclusive Clip: Eugenio Derbez as a Boy Toy Ditched for a Newer Model|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/latin-lover-exclusive-clip-eugenio-derbez-boy-toy-ditched-newer-model-170039255.html|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=April 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gleiberman|first1=Owen|title=Film Review: 'Lemon'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/lemon-review-sundance-1201969953/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Cera starred opposite [[Abbi Jacobson]] in the drama ''[[Person to Person (film)|Person to Person]]'', focusing on the struggles of different people over the course of one day in [[New York City]] and featured Cera and Jacobson as a pair of crime reporters investigating a possible murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Benjamin|title=Person to Person review \u2013 Broad City star underused in meandering ensemble indie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/20/person-to-person-review-broad-city-star-abbi-jacobson-michael-cera|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In his final film of the year, [[Aaron Sorkin]]'s crime drama ''[[Molly's Game]]'', Cera played a celebrity known only as Player X who participates in a high-stakes underground poker empire run by [[Molly Bloom (author)|Molly Bloom]] (played by [[Jessica Chastain]]). Cera's fictional character in the film was a [[composite character]] of real-life celebrity poker players [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Tobey Maguire]] and [[Ben Affleck]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Hilary|title='Molly's Game' Team Talks Making Timely Tale of Female Empowerment|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jessica-chastain-aaron-sorkins-mollys-game-molly-bloom-sexual-misconduct-claims-michael-cera-player-1070323|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA \"giant fan\" of director [[David Lynch]],<ref name=\"Chval\" /> Cera made a guest appearance in the [[Twin Peaks (season 3)|2017 revival]] of Lynch and [[Mark Frost]]'s television show ''[[Twin Peaks]]'' in the show's fourth episode, as Wally \"Brando\" Brennan, the son of Deputy Sheriff [[List of Twin Peaks characters#Andy Brennan|Andy Brennan]] and [[Lucy Moran|Lucy Brennan]].<ref name=\"WallyBrando\">{{cite web|last1=Nguyen|first1=Hanh|title='Twin Peaks' MVP Wally Brando: 5 Reasons Michael Cera's Brilliant Cameo Is Just What the Show Needed|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/05/twin-peaks-wally-brando-michael-sera-marlon-brando-wild-one-1201834109/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref> The appearance contained several references to the work of actor [[Marlon Brando]] as Wally shares the same birthday and is nicknamed after Brando.<ref name=\"WallyBrando\" />\n\nCera returned to the stage in March 2018, starring in a second Kenneth Lonergan production, ''[[Lobby Hero]]'', at the [[Helen Hayes Theatre]] on Broadway. The play also stars [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]], [[Brian Tyree Henry]] and [[Bel Powley]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vine|first1=Hannah|title=Michael Cera, Chris Evans, and the Cast of ''Lobby Hero'' Meet the Press|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/michael-cera-chris-evans-and-the-cast-of-lobby-hero-meet-the-press|website=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Cera and Henry are both nominated for [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]] at the [[72nd Tony Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Libbey|first1=Peter|title=Tony Awards 2018: Full List of Nominations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/01/theater/tony-awards-nominees-list.html|accessdate=May 22, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCera appeared onstage again in October 2018, starring in the third Kenneth Lonergan production, this time a revival of ''[[The Waverly Gallery]]'' at the [[John Golden Theatre]] on Broadway. The play also starred [[Elaine May]], [[Lucas Hedges]], and [[Joan Allen]].<ref>https://www.broadway.com/shows/waverly-gallery/</ref>\n\nCera co-starred in the 2018 drama ''[[Gloria Bell]]'', with [[Julianne Moore]] as the title character.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=John Turturro and Newcomer Caren Pistorius Join Julianne Moore in 'Gloria' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/john-turturro-caren-pistorious-gloria-julianna-more-1202617002/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> Cera's upcoming projects include the animated comedy ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' about a dog who wishes to become a samurai.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title='Blazing Samurai' Lands A-List Voice Talent Led By Samuel L. Jackson|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/blazing-samurai-animated-feature-samuel-l-jackson-mel-brooks-george-takei-1201605395/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=November 3, 2015}}</ref> Cera returned to his role as George Michael in the fifth season of ''[[Arrested Development (season 5)|Arrested Development]]'' in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elise Sandberg|first1=Bryn|title='Arrested Development' Officially Renewed for Season 5 at Netflix|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/arrested-development-officially-renewed-season-5-at-netflix-1004529|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[File:Michael Cera 2011.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Cera performing in 2011]]\nIn 2010 Cera contributed mandolin and backing vocals to the [[Weezer]] song \"Hang On\" from their album ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]''.<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web|last=Dorof|first=Jakob|title=Weezer \u2013 Hurley|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/weezer-hurley/2247|work=Slantmagazine|accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref>\nCera has also established himself as the touring bass player in [[Mister Heavenly]], an indie rock band originating in the American northwest,<ref>{{cite web|author=Erik Ziedses des Plantes |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/michael-cera-is-apparently-mister-heavenlys-bassis/46626/ |title=Michael Cera Is Apparently Mister Heavenly's Bassist |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref> and is a member of the band [[The Long Goodbye (band)|The Long Goodbye]], along with [[Clark Duke]].<ref name=\"spin-1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.spin.com/2007/08/michael-ceras-long-goodbye/ | title=Michael Cera's Long Goodbye | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=August 22, 2007 | accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Cera also played bass and sang back up during songs in both ''Scott Pilgrim vs. the World'' and ''Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist''. He released his full-length debut album ''[[True That]]'' on August 8, 2014, through his official [[Bandcamp]] page.<ref name=\"p4k-album\">{{cite web | url=https://pitchfork.com/news/56299-michael-cera-released-a-surprise-album-last-night/ | title=Michael Cera Released a Surprise Album Last Night | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Gordon, Jeremy}}</ref><ref name=\"teleg\">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11031409/Michael-Cera-releases-album-online.html | title=Michael Cera releases album online | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Travis, Ben}}</ref> The album features 19 original tracks, a cover of [[Roderick Falconer]]'s \"Play It Again\" as well as a cover of [[Blaze Foley]]'s \"Clay Pigeons.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/08/13/stream-michael-cera-album/ | title=Michael Cera Quietly Releases an Album That You Can Stream | publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Todd Olmstead}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Canadian musician [[Alden Penner]] released \"Meditate\", a track from his upcoming [[Extended Play|EP]] ''Canada in Space'', which features Cera. Penner subsequently announced that the EP would be released on 29 June 2015 on [[City Slang]] records, as well as a European tour of the UK, Netherlands, France, and Germany, which featured Cera as both co-headliner and member of Penner's backing band.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Camp|first1=Zoe|title=The Unicorns' Alden Penner Teams With Michael Cera for New EP and Tour|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/59411-the-unicorns-alden-penner-teams-with-michael-cera-for-new-ep-and-tour/|website=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc.|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=music|first1=Guardian|title=Michael Cera to tour with the Unicorns' Alden Penner|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/apr/28/michael-cera-to-tour-with-the-unicorns-alden-penner|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd.|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> The song \"Best I Can\" from the film ''[[Dina (film)|Dina]]'', written and performed by Cera and featuring [[Sharon Van Etten]], was unsuccessfully nominated for Best Song In A Documentary at the 2017 Critics' Choice Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/ |title=Documentary Awards - Critics' Choice AwardsCritics' Choice Awards |publisher=Criticschoice.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-29 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20171112085340/http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/ |archive-date=2017-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2000 || ''[[Frequency (film)|Frequency]]'' || Gordy Hersch Jr. (Age 10) ||\n|-\n| ''[[Steal This Movie!]]'' || [[Abbie Hoffman|America Hoffman]] (Age 7\u20138) ||\n|-\n| ''Ultimate G's: Zac's Flying Dream'' || Young Zac ||\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'' || [[Chuck Barris]] (Age 8\u201311) ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007 || ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' || Evan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' ||Paulie Bleeker ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008 || ''[[Extreme Movie]]'' || Fred ||\n|-\n| ''[[Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist]]'' || Nick O'Leary ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2009 || ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]'' || Himself ||\n|-\n| ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'' || Oh ||\n|-\n| ''[[Youth in Revolt (film)|Youth in Revolt]]'' || Nick Twisp / Fran\u00e7ois Dillinger ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010 || ''Scott Pilgrim vs. the Animation'' || [[Scott Pilgrim]] (voice) || [[Short film]]\n|-\n| ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' || Scott Pilgrim ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012 || ''[[The End of Love]] || Michael ||\n|-\n| ''The Immigrant'' || Michael || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2013 || ''[[Crystal Fairy & the Magical Cactus]]'' || Jamie ||\n|-\n| ''[[Magic Magic (2013 film)|Magic Magic]] || Brink || Also executive producer\n|-\n| ''Brazzaville Teen-Ager'' || Gunther || Short film; also director and writer\n|-\n| ''Failure'' || Man || Short film; also director and writer\n|-\n| ''[[This Is the End]]'' || Himself ||\n|-\n| ''[[Gregory Go Boom]]'' || Gregory || Short film\n|-\n| ''[[imdbtitle:3228404|Bitch]]''|| Himself || Short film; also director and writer\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Hits (film)|Hits]]'' || Bennie ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2015 || ''[[Entertainment (2015 film)|Entertainment]]'' || Tommy || \n|-\n| ''That Dog'' || Tim || Short film\n|-\n| ''[[A Very Murray Christmas]]'' || Jackie the Talent Agent || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016 || ''[[Sausage Party]]'' || Barry (voice) ||\n|-\n| ''Man Rots from the Head '' || Sydney Ward || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2017 || ''[[Person to Person (film)|Person to Person]]'' || Phil || \n|-\n| ''[[Lemon (2017 film)|Lemon]]'' || Alex || \n|-\n| ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' || [[Dick Grayson|Richard \"Dick\" Grayson]] / [[Robin (comics)|Robin]] (voice) || \n|-\n| ''[[How to Be a Latin Lover]]'' || Remy || \n|-\n| ''[[Molly's Game]]'' || Player X || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| ''[[Tyrel (film)|Tyrel]]'' || Alan || \n|-\n| ''Spivak'' || Robby LeBeau ||\n|-\n| ''[[Gloria Bell]]'' || Peter || \n|-\n| 2021 || ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' || Hank (voice) || Post-production\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| clas