e Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Next Generation|Breakthrough Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| ''Juno''\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss|Best Kiss]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Actor in a Movie|Best Male Performance]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| ''[[Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist]]''\n| |[[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor: Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| ''Superbad''\n| rowspan=5|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor: Comedy\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie Breakout: Male\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|''Juno''\n| Best Movie Actor: Comedy\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie Breakout: Male\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Himself\n| Choice Comedian\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 |2009\n| colspan=\"2\"|[[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| ''Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist''\n|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor: Music/Dance\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]''\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor: Comedy or Musical]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor: Action\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Arrested Development''\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Lobby Hero]]''\n| [[Tony Awards]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of former child actors from Canada]]\n*[[Italians in Toronto]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT ADD LINKS TO FANSITES HERE -->\n<!--   THEY WILL JUST BE REMOVED PER WP:EL    -->\n*{{IMDb name|id=0148418|name=Michael Cera}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160525094534/http://www.the1secondfilm.com/crew/130806 Michael Cera's Crew Profile on The 1 Second Film]\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT ADD LINKS TO FANSITES HERE -->\n<!--   THEY WILL JUST BE REMOVED PER WP:EL    -->\n{{Satellite Award Best Actor Motion Picture}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cera, Michael}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian television writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Ontario]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:People from Brampton]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Mister Heavenly members]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Canadian actor}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Michael Cera 2012 (Cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Cera in 2012\n| birthname    = Michael Austin Cera\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|6|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Brampton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| residence    = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| othername    = \n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|producer|singer|songwriter}}\n| yearsactive  = 1999\u2013present\n| homepage     = \n| module       = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Lo-fi music|Lo-fi]]|[[indie folk]]}}\n| instruments = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|piano|keyboard|bass|drums|percussion}}\n| website = {{url|michaelceramusic.bandcamp.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Michael Austin Cera ''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u025b\u0259r|\u0259}}; {{IPA-it|\u02c8t\u0283e\u02d0ra|lang}}; born June 7, 1988)<ref>{{cite news| last =Schneller| first =Johanna| title =Triple threat| pages =R1\u20133| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-29}}</ref> is a Canadian actor, producer, singer, and songwriter. He started his career as a child actor, portraying a young [[Chuck Barris]] in ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'' (2002). He is known for his role as [[List of Arrested Development characters|George Michael Bluth]] on the sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019) and for his film roles as Evan in ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), as Paulie Bleeker in ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' (2007), as [[Scott Pilgrim]] in ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010), as a fictional version of himself in ''[[This Is the End]]'' (2013), and as the voice of [[Dick Grayson]] / [[Robin (comics)|Robin]] in ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'' (2017), as well as Sal Viscuso, the voice behind the announcements in ''[[Childrens Hospital]]''.\n\nCera made his [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] debut in the 2014 production of [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s ''[[This Is Our Youth]]''. For his performance in the 2018 production of Lonergan's ''[[Lobby Hero]]'', Cera was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Play]]. Cera most recently starred in the revival of Lonergan's ''[[The Waverly Gallery]]''.\n\nIn addition to acting, Cera is a musician, having released his debut album ''[[True That]]'' in 2014. Previously, Cera has also acted as the touring bassist for indie rock supergroup [[Mister Heavenly]].\n\n==Early life==\nCera was born in [[Brampton]], Ontario. He is the son of Linda (n\u00e9e Cockman) and Luigi Cera, a technician. His father is [[Sicilian people|Sicilian]],<ref>Synnot, Siobhan (2009-01-25). \"Irresistible rise of the nerd\", ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'', p. 6.</ref> and his mother has Irish, Dutch, Scottish, and English ancestry.<ref name=\"Linda\">{{cite news|last=Rhodes|first=Joe|title='Superbad' \u2013 but in a good way|pages=|publisher=Springfield State Journal Register|date=2007-08-15|url=http://www.sj-r.com/Entertainment/stories/14299.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927001207/http://www.sj-r.com/Entertainment/stories/14299.asp|archivedate=2007-09-27|accessdate=2007-08-18}}</ref><ref name=thestar03>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Michael Cera: Colin is Farr' too boring |url=http://thestar.ie/about-us/michael-cera-colin-is-farr-too-boring/ |newspaper=[[Irish Daily Star]] |location= |date= |access-date=25 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815070143/http://thestar.ie/about-us/michael-cera-colin-is-farr-too-boring/ |archive-date=15 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His parents both worked for [[Xerox]].<ref name=\"Biography Today\">{{cite book|last=|first=|title=Biography Today|year=2009|page=[https://archive.org/details/biographytodayge0000unse/page/19 19]|publisher=Omnigraphics|location=[[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]|isbn=978-0-7808-1051-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/biographytodayge0000unse/page/19}}</ref> Cera has an older sister, Jordan, and a younger sister, Molly. He became interested in acting after viewing ''[[Ghostbusters]]'' repeatedly when sick with the [[chicken pox]] at the age of three.<ref name=\"WTF with Marc Maron, Ep. 265\">\"WTF with Marc Maron\", Ep. 265</ref> He memorized all the dialogue and idolized [[Bill Murray]].<ref name=\"Biography Today, pp.20\">\"Biography Today\", pp.20</ref> He enrolled in [[the Second City]] [[Toronto]] and took improvisation classes.<ref name=\"Biography Today, pp.20\"/>\n\nCera attended Conestoga Public School, Robert H. Lagerquist Senior Public School and [[Heart Lake Secondary School]] until grade nine, but then completed school online through grade 12.<ref name=\"Luigi\">{{cite news|last=Leszcz |first=Benjamin |title=The essence of adolescence |pages= |publisher=[[National Post]] |date=2006-01-04 |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=c6abbc16-63ed-4ada-bed8-20893c3e832e |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129141221/http://www.nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=c6abbc16-63ed-4ada-bed8-20893c3e832e |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-29 |accessdate=2007-08-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"Strauss\">{{cite news| last =Strauss| first =Bob| title =Hollywood heavy still a Brampton beanpole| page =R1| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1999\u20132008: Child acting and breakthrough===\nHis first role was an unpaid appearance in a [[Tim Hortons]] summer camp commercial.<ref name=\"Luigi\"/><ref name=\"Strauss\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Leszcz |first=Benjamin |title=Que Sera Cera |pages= |publisher=[[Toronto Life]] |date=August 2007 |url=http://www.torontolife.com/features/que-sera-cera/ |accessdate=2007-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223164253/http://www.torontolife.com/features/que-sera-cera/ |archivedate=2007-12-23 |df= }}</ref> That appearance eventually landed him a position in a Pillsbury commercial in which he poked the [[Pillsbury Doughboy]], his first role with lines.<ref name=Jones>Jones, Chris (July 2009), \"Michael Cera\". ''Esquire''. '''152''' (1):86\u201388</ref> He found not being cast in commercials after auditioning \"really disheartening\" but, in 1999, Cera was cast as Larrabe Hicks in the Canadian children's show ''[[I Was a Sixth Grade Alien]]'', which ran for two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Robert|title=He was a Sixth-Grade Alien: A Q&A with Michael Cera|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2008/10/he-was-a-sixth-grade-alien-a-qa-with-michael-cera.html|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|publisher=[[Wolfgang's Vault]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=October 13, 2008}}</ref> That year, he also appeared in the television films ''[[What Katy Did]]'' and ''[[Switching Goals]]'' starring the [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen twins]].<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\">{{cite web|last1=Hayes|first1=Britt|title=Way Back When: Michael|url=https://screencrush.com/way-back-when-michael-cera/|website=[[ScreenCrush]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Cera then made his theatrical film debut in the science fiction film ''[[Frequency (film)|Frequency]]'' (2000) as the son of [[Noah Emmerich]]'s character.<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\" /> Cera also appeared in the films ''[[Steal This Movie!]]'' and ''Ultimate G's: Zac's Flying Dream'' in 2000, the latter of which featured Cera in his first leading role and was presented in [[IMAX]] theaters.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMAX Theatre To launch Ultimate G's \u2013 Zac's flying dream in 3D|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2005-10-12/news/imax-theatre-to-launch-ultimate-gs-zacs-flying-dream-in-3d-82399/|website=[[The Malta Independent]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=12 October 2005}}</ref><ref name=Biography.com>{{cite web|title=Michael Cera Biography|url=https://www.biography.com/people/michael-cera-566896|website=[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=April 2, 2014}}</ref> Cera appeared in several television films in 2001 including ''[[My Louisiana Sky]]'' and ''[[The Familiar Stranger]]'' and also began voicing Josh Spitz in the animated series ''[[Braceface]]'', continuing to do so until 2004.<ref name=\"ScreenCrush\" /> In 2002, Cera played the young [[Chuck Barris]] (played by [[Sam Rockwell]]) in the [[George Clooney]]-directed film ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aftab|first1=Kaleem|title=Michael Cera: The geek who inherited the earth|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/michael-cera-the-geek-who-inherited-the-earth-8638387.html|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> He provided the voice for Brother Bear&nbsp;\u2013 an [[anthropomorphic]] [[bear]]&nbsp;\u2013 in the 2003 ''[[The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series)|The Berenstain Bears]]'' animated series, which aired for three seasons.<ref name=\"Biography.com\" />\n\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote=\"''Arrested Development'' never felt safe. Even the first season, we did thirteen episodes, and we thought we'd never do a back nine. So I never thought in a million years we'd get to make three seasons. I was happy we got that far. I thought it was really good, and I'm really proud of it. I don't think we made a bad episode.\"|source=\u2014Michael Cera, ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' (2009)<ref name=\"Jones\"/>}}\n\nFollowing a role in the critically panned unaired [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] pilot ''[[The Grubbs]]'' in 2002,<ref>\"Biography Today\", pp.21\u201323</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Cera successfully auditioned for a part in another Fox sitcom, ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', which began airing in November 2003.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The show follows the formerly wealthy and [[Dysfunctional family|dysfunctional]] Bluth family, with Cera playing [[George Michael Bluth]], the teenage son of [[Jason Bateman]]'s character, [[Michael Bluth]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chocano|first1=Carina|title=Arrested Development|url=https://ew.com/article/2003/11/07/arrested-development-3/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 7, 2003}}</ref> After three seasons, Fox canceled the series in 2006 due to low viewership despite critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chalk|first1=Will|title=Arrested Development: The show that can't be cancelled|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39960801/arrested-development-the-show-that-cant-be-cancelled|website=[[Newsbeat]]|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> In 2006, he created and starred in a parody of ''[[Impossible Is Nothing (video r\u00e9sum\u00e9)|Impossible is Nothing]]'', a video r\u00e9sum\u00e9 created by Aleksey Vayner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nAV0sxwx9rY |title=Youtube ''Impossible is the Opposite of Possible'' |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2006-12-20 |accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref> Cera and his ''Arrested Development'' co-star [[Alia Shawkat]] guest starred as a pair of college students in the teen noir drama ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' in the episode \"[[The Rapes of Graff]]\" in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1938062/veronica-mars-facts-trivia/|title=22 Facts Even Marshmallows May Not Know About Veronica Mars|work=[[MTV]]|last=Whitney|first=Alyse|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Along with best friend [[Clark Duke]], Cera wrote and starred in a series of short videos released on their website.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The idea came from Duke, who was enrolled at [[Loyola Marymount University]] and did it for his film school studies.<ref>\"Biography Today\", pp.24</ref> In 2007, they signed a deal with [[CBS Television]] to write, produce, direct, and act in a short-form comedy series entitled ''[[Clark and Michael]]''. The show featured guest stars such as [[David Cross]], [[Andy Richter]] and [[Patton Oswalt]], and was distributed via CBS's internet channel, [[CBS Innertube]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=''Wired'' Staff|title=Sitcom to Bitcom|url=https://www.wired.com/2007/03/snackfilmtv/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael Cera - 001.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Cera in 2007]]\nIn May 2007, Cera appeared in a staged comedy video that shows him being fired from the lead role of the film ''[[Knocked Up]]'' after belittling and arguing with its director [[Judd Apatow]], in a scene that mocks the [[David O. Russell]] blow up on the set of ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]''.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Cera then starred in the Apatow-produced teen comedy ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' alongside [[Jonah Hill]]. Their characters in the film&nbsp;\u2013 two [[virgin]] teenagers about to graduate from high school whose party plans go awry&nbsp;\u2013 were based on its writers [[Seth Rogen]] and [[Evan Goldberg]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patterson|first1=John|title=Comedy's new centre of gravity|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/sep/14/3|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=September 14, 2007}}</ref> ''Superbad'' was released in cinemas in August 2007, topping the US box office for two weeks in a row.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2376&p=.htm |first=Brandon |last=Gray |title='Superbad' Stays on Top |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref> Cera's performance was met with critical acclaim, with ''[[The Atlantic]]'' opining that the film \"belongs to Michael Cera\" for capturing \"teenage sexual abashment as indelibly as he did in the role of George Michael\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Orr|first1=Christopher|title=The Movie Review: 'Superbad'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2007/08/the-movie-review-superbad/69238/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 13, 2007}}</ref> while ''[[The New York Times]]'' felt he was \"excellent\" and [[CNN]] praised Cera and Hill for playing \"off each other beautifully\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dargis|first1=Manohla|title=For Three Virgins, the Path to Sunrise Is Paved With Excess|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/17/movies/17supe.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 17, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Charity|first1=Tom|title=Review: 'Superbad' funniest comedy since 'Borat'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Movies/08/16/review.superbad/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=August 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, Cera hosted an untelevised live staged version of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', not broadcast due to the then-ongoing [[2007 Writers Guild of America Strike]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=Strike or No Strike, for a Select Few, Saturday Night Was Live|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/19/arts/television/19snl.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 19, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Strauss| first =Bob| title =Hollywood heavy still a Brampton beanpole| page =R1| publisher =[[The Globe and Mail]]| date =2007-12-08}}</ref> In his second film of 2007, Cera co-starred in ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' as Paulie Bleeker, a teenager who impregnates his long-time school friend Juno (played by [[Ellen Page]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Venutolo|first1=Anthony|title=Deadpan delivery: Michael Cera takes a romantic turn|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2007/12/deadpan_delivery_michael_cera.html|publisher=[[NJ.com]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 20, 2007}}</ref> For ''Superbad'' and ''Juno'', Cera won Breakthrough Artist in the [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2007]]\nand was included in ''[[Entertainment Weekly|Entertainment Weekly's]]'' 30 Under 30 list in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austin Film Critics Association Announces Top Pic(k)s|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2007-12-21/574157/|website=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Markovitz|first1=Adam|last2=Stransky|first2=Tanner|title=30 Under 30: The Actors|url=https://ew.com/gallery/30-under-30-actors/1|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=February 27, 2008}}</ref> Cera starred alongside [[Kat Dennings]] in the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Nick & Norah's Infinite Playlist]]'' (2008), in which they played two strangers who bond over their shared love of a band and try to find their secret show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=A.O.|authorlink1=A.O. Scott|title=For Muddled Youth, Music to Live By|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/19/arts/television/19snl.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref> He then starred in the comedy ''[[Extreme Movie]]'' (2008), which was composed of vignettes focusing on [[teen sex]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Extreme Movie (2008)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/extreme_movie/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Cera held a recurring role on the comedy series ''[[Childrens Hospital]]'' from 2008 to 2016 as Sal Viscuso, a hospital staffer who is only ever heard through an [[intercom]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Idasetima|first1=Courtney|title=The Cast of 'Juno,' Then and Now|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/cast-juno-1054254|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132013: Varied success and stage debut===\n[[File:Michael Cera as Captain America by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Cera dressed as [[Captain America]] to promote ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic Con]]]]\nCera played a fictionalized version of himself in the independent romantic comedy ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]'' (2009), which followed the fictional relationship between Cera and the film's writer [[Charlyne Yi]], also playing herself. Cera and Yi composed the film's score together.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Catsoulis|first1=Jeannette|title=Out on the Highways in Search of Love, an Endlessly Elusive Quest|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/07/movies/07paper.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Cera then starred opposite [[Jack Black]] in the comedy ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'', set during the [[Stone Age]]. The film, directed by [[Harold Ramis]], was poorly received, although ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine critic Mary Pols felt Cera's performance saved the film from being a \"catastrophe\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pols|first1=Mary|title=Year One: Jokes from the Stone Age|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1905453,00.html|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 18, 2009}}</ref> In his final film of 2009, Cera starred in ''[[Youth in Revolt (film)|Youth in Revolt]]'', an adaptation of the [[Youth in Revolt|eponymous novel]]. He played a shy teenager named Nick Twisp who creates a destructive [[alter ego]], Fran\u00e7ois Dillinger, after becoming smitten with a girl, who is played by [[Portia Doubleday]].<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|last=Male|first=Andrew|title=Sardonic youth|pages=|publisher=Guardian Unlimited|date=2007-09-15|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/sep/15/1|accessdate=2007-09-15 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"twisp\">{{cite news|last=Dimension Films|first=|title=Michael Cera Is Nick Twisp|pages=|publisher=MovieWeb|date=2007-08-15|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/91/21991.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181328/http://www.movieweb.com/news/91/21991.php|archivedate=2007-09-30|accessdate=2007-08-19}}</ref> Cera's first published short story, \"Pinecone\", appeared in ''[[Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern#30|McSweeney's Quarterly]]'' thirtieth issue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Toole|first1=Kristen|title=Fiction Fix: \"Pinecone\" by Michael Cera (plus bonus non-fiction by Matthew Derby!)|url=http://flavorwire.com/16351/fiction-fix-pinecone-by-michael-cera-plus-bonus-non-fiction-by-matthew-derby|website=[[Flavorwire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=April 1, 2009}}</ref> Cera was cast as [[Scott Pilgrim]] in the film adaptation of the [[graphic novel]] series by [[Bryan Lee O'Malley]] after the film's director [[Edgar Wright]] had seen ''Arrested Development'' and needed an actor \"audiences will still follow even when the character is being a bit of an ass\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Nancy|title=Director Edgar Wright, Actor Michael Cera Crack Wise About Scott Pilgrim|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/06/ff_cerawright/all/1/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 22, 2010}}</ref> The film, ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'', follows Pilgrim, a musician who must battle the seven evil exes of his girlfriend [[Ramona Flowers|Ramona]] (played by [[Mary Elizabeth Winstead]]). It was released in cinemas in August 2010, whereupon it became a [[box office bomb]] after just grossing $47.7&nbsp;million against a production budget of $85\u201390&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mercer|first1=Benjamin|title='Scott Pilgrim vs. the World': From Box Office Flop to Cult Classic?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2010/11/scott-pilgrim-vs-the-world-from-box-office-flop-to-cult-classic/66453/|website=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=November 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Scott Pilgrim vs. The World (2010)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=scottpilgrim.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCera made a guest appearance in \"[[The Daughter Also Rises]]\", a 2012 episode of the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as the voice of Nick, a love interest to [[Lisa Simpson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Snierson|first1=Dan|title=Michael Cera to guest on 'The Simpsons'|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/06/02/michael-cera-the-simpsons/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 2, 2011}}</ref> Cera made his theater debut in a production of [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s play ''[[This Is Our Youth]]'' in a two-week run during March 2012 at the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The play also featured his ''Scott Pilgrim'' co-star [[Kieran Culkin]] and [[Tavi Gevinson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hardie|first1=Giles|title=Never grows old|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/never-grows-old-20120307-1ul64.html|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=March 9, 2012}}</ref> A [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production at the [[Cort Theater]] opened in September 2014 and closed in January 2015. ''[[The New York Times]]'' theater critic [[Ben Brantley]] praised Cera for achieving \"something remarkable\": \"the sense of an amorphous being assuming and losing shape in the course of roughly 12 hours\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|authorlink1=Ben Brantley|title=Desperate Fledglings, Flung From the Nest|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/12/theater/this-is-our-youth-stars-michael-cera-kieran-culkin-and-tavi-gevinson.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=September 11, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2012, Cera played a supporting role in the drama ''[[The End of Love]]'' and appeared in the short film ''The Immigrant''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Sam|title=The End Of Love|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-end-of-love-1798175965|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=February 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Megh|title=Check Out Scott Thompson's Short Film 'The Immigrant' with Dave Foley, Michael Cera, Margaret Cho, and Will Forte|url=http://splitsider.com/2014/02/check-out-scott-thompsons-short-film-the-immigrant-with-michael-cera-margaret-cho-and-will-forte/|website=[[Splitsider]]|publisher=[[The Awl]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> ''Arrested Development'' was revived for a fourth season in 2012 by [[Netflix]], with Cera reprising his role as George Michael. Cera worked in the writer's room and served as a consulting producer during its production.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Jason|title=How Jesse Eisenberg Became More Annoyingly Awkward Than Michael Cera|url=http://flavorwire.com/395776/how-jesse-eisenberg-became-more-annoyingly-awkward-than-michael-cera|website=[[Flavorwire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=June 4, 2013|quote=he was actively involved in the show's production, working in the writers' room and credited as a consulting producer}}</ref> The season was released in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Itzkoff|first1=Dave|title=New 'Arrested Development' Season Coming to Netflix on May 26|url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/04/04/new-arrested-development-season-coming-to-netflix-on-may-26/|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=April 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCera collaborated with Chilean filmmaker [[Sebasti\u00e1n Silva (director)|Sebasti\u00e1n Silva]] on two films in 2013&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Magic Magic (2013 film)|Magic Magic]]'' and ''[[Crystal Fairy & the Magical Cactus]]''&nbsp;\u2013 both of which were filmed in Chile and premiered at the [[2013 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Magic Magic Crystal Fairy\">{{cite web|last1=McCarthy|first1=Todd|title=Crystal Fairy & the Magic Cactus and 2012: Sundance Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crystal-fairy-magic-cactus-2012-413569|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=January 18, 2013}}</ref> He spent \"five hours a day learning [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\" for ''Magic Magic''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/movies/juno-star-michael-cera-takes-spanish-second-language|title=\"Juno\" Star Michael Cera Takes Up Spanish as a Second Language| first=Lee| last=Hernandez|publisher=[[Latina magazine]]|date=2011-02-11 |accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref> Cera was featured most prominently in ''Crystal Fairy'', in which he starred as a self-absorbed man travelling Chile with a woman named \"Crystal Fairy\" (played by [[Gaby Hoffmann]]) while bearing a [[cactus]].<ref name=\"Magic Magic Crystal Fairy\" /> Along with [[Reggie Watts]], [[Tim & Eric]], and [[Sarah Silverman]], Cera created the [[web-based]] comedy [[YouTube]] channel [[Jash]] in March 2013, where he has posted short films which he directs and/or stars in.<ref name=\"USA Today Introduces Jash\">{{cite news|last=Matheson|first=Whitney|title=JASH: Your fave comedians launch a YouTube channel|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2013/03/11/jash-youtube/1978521/|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Rolling Stone Magazine Introduces Jash\">{{cite news|last=Danton|first=Eric R.|title=Sarah Silverman, Michael Cera Launch JASH Comedy Channel on YouTube|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/videos/sarah-silverman-michael-cera-launch-jash-comedy-channel-on-youtube-20130311|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]|date=2013-03-11}}</ref> These films include the comedy-drama ''[[Gregory Go Boom]]'' (2013), in which Cera played a [[Hereditary spastic paraplegia|paraplegic]] man, and his directorial debut ''Brazzaville Teen-Ager'' (2013), co-starring [[Charles Grodin]] as his sick father.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travers|first1=Ben|title=Watch: Michael Cera Plays a Paraplegic in New Short Film 'Gregory Go Boom'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/05/watch-michael-cera-plays-a-paraplegic-in-new-short-film-gregory-go-boom-38202/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 24, 2018|date=May 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitney|first1=Erin|title=Watch: Michael Cera Makes His Directorial Debut With Short Film 'Brazzaville Teen-Ager'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/04/watch-michael-cera-makes-his-directorial-debut-with-short-film-brazzaville-teen-ager-39183/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> He played an exaggerated version of himself in the apocalyptic comedy film ''[[This Is the End]]'', which was released in summer of 2013 and featured his ''Superbad'' co-stars Jonah Hill and Seth Rogen.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rob |last=Bricken |title=The new This Is the End redband trailer contains Michael Cera's graphic death. That is all. |url=http://io9.com/the-new-this-is-the-end-redband-trailer-contains-michae-465827952 |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |work=[[io9]] |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=April 6, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FffhZFW6 |archivedate=April 6, 2013 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Throughout 2013, Cera also appeared on ''[[Burning Love (web series)|Burning Love]]'', a web spoof of [[Reality television#Reality competition/game shows|reality dating]] competition shows,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Busis|first1=Hillary|title='Burning Love' returns, with Michael Cera, Colin Hanks, & Nick Kroll|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/24/burning-love-season-2/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> and on an episode of ''[[Drunk History]]'' as [[John Endecott]]. Cera had previously played [[Alexander Hamilton]] in a comedic retelling of [[Burr-Hamilton duel|Hamilton's duel]] with [[Aaron Burr]] on the show's first episode as a web series in 2008 before it was adapted into a television show.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cowen|first1=Trace William|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda Gets Hilariously Sloshed for 'Drunk History' Version of 'Hamilton'|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2016/11/lin-manuel-miranda-drunk-history-hamilton|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present===\nCera appeared in his ''Arrested Development'' co-star [[David Cross]]' 2014 film ''[[Hits (film)|Hits]]'', playing a [[marijuana]] [[drug dealer|dealer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Photos: Michael Cera on the Set of David Cross's ''Hits''|url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/10/michael-cera-on-set-david-cross-hits.html|website=[[Vulture (web site)|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York Media, LLC]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=November 11, 2013}}</ref> He also co-starred alongside [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] and [[Sally Hawkins]] in [[Charlie Kaufman]]'s [[television pilot]] ''How & Why'', which was rejected by [[FX (TV channel)|FX]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=FX Passes on Charlie Kaufman Comedy 'How & Why|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fx-passes-charlie-kaufman-comedy-719856|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=July 21, 2014}}</ref> After a brief, \"menacing\" appearance in the drama ''[[Entertainment (2015 film)|Entertainment]]'' (2015),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dowd|first1=A.A.|title=''Entertainment'' gives Neil Hamburger the alienating star vehicle he deserves|url=https://film.avclub.com/entertainment-gives-neil-hamburger-the-alienating-star-1798185615|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=November 12, 2015}}</ref> Cera appeared in the [[prequel]] to the 2001 comedy film ''[[Wet Hot American Summer]]'', the comedy series ''[[Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp]]'' and in the Christmas musical comedy film ''[[A Very Murray Christmas]]'' as [[Bill Murray]]'s fictional talent agent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Matt|title=10 Things That Save Bill Murray's Netflix Christmas Special|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/news/a40209/bill-murray-christmas-special/|website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> Cera then voiced a [[hot dog]] trying to escape his fate in a supermarket in the animated comedy ''[[Sausage Party]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"Chval\">{{cite web|last1=Chval|first1=Lauren|title=Interview: Michael Cera talks 'Sausage Party,' acting on Broadway and the 'Twin Peaks' reboot|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/redeye-interview-michael-cera-sausage-party-20160809-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018|date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Cera made a cameo on [[Louis C.K.]]'s ''[[Louie (U.S. TV series)|Louie]]'' on [[FX (TV channel)|FX]], in the season five episode \"Sleepover\" alongside [[Glenn Close]], [[John Lithgow]], and [[Matthew Broderick]].<ref>https://tv.avclub.com/louie-sleepover-1798183816</ref>\n\nCera had five film releases in 2017, the first of which was the animated superhero comedy ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'', which featured Cera as the voice of the [[Batman]]'s sidekick [[Robin (character)|Robin]].<ref name=\"Chval\" /> He then played a supporting role as a sleazy [[car salesman]] in the comedy ''[[How to Be a Latin Lover]]'' and co-starred in the comedy-drama ''[[Lemon (2017 film)|Lemon]]'' as an actor with a \"wedge of hair that makes him look like [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin]] crossed with ''[[Eraserhead]]''\", as described by ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' critic [[Owen Gleiberman]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schager|first1=Nick|title='How to Be a Latin Lover' Exclusive Clip: Eugenio Derbez as a Boy Toy Ditched for a Newer Model|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/latin-lover-exclusive-clip-eugenio-derbez-boy-toy-ditched-newer-model-170039255.html|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=April 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gleiberman|first1=Owen|title=Film Review: 'Lemon'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/lemon-review-sundance-1201969953/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Cera starred opposite [[Abbi Jacobson]] in the drama ''[[Person to Person (film)|Person to Person]]'', focusing on the struggles of different people over the course of one day in [[New York City]] and featured Cera and Jacobson as a pair of crime reporters investigating a possible murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Benjamin|title=Person to Person review \u2013 Broad City star underused in meandering ensemble indie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/20/person-to-person-review-broad-city-star-abbi-jacobson-michael-cera|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In his final film of the year, [[Aaron Sorkin]]'s crime drama ''[[Molly's Game]]'', Cera played a celebrity known only as Player X who participates in a high-stakes underground poker empire run by [[Molly Bloom (author)|Molly Bloom]] (played by [[Jessica Chastain]]). Cera's fictional character in the film was a [[composite character]] of real-life celebrity poker players [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Tobey Maguire]] and [[Ben Affleck]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Hilary|title='Molly's Game' Team Talks Making Timely Tale of Female Empowerment|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jessica-chastain-aaron-sorkins-mollys-game-molly-bloom-sexual-misconduct-claims-michael-cera-player-1070323|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA \"giant fan\" of director [[David Lynch]],<ref name=\"Chval\" /> Cera made a guest appearance in the [[Twin Peaks (season 3)|2017 revival]] of Lynch and [[Mark Frost]]'s television show ''[[Twin Peaks]]'' in the show's fourth episode, as Wally \"Brando\" Brennan, the son of Deputy Sheriff [[List of Twin Peaks characters#Andy Brennan|Andy Brennan]] and [[Lucy Moran|Lucy Brennan]].<ref name=\"WallyBrando\">{{cite web|last1=Nguyen|first1=Hanh|title='Twin Peaks' MVP Wally Brando: 5 Reasons Michael Cera's Brilliant Cameo Is Just What the Show Needed|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/05/twin-peaks-wally-brando-michael-sera-marlon-brando-wild-one-1201834109/|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref> The appearance contained several references to the work of actor [[Marlon Brando]] as Wally shares the same birthday and is nicknamed after Brando.<ref name=\"WallyBrando\" />\n\nCera returned to the stage in March 2018, starring in a second Kenneth Lonergan production, ''[[Lobby Hero]]'', at the [[Helen Hayes Theatre]] on Broadway. The play also stars [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]], [[Brian Tyree Henry]] and [[Bel Powley]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vine|first1=Hannah|title=Michael Cera, Chris Evans, and the Cast of ''Lobby Hero'' Meet the Press|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/michael-cera-chris-evans-and-the-cast-of-lobby-hero-meet-the-press|website=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Cera and Henry are both nominated for [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]] at the [[72nd Tony Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Libbey|first1=Peter|title=Tony Awards 2018: Full List of Nominations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/01/theater/tony-awards-nominees-list.html|accessdate=May 22, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCera appeared onstage again in October 2018, starring in the third Kenneth Lonergan production, this time a revival of ''[[The Waverly Gallery]]'' at the [[John Golden Theatre]] on Broadway. The play also starred [[Elaine May]], [[Lucas Hedges]], and [[Joan Allen]].<ref>https://www.broadway.com/shows/waverly-gallery/</ref>\n\nCera co-starred in the 2018 drama ''[[Gloria Bell]]'', with [[Julianne Moore]] as the title character.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=John Turturro and Newcomer Caren Pistorius Join Julianne Moore in 'Gloria' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/john-turturro-caren-pistorious-gloria-julianna-more-1202617002/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=February 26, 2018|date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> Cera's upcoming projects include the animated comedy ''[[Blazing Samurai]]'' about a dog who wishes to become a samurai.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title='Blazing Samurai' Lands A-List Voice Talent Led By Samuel L. Jackson|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/blazing-samurai-animated-feature-samuel-l-jackson-mel-brooks-george-takei-1201605395/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=November 3, 2015}}</ref> Cera returned to his role as George Michael in the fifth season of ''[[Arrested Development (season 5)|Arrested Development]]'' in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elise Sandberg|first1=Bryn|title='Arrested Development' Officially Renewed for Season 5 at Netflix|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/arrested-development-officially-renewed-season-5-at-netflix-1004529|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 12, 2018|date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[File:Michael Cera 2011.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Cera performing in 2011]]\nIn 2010 Cera contributed mandolin and backing vocals to the [[Weezer]] song \"Hang On\" from their album ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]''.<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web|last=Dorof|first=Jakob|title=Weezer \u2013 Hurley|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/weezer-hurley/2247|work=Slantmagazine|accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref>\nCera has also established himself as the touring bass player in [[Mister Heavenly]], an indie rock band originating in the American northwest,<ref>{{cite web|author=Erik Ziedses des Plantes |url=http://www.prefixmag.com/news/michael-cera-is-apparently-mister-heavenlys-bassis/46626/ |title=Michael Cera Is Apparently Mister Heavenly's Bassist |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2010-12-07}}</ref> and is a member of the band [[The Long Goodbye (band)|The Long Goodbye]], along with [[Clark Duke]].<ref name=\"spin-1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.spin.com/2007/08/michael-ceras-long-goodbye/ | title=Michael Cera's Long Goodbye | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | date=August 22, 2007 | accessdate=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Cera also played bass and sang back up during songs in both ''Scott Pilgrim vs. the World'' and ''Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist''. He released his full-length debut album ''[[True That]]'' on August 8, 2014, through his official [[Bandcamp]] page.<ref name=\"p4k-album\">{{cite web | url=https://pitchfork.com/news/56299-michael-cera-released-a-surprise-album-last-night/ | title=Michael Cera Released a Surprise Album Last Night | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Gordon, Jeremy}}</ref><ref name=\"teleg\">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11031409/Michael-Cera-releases-album-online.html | title=Michael Cera releases album online | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Travis, Ben}}</ref> The album features 19 original tracks, a cover of [[Roderick Falconer]]'s \"Play It Again\" as well as a cover of [[Blaze Foley]]'s \"Clay Pigeons.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/08/13/stream-michael-cera-album/ | title=Michael Cera Quietly Releases an Album That You Can Stream | publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=August 13, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2014 | author=Todd Olmstead}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Canadian musician [[Alden Penner]] released \"Meditate\", a track from his upcoming [[Extended Play|EP]] ''Canada in Space'', which features Cera. Penner subsequently announced that the EP would be released on 29 June 2015 on [[City Slang]] records, as well as a European tour of the UK, Netherlands, France, and Germany, which featured Cera as both co-headliner and member of Penner's backing band.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Camp|first1=Zoe|title=The Unicorns' Alden Penner Teams With Michael Cera for New EP and Tour|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/59411-the-unicorns-alden-penner-teams-with-michael-cera-for-new-ep-and-tour/|website=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc.|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=music|first1=Guardian|title=Michael Cera to tour with the Unicorns' Alden Penner|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/apr/28/michael-cera-to-tour-with-the-unicorns-alden-penner|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd.|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> The song \"Best I Can\" from the film ''[[Dina (film)|Dina]]'', written and performed by Cera and featuring [[Sharon Van Etten]], was unsuccessfully nominated for Best Song In A Documentary at the 2017 Critics' Choice Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/ |title=Documentary Awards - Critics' Choice AwardsCritics' Choice Awards |publisher=Criticschoice.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-29 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20171112085340/http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/ |archive-date=2017-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2000 || ''[[Frequency (film)|Frequency]]'' || Gordy Hersch Jr. (Age 10) ||\n|-\n| ''[[Steal This Movie!]]'' || [[Abbie Hoffman|America Hoffman]] (Age 7\u20138) ||\n|-\n| ''Ultimate G's: Zac's Flying Dream'' || Young Zac ||\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'' || [[Chuck Barris]] (Age 8\u201311) ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007 || ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' || Evan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'' ||Paulie Bleeker ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008 || ''[[Extreme Movie]]'' || Fred ||\n|-\n| ''[[Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist]]'' || Nick O'Leary ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2009 || ''[[Paper Heart (film)|Paper Heart]]'' || Himself ||\n|-\n| ''[[Year One (film)|Year One]]'' || Oh ||\n|-\n| ''[[Youth in Revolt (film)|Youth in Revolt]]'' || Nick Twisp / Fran\u00e7ois Dillinger ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010 || ''Scott Pilgrim vs. the Animation'' || [[Scott Pilgrim]] (voice) || [[Short film]]\n|-\n| ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' || Scott Pilgrim ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012 || ''[[The End of Love]] || Michael ||\n|-\n| ''The Immigrant'' || Michael || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2013 || ''[[Crystal Fairy & the Magical Cactus]]'' || Jamie ||\n|-\n| ''[[Magic Magic (2013 film)|Magic Magic]] || Brink || Also executive producer\n|-\n| ''Brazzaville Teen-Ager'' || Gunther || Short film; also director and writer\n|-\n| ''Failure'' || Man || S